<HEADLINE>Woman `sent to Coventry' after affair, tribunal told</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913537</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A WOMAN was ``sent to Coventry'' when she returned to work at a data-processing
plant after her affair with the boss ended, an industrial tribunal heard
yesterday.
Mrs Jenny McMillan, 25, from Ardrossan, was the subject of gossip and rumours
because of her affair with Mr Mike Dale, Saztec Europe's deputy general manager
at the time, the Glasgow tribunal was told.
The affair ended, then Mrs McMillan, a senior coding supervisor, went on sick
leave, suffering from stress after her grandmother's death. On her return, she
claimed, she was effectively demoted. She had no desk or office, no personal
belongings and she faced a drop in salary. She resigned and claimed
constructive dismissal.
Mrs June Watson, a worker at the company, said that on Mrs McMillan's first day
back she was put in a room to work alone, given menial tasks and ``sent to
Coventry''. Mrs Watson said: ``She looked really down. She said she was
terrible. She didn't have an office, she didn't have a desk, she didn't have
any personal belongings.''
Mrs Joanna Milligan, a project worker at the plant, said that Mrs McMillan was
given the task of assisting her on a very important project on her return to
work. She was being given a chance to be in on a new job from square one. She
said Mrs McMillan was still senior coding supervisor, but agreed that her
duties that day were not consistent with that title.
Mrs Milligan told the tribunal: ``Jenny didn't seem to mind that day where she
worked. She made the comment that she didn't care what people thought, she was
only here for the money.''
However, she agreed that Mrs McMillan, who had been responsible for supervising
up to 49 workers, was in charge of no-one on the day she came back.
The tribunal heard earlier that Mr Dale, a married father of two from Yateley,
Hampshire, who is now vice-president and general manager, also had an affair
with another employee, former production manager-designate Ms Ruth Donnachie,
before his relationship with Mrs McMillan.
Ms Donnachie said that she also ended up losing her job after the affair ended.
She said that, when she told Mr Dale she was seeing someone else, he called her
an ``evil bitch''.
Ms Donnachie said that the next week her sister was sacked as personnel manager
and she herself was made redundant in May last year.
Mr Dale told the tribunal at an earlier hearing that he still missed Ms
Donnachie, and agreed his involvement with the two employees had been a mistake.
He said he had nothing to do with Mrs McMillan's departure. The hearing
continues today.
</TEXT>
