<HEADLINE>Tanks and heavy artillery to bolster Bosnia force</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEPHEN McGREGOR Parliamentary Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913538</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE biggest movement of British troops since the Gulf war was announced to the
Commons yesterday by Defence Secretary Michael Portillo.
The British contribution to the Bosnian peace implementation force, expected to
be on the move before Christmas, will be a total of 13,000 troops, although no
Scottish regiments will be involved. They will include signallers, engineers,
medical teams and logistic troops, and will be backed up by 7500 vehicles and
7000 tonnes of ammunition. There will be Challenger tanks, AS90 heavy artillery
and armed helicopters.
Mr Portillo warned in a statement to the House: ``Of course, they will seek to
use persuasion to implement the peace, and in the British Army even the most
junior ranks have experience of making highly sensitive judgements on the spot.
But when they need to take robust action they will be equipped and authorised
to do so.''
The Defence Secretary's statement stemmed from the expectation that the Bosnian
peace agreement will be signed in Paris tomorrow. Within a few days, Nato will
take over full military responsibility from the UN and deploy forces to
implement the agreement.
Mr Portillo said: ``Our mission is to oversee the separation of the warring
factions and the return to barracks of their soldiers, and to provide the
security necessary for Bosnia and Herzegovina to establish national
institutions and hold free elections.
``Nato's mission is rightly limited in scope. It is also limited in duration -
to 12 months.''
Britain would supply a brigade and a divisional headquarters to command one of
the three military sectors and, in addition, Britain had the leading role in
commanding Nato's Rapid Reaction Corps - a British-led, multinational Nato
force. Britain also would provide most of the field headquarters controlling
the whole operation.''
For Labour, Defence spokesman Dr David Clark welcomed the statement. He said:
``Our experience in Northern Ireland will serve us well when we try to broker
peace and ensure it is continued between three different nations. We wish our
troops who will serve in the new mission every success and we trust every one
of them will return home safely.''
He added: ``We welcome the strengthening of the rules of engagement and we have
argued all along that our troops in this situation should not be
disadvantaged.''
For the Liberal Democrats, Mr Menzies Campbell voiced support for the operation
and confidence that British forces would ``fulfil their responsibilities with
distinction and with professionalism''.
Mr Campbell expressed the hope that the 12-month timescale referred to by Mr
Portillo was ``a target and not a deadline, and that if the peace agreement is
on course for successful implementation, there will be no automatic withdrawal
at the expiry of 12 months''.
The Defence Secretary insisted that the mission was ``well achievable within
the 12-month period''.
</TEXT>
