<HEADLINE>Pantomime   Sleeping Beauty, Brunton Hall, Musselburgh</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Mary Brennan</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974913539</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BRUNTON'S theatre space is currently under renovation, but as my chum Ofpants
is wont to say: ``Two planks and a passion gives you theatah. One plank missing
gives you panto!'' Quite. And panto is what you get if you venture upstairs to
Brunton's Main Hall, valiantly disguised with gauzy draperies and coloured
lights.
Here, director Robin Peoples and his team do battle with the twin demons of
boomy acoustics and level seating by setting the action on steeply stepped
rostra which are liberally scattered with microphones.
So much good effort has gone into overcoming the limitations of this space - a
change of scenery gets slotted in like some huge Pollok's toy theatre,
Carabosse's chariot actually comes among us, much to the delighted fright of
the young audience - that it's a shame the script itself wasn't a bit fresher.
Raymond Ross's Sleeping Beauty follows close on the heels - and the storylines
- of the version recently featuring Les Dennis as Lester the Jester.
Not necessarily cause for an automatic thumbs down - panto is, after all, a
retelling of the familiar - but the morning I saw it, I was struck by how
sparse some of the material was. I suppose I had expected more of a show from
Russel Hunter's dame - is this, maybe, reserved for evening/more adult
audiences? And remembering how cleverly bumbling Kevin MacLeod was, in last
year's panto, I felt he was disappointingly under used as Norval the witch's
numpty henchman.
Still, Paul Reilly's Lester (yes, a jester) kept the audience cheerfully on the
ball, Marjory Hogarth's Carabosse achieved a high Eek! factor, while Diane
Sobolewska brought a nice touch of the hoyden to the princess - and the best
bit of stage magic.......she doubled as the Good Fairy. Our official panto
watchdog passed it on points - but felt the cast deserved better material.
</TEXT>
