<HEADLINE>Blast from the past</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913540</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FOUR Scots fishermen yesterday watched a Royal Navy bomb squad blow up 500lbs
of TNT that had shared their trawler with them for seven days. They had thought
it was a drum of paint.
Coastguards said the explosives, trawled up off the island of Fetlar by the
Kirkcaldy-registered Integrity III, were the central core of a Second World War
mine. They warned fishermen to report immediately anything ``unidentified or
strange'' found in their nets.
The Integrity III was loading ice at a Lerwick pier on Monday, within 500 yards
of two crowded shopping centres, when a shore worker alerted her skipper Kelvin
MacGregor to the danger.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
