<HEADLINE>Winning ways to boost exports</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Joan Grady</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Advertising Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974913541</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Joan Grady reports on a businesscompetition which has helpedfive companies to
expand
IN April this year five Glasgow-based companies each received #20,000 to
increase their export potential and create jobs. Since then, those companies
have gone on to generate #1,000,000 in additional export sales and open up new
markets all over the world.
This was the result of the first International Executive Scheme, the biggest
business-related competition in the country, run by the Glasgow Development
Agency. It is now ready to launch another round of awards, designed to
encourage small and medium-sized companies in Glasgow to think about expanding
into a more global market.
``Glasgow Development Agency is committed to supporting export growth under its
objective of improving the performance of existing businesses,'' said GDA chief
executive Stuart Gulliver. ``Glasgow's companies export, on average, at half
the rate of companies across Scotland and the UK.
``The International Executive Scheme has been developed to offer support for
those companies showing a commitment to increasing export sales. It has already
proved to be a tremendous success.''
Companies entering the competition must be Glasgow-based and involved in export
business. They must demonstrate that with outside help, they can introduce
changes to improve export potential. Each successful company will receive
#20,000 over two years as a contribution to the cost of recruiting a new export
executive.
GDA offers back-up in drawing up job descriptions and getting through the
recruitment process. It will help the winning company draw up an export action
plan and arrange a ``health check'' of export activities by an experienced
export consultant.
Aftercare is provided through informal meetings of the winning companies during
which they can exchange information, ideas and advice. There are also training
days on export-related topics such as credit control and distribution.
A recent survey of Glasgow companies showed that 29% of exporters based their
businesses on unsolicited orders from overseas. GDA help such companies
increase proactive exporting and improve sales potential.
In 1992, California Cake &amp; Cookie Limited sold all its products in the UK
market. It had a steady turnover of #1.8m and a healthy number of bluechip
clients, including British Airways, Sainsbury and Tesco.
``We had a popular range of products, we were maintaining our position in the
marketplace and the scene was set for something to happen,'' said executive
chairman Tom Lambie. ``And it did - at a trade exbibition in England.''
The company was approached by Joanne Alexander Sefre, a former British Bakeries
export manger who was at the time looking for quality British cake products
which could be sold on the Continent.
Sefre produced a business plan outlining her proposals to market a range of the
Company's products in France, and California Cake &amp; Cookie saw the chance to
expand its market and boost its sales.
``It was evident that Joanne had the necessary knowledge and experience of
working in this market sector,'' said Lambie. ``Here was an opportunity to
explore the potential of increasing sales at a time when the home market was as
difficult as ever.'' Sefre's knowledge of languages and wide range of contacts
in the Eurpean food retail and wholesale trade made her the ideal agent for the
company. The award from GDA provided the necessary cash flow to produce
labelling and point of sale materials in languages other than English and help
offset Sefre's cost.
Exports now account for 2.5% of total sales, adding to and not replacing the
already existing home sales. French supermarket chain Monoprix, which has more
than 300 retail outlets, placed a #20,000 promotional order, giving California
Cake &amp; Cookie a listing as one of its suppliers.
Tom Lambie was delighted with the result, and recognises the enormous efforts
put in by the whole team and the GDA's valuable contribution. ``What has been
achieved over the last two years has been done through careful planning, hard
work and targeted assistance from the Glasgow Development Agency,'' he said.
``The #20,000 was a financial leg-up which helped short-cut a lot of work.
A key area of GDA strategy is to improve the relatively low levels of Glasgow's
exporting activities. 50 companies of all shapes and sizes entered the first
year of the International Executive Scheme, and the GDA hopes to elicit the
same response this time around.
For further information of the International Executive Scheme, contact Irene
Mitton at the Glasgow Development Agency on 0141 242 8227
</TEXT>
