<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Brake put on patent</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913542</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SCOTTISH teenager's hopes of selling an invention worldwide is in jeopardy
after he missed the deadline for the international patent because of lack of
money.
Martin Johnstone, 18, of Acres Road, Kingussie, Inverness-shire, fears big
manufacturers will steal his idea and market the prototype car cycle rack.
The device is powered directly from a vehicle's cigarette lighter and allows it
to show rear light signals clearly even when it is carrying luggage such as
bicycles.
Martin has won several national awards and appeared on the TV programme Eureka.
His father, Mark, has spent more than #20,000 showing the device at exhibitions.
However, Mr Johnstone, 45, could not yesterday raise the #4600 needed to
protect a world-wide patent application lodged with Glasgow's Murgitroyds. ``I
just simply do have anymore money left to plough into this project. We need a
backer if we are going to get this project off the ground but I am losing hope
now.''
He added: ``We need further capital of around #30,000 to manufacture the first
1000 units from our Kingussie workshops. It will be an absolute tragedy if
Martin's idea is stolen by someone else.''
He estimates that Tail-lit, as Martin calls it, would retail at around #65 and
could reach a potential market of 20,000 each year, based on enquiries to trade
manufacturers.
The idea for the project came when father and son were travelling down the A9
and got stuck behind a vehicle which was dangerously laden with bicycles
obscuring its brake lights.
At the time Martin was looking for ideas for a technical project at school and
he took up the challenge.
His head teacher at Kingussie High School, Mr Brian Dziennick, helped out and
the invention was soon thrust into the limelight of national television.
</TEXT>
