<HEADLINE>Fewer fail drink-drive breath tests</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913543</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND'S Roads Minister last night welcomed a drop in the percentage of
drivers who failed or refused the breath test, over the first 18 days of the
country's latest drink-drive campaign, compared to last year's figures.
Lord James Douglas-Hamilton, however, said the level of positive tests was
still much too high.
``The police are operating a high level of breath testing this year and people
who drink and drive run a very high risk of being caught.
``Motorists must continue to heed the message that drinking and driving wrecks
lives.''
According to the latest figures released by the Association of Chief Police
Officers in Scotland the number tested from November 24 to December 11 was
30,290 as against 20,148 for the same period last year.
However, the proportion of people who failed or refused the breath test was
only 1.8%, compared with 2.6% last year.
</TEXT>
