<DOCNO>GH951213-000007</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000007</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>City of scars turns its back on failure</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Michael Fry</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974913544</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HOW can anyone be a communist in 1995? The question is all the harder to answer
in Berlin whence, before long, one of the world's most successful capitalist
economies will be governed.
Berlin still bears the scars of its history, but the plastic surgery is radical
and rapid. By the time the federal government shifts from Bonn at the end of
the decade, this will be a dramatic post-modern metropolis, a portent of the
twenty-first century and, with its four million citizens, among the largest
cities in Europe. Perhaps people will come to admire it as they did the London
of Sir Christopher Wren or the Paris of Baron Haussman.
For the time being, East Berlin is actually more chic than West Berlin. The
west was always a rather soulless exemplar of post-war Germany, a sea of
concrete rendered interesting only by the barbed wire round it. The east,
despite or because of its desperate dilapidation and its bolder brutalism, is
the more evocative place.
It houses what remains - and, restored out of the ruins, it is quite a lot - of
the Berlin of the eighteenth-century, a gracious, enlightened city. It still
has street after street of single-ends, just like Glaswegian tenements.
The old Jewish quarter looks much as it must have done on the day its hapless
denizens were deported en masse in 1941; amazingly, its golden-domed synagogue
has survived. The dingy greyness by day, the dim yellow light by night, have
you ready to run into George Smiley at any time.
All this makes it a huge adventure playground for the western avant-garde.
Oviform shopping centre, elliptical skyscrapers, rise from the no man's land
where the Wall once ran, obliterating the last few lumps of concrete which mark
the entrance to Adolf Hitler's bunker. Meanwhile, all the most fashionable
restaurants, all the most swinging night-spots, all the most frenetic discos
are to be found in the mean streets of East Berlin.
There is another analogy with Glasgow, with the Glasgow of the 1980s, a city
consciously turning its back on its failures, embracing and being embraced by
the global economy. A mere change of heart does not, of course, suffice to
solve all the long-term problems. Still, it is a good start. One astounding
fact about Berlin is that unemployment in the eastern half is now lower than in
the western half.
Perhaps that is why some genuine working-class districts of East Berlin are, if
anything, dominated by the party of the right and senior partner in the federal
government, the Christian Democrats. But then there were not that many genuine
working-class districts in East Berlin.
It may have been the capital of a proletarian state, but it was itself a city
of the privileged, of an elite gathered round the wellsprings of power in a
highly centralised system. As the system began to collapse and protests took to
the streets down in industrial Saxony - which does have a genuine working class
- the first slogan they put on their banners was ``Away with privilege. We are
the people''.
The privileged, the functionaries of every kind in their communist apparatus,
naturally resent losing their privileges, though for most this means no more
than finding something to fill their time in retirement on an adequate, though
by no means princely, pension. Like nearly all East Germans, they will have
swopped their stinking, chugging Trabi for at least a Volkswagen, if they are
lucky, or extravagant, perhaps for a BMW. Otherwise, many nurse a stubborn
refusal to concede that Germany is a better place since 1990.
This is the basic reason why the old East German Communist Party, renamed the
Party of Democratic Socialism, has been able to survive, even to flourish to
some extent.
It has comfortably fulfilled the qualifications for representation of the
Bundestag. In some future hung Bundestag, it might even exert a decisive
influence, though its attitude towards the other parties leans to the sour. At
the local level, it still has more members than all of them together in united
Berlin.
Since those others have come out of the West Germany tradition, where the
duties of membership do not go far beyond giving money, memories of
revolutionary militancy serve the communists well. At least they will, as their
rivals will not, tramp around knocking on doors, canvassing for their
candidates and encouraging people to join them. They have no reason to be
dissatisfied with the results. Their vote has been rising and they now provide
mayors for three of Berlin's 22 boroughs.
In its internal affairs, too, the party has become positively dynamic, with
factions ranging from the Stalinist to the libertarian. As with the British
Conservatives, much of the leadership's time is taken up with suppressing, or
at least controlling, these freelance activities. But at least the Tories are
in power, whereas the East German communists will by definition never hold
power again.
So why be a communist? A visitor gets the impression that it is almost a matter
of sentiment rather than of any serious political purpose. Once the new Berlin
arises, it will have beneath its glittering futuristic facade a heritage of
extraordinary richness too, including evidences of what people elsewhere do not
care to think much about, the capacity of states for totalitarianism and
terror. Berlin has survived them.
If some of its people still vote communist just because they have been
consigned to the dustbin of history, the rest of us may look on with equanimity.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
