<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Psychiatrist tells court of accused's watching his `dark side' carry out attack Classroom `killer mentally ill'</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913545</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE killer of schoolgirl Nikki Conroy was yesterday described as ``very
seriously mentally ill'' by a prosecution psychiatrist who has questioned him
more than 20 times since the classroom attack.
Dr Lawrence Naismith said that after initially being unable to remember
anything about the incident at Hall Garth school, Middlesbrough, Cleveland,
Stephen Wilkinson eventually gave a graphic account of how he witnessed it in
an out-of-body experience.
Wilkinson, 31, explained how his ``dark side'' alter ego, Wilson Jinks, left
his home in his body and he felt compelled to go with him. He explained how he
watched Wilson Jinks carrying out the attack in the classroom and it was only
after two teachers burst in and overpowered the killer that he returned to his
own body, realised he had not been dreaming and that it was he who was being
held down on the floor.
Dr Naismith told Leeds Crown Court his conclusion was that Wilkinson was ``very
seriously mentally ill'' at the time of the attack on March 28 last year.
He was suffering from paranoid psychosis or he would be equally happy to call
it paranoid schizophrenia.
Twelve-year-old Nikki of Ridley Avenue, Middlesbrough, was stabbed after
Wilkinson stormed into the maths lesson and forced the teacher to leave at
gunpoint.
He also plunged knives into Michelle Reeve, 13, and Emma Winter, 12, but they
recovered from their wounds while Nikki died within minutes. One knife thrust
went right through her body.
Wilkinson, of Caversham Road, Middlesbrough, a former pupil at the school when
it was called Boynton Secondary, has denied murdering Nikki but admitted
manslaughter on the grounds of diminished responsibility. He has also pled
guilty to the attempted murder of Michelle and Emma.
The outrage at Hall Garth was chillingly foretold in a short story, The Tears
Shall Drown the Wind, written by Wilkinson, the court heard.
In the story he said: ``If I had been stronger I would have taken my knife to
these insolent wretches. I would have marched into the classroom and silenced
their tongues forever.''
Wilkinson told Dr Naismith that he fantasised about killing people, although he
denied his violent thoughts involved children.
``I imagine the deaths of young maidens slain in a room choked with desks,'' he
wrote.
He was also interested in the occult, telling a psychiatrist: ``I'm just
satisfied by the dark side of human nature.''
Wilkinson told police that on the night before Nikki's death he was very
depressed and had been drinking whisky and thinking about suicide. After that,
he said there was a ``void'' in his mind until he was arrested.
The jury heard that Wilkinson, who had never had a girlfriend or a sexual
relationship, wanted to commit suicide in public. He told police: ``I wanted to
communicate my despair to the people of Middlesbrough. I wanted them to see my
suffering.''
Referring to Wilkinson's account of the alter ego Wilson Jinks character,
carrying out the killing, the psychiatrist said: ``I cannot recall anything
like this in my experience.''
Wilkinson told him that after he and Wilson Jinks left the house they headed
towards Acklam cemetery. He described walking beside his alter ego all the way
to the classroom and putting a gun to a pupil's head.
Dr Naismith said Wilkinson was describing ``a kind of dissociated process - a
sort of dissociated state in which he perceived himself to be outside his own
body.''
Such concepts had long been associated with schizophrenia, depression and
anxiety. It has also been linked with alcoholism and being in a highly-charged
emotional state.
Asked by David Robson QC, prosecuting, what effect this would have had on his
state of mind at the time of the incident, he replied: ``I would take the view
this disorder did substantially diminish his responsibility.''
The trial continues.
</TEXT>
