<HEADLINE>It's the Euro, to coin a phrase</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MURRAY RITCHIE European Editor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913546</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Brussels
EUROPE'S planned single currency probably will be called the ``Euro'' when EU
leaders gather later this week for the Madrid summit.
The name is top of the list of possibilities, not because it is popular but
because no-one has been able to come up with a better suggestion.
Chancellor Kenneth Clarke earlier this year suggested names including the
crown, florin and shilling. However, the British voice is unlikely to carry
much weight in the debate because of the Government's right to opt out of the
single currency if it so wishes.
Most recently, the Italians mischievously suggested the Franco but this was
vetoed by the Spanish socialist Prime Minister, Felipe Gonzalez, who will chair
the talks.
Only France is left still calling for the new money to be called the Ecu, after
the old French coin.
Other names include the mark, which is supported by the Germans and the Finns
(whose currency is the markke) but it is not favoured by other nations, fearful
of German economic domination.
British officials yesterday suggested the Euro might be adopted along with a
suffix for each country to denote existing national currencies - like the
Europound or the Eurofranc. That way, public doubts about the new money could
be assuaged.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951213-000010</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000010</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Rich blend of country and music</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Michael Tumelty</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974913547</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AMONG a plethora of festive concerts being staged around now, there is one that
merits special attention. Next Sunday, at Killearn Kirk in Stirlingshire, the
Scottish Bach Consort will give a concert entitled A Baroque Christmas that
will fulfil a triple ambition of the small orchestra's leader and founder, John
Doig.
Doig, a well-known violinist on the Scottish music scene, is the leader of the
Orchestra of Scottish Opera and a former co-leader of the Scottish Chamber
Orchestra. Last year, he founded the Scottish Bach Consort out of a number of
convictions.
Principal among these was the awareness that, despite the touring programmes of
orchestras and groups such as the Scottish Chamber Orchestra and the BT
Scottish Ensemble, there are still vast areas of Scotland - and not in the
hinterland either - which are seldom, if ever, visited by professional musical
ensembles.
``Basically, I am talking about taking music into rural areas - and I mean
rural - where there are villages with beautiful churches and wonderful
acoustics that are just not visited at all,'' said Doig. The violinist, himself
a resident of Killearn, had realised some years back that villages such as his
own contain a large number of concert-goers who have to travel to one of the
key centres in the central belt for their regular musical fix.
And thus was the idea born of a small orchestra of professional musicians,
which would not operate in the main centres, or compete with the existing major
organisations, but which would specialise in taking music into rural areas.
But that was only part of Doig's ambition. Additionally, he was aware of the
large number of choral societies that operate in these areas. The practice is,
generally, that when these societies stage a large-scale choral work requiring
orchestral resources, an ad hoc orchestra is recruited for the occasion.
Doig's vision was that the Scottish Bach Consort, formed around a tight core of
12 string players and harpsichord, would be available, as an integrated unit
capable of expansion when required, to service the needs of rural choral
societies ``providing a professional orchestra of a very high standard, and at
good rates''.
Of some 14 concerts in its first year of operation, a number of these have
involved local choral societies, such as Stirling's Rosenethe Singers,
Killearn's own Strathendrick Singers, and Crieff Choral Society.
And Doig's experience of the first year of the Scottish Bach Consort has only
firmed his conviction about a need to be met. ``If you marry the music to the
acoustic of these fine buildings and churches, and if you use the locality and
get it right, there are rewards.''
THE rewards, he said, are the numbers in the audiences. ``Every concert we do
is sold out; the problem of declining audiences that we hear about all the time
is just not true in rural areas. In fact, the reverse is true; there's an
upward move.'' And the rewards also include the group's first sponsor,
Independent Pension Trustees plc, like the Consort, based in Killearn and
specialising in services to rural areas.
However, it is the third aspect of Doig's ambition for the Consort - and the
one most personal to him - that brings the particular interest to his group's
concert next Sunday. Doig's own experience as a young musician on the edge of
the profession - which he describes as ``very fortunate'' - convinced him the
only way to learn the ropes of playing in an orchestra was not by being
closeted in the practice room of an academy, but by sitting beside seasoned
professionals in an orchestra.
By the age of 17, Helensburgh-born Doig was playing in the BBC Symphony
Orchestra in London. ``It proved to me that the younger you can get into the
profession the better; not with big-time ideas, but just to learn your craft on
the shop floor.''
In the Scottish Bach Consort, then, Doig runs what he describes as ``loosely, a
sort of apprenticeship scheme, where young talented musicians play beside the
pros''. And next Sunday, four of them get the chance to step into the limelight
in a performance of Vivaldi's Four Seasons.
The Seasons is probably the best known work in the entire repertoire. While it
usually features a single violin soloist, it is, in fact, comprised of four
separate violin concertos. Four young violinists who have all played in the
Consort - Elaine Clark, Alison Dixon, Jane Sidebottom, and Louise Webster -
will share the solo parts in one concerto each.
All four are already establishing a pedigree. Aberdeen-born Clark, aged 22, is
a competition prize-winner, and now studies abroad. Alison Dixon, 21, Jane
Sidebottom and Louise Webster, both 20, have, between them, appeared in almost
all of the professional Scottish orchestras.
``Bringing the four of them to the front as soloists is a new venture for us,''
said Doig. ``This is their night.''
q.Scottish Bach Consort: Killearn Kirk, Sunday, 8pm
Michael Tumelty explains how a violinist's ambition took classical music to
rural Scotland
</TEXT>
