<HEADLINE>Excellent returns as demand exceeds supply Deer industry eager for new recruits</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBERT ROSS, Farming Editor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974913548</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MAINSTREAM livestock producers who may be beset with worries about sheep quotas
or cattle premiums should consider adapting their skills to deer farming, it
was suggested yesterday.
The British Deer Farmers' Association is anxious to win more converts to the
industry as, for the first time, demand for farmed venison exceeds supply. The
association has 180 members, many of whom are having to turn away business.
``That is a real problem for the industry - we could become vulnerable,'' said
Hugh Fullerton-Smith, association chairman, at a deer farm open day at Barony
College near Dumfries.
More than 60 people attended the event which included a tour of the college's
own deer unit.
Most members of the association are former sheep or cattle farmers and part of
its strategy is to persuade them that deer can be integrated into their other
farming operations.
Dr John Fletcher of Reediehill Deer Farm, Auchtermuchty, who has been farming
them for 25 years, reassured visitors at the open day that they would not be
venturing into the unknown. A lot was known about the care of red deer, he
said. The Moredun Institute in Edinburgh was a world centre of expertise on
their health.
With the creation of Scottish Farm Venision as a marketing co-op there was an
efficient arrangement for selling produce, he added.
Dr Fletcher cautioned, however, against thinking: ``Here is some rough land at
the top of the hill, I will put some deer on it.'' A more likely prospect, he
suggested, was the conversion of a dairy farm which could produce good quality
grass. ``The reason deer live at the top of the hill in the Highlands is that
if they come down people shoot them,'' he said.
The chairman of Scottish Farm Venison, Russell Marchant, vice-principal of
Barony College, said the college had shown that deer farming could be run as a
low-labour enterprise. ``We run beef and sheep herds here and we have not been
involved in any extra labour because of deer,'' he said.
Among the advantages he listed was the fact that venison was not subject to
European Union price fixing and could provide a viable enterprise without aid
from the CAP. He produced figures showing that a gross margin of #459 a hectare
could be achieved by a breeder/finisher, #214 for a store calf producer and
#392 for a finisher.
By comparison, an 18-month beef operation could achieve #515, lowland spring
lamb #339 and upland sheep #342. With subsidies stripped out, the lowland lamb
figure would be #127, the upland #105.
Another advantage, as BSE fever takes a grip, is that deer are not subject to
the disease. Venison also has a healthy image as a low-fat meat.
Alex Bowles, chief executive of the marketing co-op, said the UK market was
growing at 15% a year. Scottish Farm Venison was killing 100 animals a week at
Strathaven, and about 15,000 a year were being slaughtered on a UK basis, he
added.
</TEXT>
