<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Court told of hotel drugs raid</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913551</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH Crime Squad detectives worked undercover at a nightspot where drug
dealing was suspected, a court heard yesterday.
They later called in 10 uniformed police - in an operation codenamed Felix - to
raid the Kat House in the Blue Bell Hotel at Lockerbie, and detained 78 people.
Those detained were handcuffed and held in three holding centres at Lockerbie,
Dumfries, and Annan for searches and interviews.
The policeman in charge of the operation, Chief Inspector John McGoldrick, told
a jury at Dumfries Sheriff Court: ``Eight persons were eventually arrested in
connection with allegations of supplying drugs......I think two others were
arrested for being in possession of drugs.''
A quantity of drugs and wraps were recovered throughout the premises as well as
two knives.
Mr McGoldrick was giving evidence at the trial of Mr Ian Gass, 26, of Victoria
Park, Lockerbie, who has pled not guilty to five drugs-related charges.
He denies supplying or offering to supply amphetamine to another person at the
Kat House and possessing amphetamine and ecstasy on August 12 - the day of the
raid.
He also denies being concerned in supplying amphetamine and ecstasy to others
in the nightspot on various occasions last year.
Detective Chief Inspector Tom McCulloch explained that it was decided to
handcuff those detained in the raid to prevent any drugs in their possession
being discarded.
Mr McCulloch added that intelligence had suggested that some of those attending
the Kat House could be violent and had access to knives or firearms.
Detective Constable Veronica Jackson, from the Scottish Crime Squad was
undercover in the nightspot prior to the raid. She told the court that she had
seen Mr Gass approach another man next to a pool table and had seen him take
money and hand over a small flat package.
The trial before Sheriff Kenneth Barr continues.
</TEXT>
