<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Noisy neighbours to face on-the-spot fines</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913552</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NOISY neighbours face a #40 on-the-spot fixed penalty if they refuse to comply
with warnings to tone down night-time nuisance, under tough measures announced
by the Government yesterday.
The creation of a new night-time noise offence - between 11pm and 7am, is part
of a package designed to tackle and clarify ways of dealing with the problem of
noise south of the Border..
A Scottish Office spokesman said the new laws would not apply in Scotland -
where police have more powers than their English counterparts under breach of
the peace laws. However, he said the operation of the laws south of the Border
would be monitored to see if any advantages could be applied in Scotland.
Under the new offence - noise such as from a ghetto blaster, discotheque or
live band or machinery - would have to exceed 35 decibels and the background
level by at least 10 decibels when measured in a complainant's house, before
action is taken.
</TEXT>
