<DOCNO>GH951213-000016</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000016</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Revenge is sparked on drink-drive goalkeeper</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974913553</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SPARK from a barbecue and the fury of a woman landed former goalkeeper David
McWilliam in the dock yesterday.
Glasgow Sheriff Court heard that, as McWilliam cooked a meal over the charcoal
for his girlfriend, a spark landed on her son's arm, causing a minor burn. The
boy's howls, however, fuelled revenge in his mother's heart.
Solicitor-advocate Joe Beltrami said the woman ordered the former Airdrie
footballer out of her Motherwell home, and told him to take his car with him or
she would have it removed. Then she telephoned the police, told them McWilliam
had been drinking, and gave them his home address.
As McWilliam, 43, drove up to his flat in Candleriggs, in Glasgow's Merchant
City, police were waiting for him.
The court was told he initially failed to give a breath test and was taken to
the police station for a test on the Camic machine. This showed that he was
four-and-a-half times the legal limit.
McWilliam yesterday admitted failing to give a breath test and having 154
microgrammes of alcohol in his breath.
Sheriff William Finlayson fined him #250 and banned him from driving for 30
months.
Mr Beltrami said that, had it not been for the spark and the row that followed
it, McWilliam car would have stayed in his girlfriend's driveway for the
weekend.
He added: ``Hell hath no fury like a woman scorned. She blamed him for a slight
burn on her son's arm, and couldn't accept it was an accident.''
After the case McWilliam, who won a Cup Final runners-up medal in 1975 when
Airdrie lost to Celtic, refused to name his girlfriend but said: ``To say that
I am devastated at what she did to me is an understatement. I haven't seen her
since and have no intentions to ever see her again.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951213-000017</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000017</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Capital honour for aid worker</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROB ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974913554</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE founder of a Scottish aid charity was made an MBE yesterday in recognition
of his missions to Bosnia.
Dr Denis Rutovitz of Edinburgh Direct Aid was presented with the award at a
ceremony in the city.
Collecting the award from Edinburgh Lord Provost Norman Irons, Dr Rutovitz, 67,
said the medal was a tribute to all the charity's volunteers including
Christine Witcutt who was killed by a sniper's bullet near Sarajevo two years
ago.
He then announced that he would lead the biggest ever EDA convoy to Sarajevo
which leaves Edinburgh on Saturday. He praised Glasgow's Asian business
community for providing much of the clothing to be taken to refugees.
Dr Rutovitz, who was shot in the chest while on a mission to Sarajevo in April,
was named in the Queen's Birthday honours list in May.
Rather than receive the honour at Buckingham Palace, London, he opted to accept
it from Provost Irons with staff from Edinburgh Direct Aid, including Mrs
Witcutt's husband, Alan, 52, at his side.
On receiving the award the retired doctor said the MBE was in recognition of
the work everyone had done with EDA since it started four years ago.
Doctor Rutovitz said: ``This is an honour for everyone involved in the
organisation.''
Mr Witcutt, of Wishaw, Lanarkshire, said he was delighted Dr Rutovitz had
received the honour and was sure his wife would have approved.
q Meanwhile at Buckingham Palace Mrs Sara Jones, the widow of Falklands hero
Colonel H Jones, was invested a CBE by the Queen for her work with veterans'
charities.
The 54-year-old went to the palace in 1982 to collect her husband's posthumous
Victoria Cross.
Actor Alan Bates, 61, was also made a CBE yesterday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951213-000018</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000018</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Contest that has not helped Labour image</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEN SMITH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974913555</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
KEN SMITH writes on the divisions that have marked the selection of the Labour
candidate in Govan, where a close result is expected tomorrow
SCOTTISH Labour Party officials are anxious to heal the rift between the two
sides of supporters after the debilitating contest between MP Mike Watson and
Glasgow councillor Mohammed Sarwar to become the party's candidate in the
Glasgow Govan constituency.
Voting among Labour members in Govan began on Monday night when four party
members cast their votes in a secret ballot. The small number of voters is
deceptive, however. There are 568 Labour members in Govan eligible to vote, and
485 of them applied for a postal vote.
The remainder have the opportunity to vote at three constituency meetings this
week, with the last one taking place tonight in Pollokshields.
All the votes, including postal votes received at Labour's Glasgow headquarters
by tomorrow morning will then be counted, with the winner being announced later
in the day.
There are in fact three candidates, but Margaret Curran, a Jordanhill lecturer
and campaigner on women's rights, is being squeezed out by the high-profile
tussle between Mr Watson and Mr Sarwar. Her supporters' votes are not lost
however, as they will then be transferred to their second choice preferences.
In fact, the contest is so close between Mr Watson and Mr Sarwar, that it is Ms
Curran's supporters who may have the final say on which of the two men becomes
Labour's candidate.
The contest has not covered New Labour in glory. There have been constant
claims of dirty tricks. First, it was alleged that retiring Pollok MP Jimmy
Dunnachie threw his hat into the ring to ensure there was a contest, and then
withdrew. He denies he did any deal with Mr Sarwar to do so.
Then there was the claim that Mr Sarwar was being investigated by Customs and
Excise over whether duty had been paid on alcohol his successful chain of
warehouses was selling. However, everything was in order.
There also was an intense scrutiny of membership lists by supporters on both
sides to try to rule out those who were ineligible by not being members for a
year or for not being on the electoral roll. About 40 names were thus removed.
But was this a particularly dirty campaign? Mr Jimmy Allison, retired Scottish
organiser of the Labour Party, said yesterday: ``People say it's the dirtiest
ever, but it's really only the dirtiest since the last one.
``It's always going to be fiercely contested when an MP is fighting for his or
her job as is the case with Mike Watson.''
Both sides are genuinely confident of victory. With a secret ballot, it is
impossible to say who has the upper hand.
However, whoever wins, Labour headquarters is keen that the divisions do not
rumble on. Certainly Mr Watson and Mr Sarwar cannot be regarded as bosom
buddies, although Mr Sarwar helped bring out the ethnic vote when Mr Watson
fought off the big SNP challenge in the Glasgow Central by-election in 1989.
Mr Sarwar said:: ``Mike Watson's view is that he is the sitting MP and that I
should not be challenging him. I could understand his anger and frustration if
he was the sitting MP, but as I've tried to explain to him for 18 months, only
a fifth of the new Govan constituency consists of part of his present
constituency. He is not the sitting MP.''
Certainly defeat would mean that Mr Watson would be out of a job after the next
election as it would be too late to apply to another constituency. It would be
a double family blow as his wife Lorraine works as his secretary, and would
also become unemployed.
Mr Watson is in his early 40s, articulate, passionate, and the type of MP that
Labour should be keen to keep.
His failure to advance to a Front Bench position in the party owes more to his
failure to ``wear out the carpet on the way to Tony Blair's office as others
have done,'' as one activist puts it.
His supporters say that Mohammed Sarwar, owning a multi-million-pound business,
is hardly at the cutting edge of socialism.
Both sides reckon 250 votes should be enough to one. Both sides believe they
have attracted enough support. No-one can say for certain who will succeed.
The Labour Party is probably relaxed about either individual.
What the party does not want is any kind of challenge to the result, or even
worse, some form of court action by the losing side. It would be difficult to
imagine Labour organiser Lesley Quinn, who has supervised the contest, being
anything less than scrupulously fair to both sides, so it is hoped that there
will be no loophole left.
Tomorrow, Labour hopes, will be the final say on Glasgow Govan. Whether the
healing process can be completed by the General Election is another matter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951213-000019</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000019</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Bill will increase maximum penalty from #1000 fine to six month prison sentence Minister acts to control knives</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>RAYMOND DUNCAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913556</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LEGISLATION to crackdown on carrying knives was announced for England and Wales
last night, following the fatal stabbing of headmaster Philip Lawrence outside
St George's School in London last week.
Home Secretary Michael Howard said the Bill would enable police to arrest
anyone carrying a knife in a public place without good reason and without a
warrant.
The Bill would also increase the maximum penalty specifically for carrying a
knife, other than a small pocket knife, in public from a #1000 fine to a six
month prison sentence.
It will add to existing legislation which already allows a maximum two-year
prison sentence for the offence of carrying an offensive weapon in public
without lawful authority or reasonable excuse.
The legislation is being introduced in the form of a Private Members' Bill
sponsored by the Tory MP for Sutton and Cheam, Lady Olga Maitland, and will
have full Government support.
q.Meanwhile, one in six Scottish schoolchildren questioned in a crime survey
believed that carrying a knife was not a serious offence, it was revealed
yesterday.
The survey findings resulted from a Young Citizens' Crime Conference held in
the summer in Edinburgh.
A total of 17% of about 200 second-year pupils in the 13 to 14-year-old group
from local authority schools across Lothian said they regarded carrying a knife
or other weapon as ``not very or not at all serious''.
The results of a questionnaire carried out at the event at New Parliament House
were published yesterday at Currie High School, on the outskirts of Edinburgh.
Councillor Marilyne MacLaren, a member of Lothian and Borders Police Board,
said the London tragedy had highlighted ``the violence around us in society''.
She said it was a valuable reference of young people's attitudes to crime, and
hoped that it would be taken notice of by authorities south of the Border.
Inspector Adam Conn, of Lothian and Borders police's community services
department, said the figure of 17% who felt knife-carrying was not serious was
very concerning.
The police had to try even harder to get the message across about the tragic
consequences of possessing a weapon.
He said the police would be studying the results carefully, and future
education on the dangers of knife-carrying would be looked at.
The survey showed that sexual offences were regarded by both male and female
participants as most serious, while vandalism was rated as the least serious
crime.
Councillor MacLaren said the majority of young people were law-abiding and
responsible and it was crucially important to tap into young teenagers'
knowledge and perceptions to reduce crime.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951213-000020</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000020</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>SNP hits at Forsyth over `London levy'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBBIE DINWOODIE Scottish Political Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913557</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE SNP yesterday launched a counter-argument to the ``tartan tax,'' claiming
that the Government had cost firms north of the Border a fortune in extra
taxation.
The party said that Scotland should forget about a tax that might never happen
and concentrate on the ``London levy'' which had cost Scottish business #1.5bn
during the nineties.
During the first five years of the decade firms in Scotland paid #1.2bn extra
in business rates, but Government moves to close that gap in poundage had left
an existing gap in valuation, because of different systems north and south of
the Border.
``What is Michael Forsyth doing about it?'' said SNP party business spokesman
Fergus Ewing.
``The Tories are quick to scaremonger about tax but slow to acknowledge and
address the London levy that Scottish business pays within the Union.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951213-000021</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000021</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>There's no chance of a still life</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Clare Henry</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974913558</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THEY say it's always a famine or a feast - and that success breeds success.
Adrian Wiszniewski is currently run off his feet with almost more commissions
that he can handle. First there's a triple portrait for the Scottish National
Gallery - to be unveiled on Friday. He's painted all three directors, Giles
Havergal, Philip Prowse, and Robert MacDonald, to celebrate the Citizens'
Theatre's fiftieth birthday. The portrait is as punchy and uncompromising as
the productions there, with the trio closely grouped and set against a
patchwork of bright emerald, yellow, red, orange and black.
Then there are two huge pictures for Liverpool Cathedral commissioned by the
Jerusalem Trust: The Good Samaritan and The House Built Upon Rock. These will
hang in the nave and be dedicated on Easter Sunday.
Another big on-going project is for Cleveland's 1996 UK Year of Visual Arts
where he's been commissioned to produce a whole package of five permanent
public art works ranging from 12 large-scale banner-flags for Middlesbrough to
an outdoor mosaic, painted cut-steel frieze and seating area plus a 60ft
Formica gable end for the city centre Odeon cinema and portable neon lighting
for various sites including swimming baths. Cleveland is being treated to one
of his best ploys: a garden of roses designed to spell out SEX. ``It's a
sculptural thing made out of real roses. It'll grow to 10ft tall. It's a maze
to wander in, think about goings on in the bushes - and smell the flowers
before entering the Middlesbrough Art Gallery,'' he explains.
Glasgow also celebrates the UK's 1996 Year of Visual Arts, (despite the fact
that the city lost) and Wiszniewski has been invited to paint the entire top
floor of the new Gallery of Modern Art in Exchange Square. ``It began as two
rooms, but now it's going to be one big function room cum cafe/restaurant, with
about six walls. I get to OK the colour of the carpet too. The architect is
enthusiastic, so I'm sure I'll enjoy myself.'' Before he settled for painting,
Wiszniewski spent three years training as an architect. It's all proved very
useful.
Meanwhile he's just completed his Glasgow Royal Concert Hall mural (of a
quartet of young musicians playing imaginary instruments), book illustrations
for George Mackay Brown's new short story, The Sixth Station, to be published
by Clarion in the next couple of weeks, and, practically overnight, produced a
huge 10ft picture for the London launch of Glasgow City of Visual Arts 1996,
``A fun piece!''
And he's scooped the plum exhibition at next year's Edinburgh Festival with a
solo show at the Talbot Rice (following Bellany and Campbell) which will then
be toured by his Belgian dealer, Gallery F17, to Holland, Germany, Brussells,
Vienna and Japan. ``We are very positive about Adrian's work. He's always ready
to experiment,'' they tell me.
There are spin-offs to this hyper-activity. Wiszniewski banners will also
feature in Central Station next year while the designs for the banners are
being made into screenprints in collaboration with Glasgow Print Studio and
North Shields Print Studio. The prints, together with preliminary Cleveland
drawings, will form an exhibition for Middlesbrough and perhaps Glasgow's 1999
Architecture and Design Gallery in Princes Square.
``But nothing's definite until it's up on the walls. I always wait until the
first cheque comes through; then you know they are serious!''
So does he have a team of helpers; a smooth running workshop; a bevy of
assistants? ``You must be joking! I work at home. On my own. My studio used to
be a byre. We have three kids aged from two to eight. Sometimes it's like a
fairground. I have all these wonderful drawing pens and then I find they're
bashed - the kids have used them for colouring in. The shelves I store my
things on get higher and higher. Kids! But they're great really.''
Louis, Holly, and Max are in fact the apples of Wiszniewski's eye. He's a
wonderful father - something that might surprise those who knew him in his
younger, wilder days. He does more than his share of looking after them with
equanimity, a fact his wife Diane takes in her stride.
Happily Wiszniewski is a fast mover and likes deadlines. The Citizens' portrait
was finished at 4am in time for collection and framing at 10am. I watched its
progress over eight weeks, interspersed with other commissions, starting with
the day he began in a makeshift studio above the Glasgow Print Studio where
each sitter came separately on consecutive days. He began with small, speedy
studies from the life and then sketched in the poses on his 8ft canvas. It's
changed a good deal since then - not so much an evolution as a fast about turn.
Originally Wiszniewski envisaged the three sitters in classical mode, Havergal,
the intellectual heavyweight who has just won t
The commission is the brain-child of Duncan Thompson and James Holloway of the
SNPG. ``James came to see the portrait a fortnight ago when it was
landscape-ish and loved it. But I didn't like it so I painted it all out five
minutes after he was out the door. I drew sections right across it, aligning
the centre division with the cube Philip sits on. James will get a fright at
the unveiling when he sees how it's changed. It was a delicate game to get it
right but I wanted something colourful and strong.''
So how does he juggle all these balls in the air and remain so easy-going and
laid back. Does he never get stressed? ``No. I quite enjoy it all. It's good
fun.'' Of all the artists I know, Wiszniewski is the one most ready to
contribute to Scotland's general artistic community. He's been on the
exhibitions committee of Edinburgh's Fruitmarket and Glasgow Print Studio,
making sure younger, conceptual artists get a foot in the door. His stylistic
interests are broad. His latest idea, for artist designed wallpaper,
(ultimately for sale as limited editions) has attracted funding from Glasgow's
1996 Fund.
His Good Samaritan painting for Liverpool exemplifies Wiszniewski's strengths,
and his ability to make painting relevant to today. He's updated the entire
scene, making the Good Samaritan into a young woman of the 1990s who aids a
victim of a street stabbing, while yuppies exchange their business cards and a
dapper youth, Italian jacket slung casually over the shoulder, looks the other
way. The huge 11ft canvas contains six figures in a complex composition where
the light from a house makes a central, critical, cross of golden light on
black shadow, and a wall shaped like a bolt of lightning acts as a reference to
tragedy which comes at us out of the blue and a support to the Christ-like stab
victim with the gash in his side.
An allegory of The House Built Upon Rock will show a family at the seaside with
a serpentine sand snake, sand-castles, buckets and spades. ``We took the kids
to St Ives. That's where I got the idea.'' Liverpool Cathedral gets 6,000,000
visitors a year so both he and the clergy want the picture to be easily
understood.
``I don't do things just for one reason. I'm using the parable as a premonition
of Christ's crucifixion. The woman, dressed in blue like one of the three
Marys, is giving the victim water in a chalice as though giving communion. The
blood is shaped like a heart while the incriminating Swiss army knife (which
has a white cross on it) points at the bystanders soundlessly accusing them of
their indifference.
`'The business cards represent the mock friendships of today. The victim's
jacket on the ground is orangey red, like the Robe - remember the film with
Richard Burton? - that the Roman soldiers played dice for. The second girl
bystander doesn't run to help but does hold on to her handbag. The Italian
youth is going to walk on by - like the song. They say the sky went dark at the
Crucifixion, a solar eclipse, so I've painted it black. There's a palm tree to
locate the scene. The colours are bright, like stained glass, because it'll be
hung 10ft off the ground. All the work went into balancing the colours. It's
like the Rubic cube. Change one; you change them all.''
I left Wiszniewski to tackle juggling his next big job. But which one would it
be? Characteristically he took the easy option. ``I think now I'll get the tea
on,'' announced Scotland's Renaissance family man.
Artist Adrian Wiszniewski is like a whirlwind of activity as he breezes through
major commissions. Clare Henry views recent works, including the Citizens'
fiftieth anniversary portrait
</TEXT>
