<HEADLINE>Abandon me if I die, musician told lover</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974913559</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MUSICIAN Pollyanna Peate told a jury yesterday how her lover warned her to
abandon him and ``run like hell'' if he should die during one of their illicit
sex sessions in the back of his car.
The 34-year-old mother of two told Chester Crown Court she would regularly have
sex with grandfather Brian Phillips, 62, after they left rehearsal sessions
with the Frodsham Silver Band.
Euphonium player Mrs Peate, 34, of Runcorn, Cheshire, denies the manslaughter
of bass trombonist Mr Phillips on November 15, 1994.
The prosecution says the couple's 10-year love affair was an ``open secret''
among colleagues in the Frodsham Silver Band, but both had managed to keep it a
secret from their marital partners.
It is alleged Mrs Peate attacked him, striking him at least four times, after
he tried to end their affair.
Mr Phillips, who had a weak heart after suffering a coronary attack in 1972,
died of a heart attack as a result.
Mrs Peate told the court she met Mr Phillips 10 years ago. She had begun a
romantic attachment with him soon afterwards.
She said: ``The first time I had sex with him was at the marshes, in the back
of his car, nearly 10 years ago.
``We would go to the marshes after band practice basically every Monday and
Tuesday, when we went to rehearsals. We wouldn't always have sexual
intercourse.''
She said the affair halted for six months five years ago when she left the band
for a time, and she confirmed that she knew from the start that he had a bad
heart.
Mr Benjamin Nolan QC, defending, asked Mrs Peate: ``Did he speak to you about
the possibility of his heart failing when he was with you?''
She agreed that he had spoken about it regularly, from the beginning of their
relationship.
``He said if he was ever to die in my company to leave him, take money for a
taxi and don't say a word - run like hell and just get home. He didn't really
want his wife to find out and I didn't want Graham to find out.''
Mr Nolan asked: ``Did you ever argue with that?''
She replied: ``I did at one stage say I could never do that to him. He said if
you love me you will carry out what I ask.''
She said that when they had sex he would cough, sometimes before they had
finished, and began becoming breathless.
Mrs Peate confirmed that he would use a spray he had for his heart condition
before they had sex.
Earlier the court heard transcripts of a police interview in which Mrs Peate
described how she made love to Mr Phillips that night.
``He was passionate for a while - then he collapsed on me,'' she told
detectives.
``He went with his full body weight on me. His head fell forward and he went
totally flat. He fell right on top of me.''
She then described desperate struggles to get from underneath him and try to
revive him as he made gurgling noises.
She had hit his back, slapped him and tried breathing into his mouth, and at
one point his head dropped after she lifted it up and she thought she had hurt
him.
Finally she had struggled to put his trousers back on, taken some money from
his pocket, tidied her hair, took her euphonium from the car and walked back
into Frodsham to catch a taxi home. She had not been aware of the injuries to
his head.
The hearing continues.
</TEXT>
