<DOCNO>GH951213-000023</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000023</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Music   Music and Memories, Scottish Arts Club, Edinburgh</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Conrad Wilson</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974913560</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LEONARD Friedman, founder of the Scottish Baroque Ensemble, would have been 65
this week. In his memory, friends and fellow-musicians gathered at the Scottish
Arts Club to play music associated with him, interspersed with spoken tributes
and readings from his letters.
Music in intimate surroundings, with performers and audience in close contact,
formed an important part of Leonard's life, and this recital - featuring solo
Scottish violin music, a Handel trio sonata, some Prokofiev, and some of the
salon pieces he so adored - was just the sort in which he himself participated
many times.
No violinist has commissioned more Scottish music than Friedman, though born in
London, of Lithuanian ancestry, he made Scotland the fulcrum of his career, and
Mendelssohn on Mull Festival, his last venture, has continued as his memorial.
Next year's, featuring the usual array of master classes, workshops, and first
performances, opens on June 26.
The Scottish music with which Christopher Field launched Monday's recital was
Macpherson's Lament - not a commissioned work, but one of the grandest of
traditional pibrochs, which developed in the manner of one of Bach's slow
sonata movements, to a peak of solemn intensity before reaching its simple
close.
Handel's G Minor sonata, too, was moving. Here, Field was joined by Daphne
Godson and Gillian Thomas, former members of the SBE, with Leon Coates as
harpsichordist. The welling, overlapping melodies were savoured
Friedman-fashion, the faster music vivaciously expounded.
The first movement of the second of Prokofiev's violin sonatas, in its original
version for flute, introduced a young player, Anna Higgins, of the quality
Leonard constantly searched for and was delighted whenever he found it.
This witty, angular music, sweetly played, lightened the mood of the evening,
paving the way for Dvorak and a spot of Scott Joplin.
</TEXT>
