<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951213-000024</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000024</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ian Bell</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974913561</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TOWARDS the end of last month Mr Rupert Murdoch, that darling man, delivered a
speech in Boston, Massachusetts, to the 250 members of something called the
``Chief Executives Club''. Inter alia, as the lawyers say, Rupe announced plans
to launch upon the world a 24-hour, ``all news'' TV network.
This, the American-Australian told his wholly representative audience, would
provide a corrective to Ted Turner's CNN. ``We think it is about time CNN is
challenged'', Murdoch said.
And for why? Cable News Network, explained the mogul, is moving ``further and
further to the left''. Murdoch thought - or said he thought - that ``it's time
to form a really objective news channel''.
``I don't know whether it happened with my friend Ted marrying Jane Fonda or
giving up lithium,'' the droll continued, ``but, one thing or another, CNN has
changed very greatly in the last couple of years.''
Think about this for a moment. Ted Turner, raving left-winger? CNN, the patriot
missile of television's own Gulf war, ``too liberal''? America, the state that
clubbed, imprisoned, exiled, or electrocuted most of its socialists decades ago
- and eradicated the very idea of pluralism - standing in need of ``objective
news''?
It is a familiar Murdoch technique, first developed in Australia and honed on
the hapless BBC in Britain during the eighties: conflate ``news'' and the
right's agenda, smear the competition, and deploy your own very considerable
resources to ensure that people like ``the Chief Executives Club'' understand
that you, a very humble entrepreneur, understand their needs only too well.
This episode is not, in itself, so very shocking, at least when compared with
some of Rupe's previous escapades. His ruthlessness is legendary, his cynicism
matchless. The mystery of what he actually wants aside, there is nothing new in
this latest outburst.
But consider what Murdoch actually means by ``news''. After all, he is probably
the globe's chief purveyor of that commodity. Much of what you read, hear, and
see in the way of information and comment passes through the hands of one of
his lieutenants. What you or I actually know about most events depends, one way
or another, on what a born-again, right-wing multi-millionaire whose concept of
national loyalty is slight happens to think on a given day.
Now the man who pulled the BBC's World Service from his Asian satellite service
to please China's geriatric ruling class offers America - and by extension the
world - ``objective'' news. While Britain grows fretful over his grip on
sporting events, Murdoch is moving to take control, quite simply, over what we
know.
Melodramatic? Rupert doesn't tell you what to think: of course not. He does not
interfere with the freedom of the media: he's a democrat, after all. Murdoch is
the champion of absolute freedom of choice - much as Henry Ford was the
champion of free choice in the colour of Model Ts. The blank-eyed mogul
wouldn't hurt a fly.
But the real point of the Murdoch enterprise is different. On the principle
that what you don't know won't hurt you, he is taking control over the
well-springs of debate. Like the tree that falls unheard in the forest, a story
unreported by Citizen Rupert is a story that never happened. A political debate
ignored is a political debate neutralised.
And so it goes. Even now, the political culture of Britain remains the product
of the unholy bargain struck by the Murdoch press and the Reaganite/Thatcherite
right in the eighties. Tony Blair's remodelling of Labour was only possible,
for example, because Murdoch's mouthpieces suppressed all alternatives. Real
dissent has all but ceased to exist in the nineties simply because it has been
choked off - amid a plethora of media ``choice'' - at source.
This isn't good for any country, but it is worse for the portion of the world
that likes to call itself free. Murdoch's attitude is contagious; fear, awe,
and envy of his power have run through the global media like a grotesque virus.
Political debate, such as it ever was, has been eradicated. Capital's
contending factions squabble but real challenges to the world order are
rendered invisible - and therefore safe.
The Gospel According to Rupert: globally, continuously, endlessly . . . The
deep, cruel irony is that most of us, grazing on Sky, basking in the Sun,
pumped full of 24-hours ``news'', will never know what is really going on with
the sources of our knowledge, or why. Murdoch will make sure of that.
</TEXT>
