<HEADLINE>Nurse who stole struck off</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRISTOPHER REEKIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913562</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A NURSE who admitted stealing #1515 belonging to patients at Lennox Castle
Hospital was struck off the register by the professional conduct committee of
the UK Central Council for Nursing, Midwifery and Health Visiting in Edinburgh
yesterday.
Mrs Margaret Main Brady admitted three charges of misconduct while she was
employed by Greater Glasgow Health Board as an enrolled nurse at the hospital
in Lennoxtown, near Glasgow.
She admitted misappropriating #1515 of patients' funds by six unauthorised
withdrawals between October 5 and December 30, 1992, attempting to
misappropriate a further #354 of patients' funds on January 25, 1993, and
forging the signatures of four nurses and two managers in furtherance of the
two earlier offences.
Mr Ian Balfour, solicitor for the council, said Mrs Brady had worked at Lennox
Castle from 1988 until Febuary, 1993. Patients who needed money arranged
through a nurse to obtain it from the hospital cashier, and this was done with
counter-signatures by another nurse and a senior nurse.
In six cases, Mrs Brady had signed the cashier's book but the transactions were
not recorded in the ward cash book.
The offences came to light after an audit in January, 1993, and she was
dismissed on February 10. Mr Dave Watson, regional officer for Unison Scotland,
for Mrs Brady, asked the council to accept that her offences were isolated and
uncharacteristic.
At the time of the offence, Mrs Brady had been under considerable stress
because one of her children was ill and her husband had left her.
Mr Watson said Mrs Brady had 11 years of exemplary service as an enrolled nurse
before this incident, and she had a good work record since.
After a recess of 55 minutes, Mrs Elizabeth Rush, chairman, said it had been
decided to remove Mrs Brady's name from the register with immediate effect.
Mrs Brady made no comment as she left the hearing.
</TEXT>
