<DOCNO>GH951213-000026</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000026</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>PC denies passing on intelligence</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913563</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A GRAMPIAN policeman yesterday denied being the source of information allegedly
given to a drugs baron for cash.
Constable James Grimmer, 35 - currently under suspension - told the High Court
in Aberdeen he did not pass police intelligence to Ronald Cormack in exchange
for more than #6000.
He was giving evidence at the trial of Grampian colleague Constable Neil
Cooper, 36, who denies one charge of corruption and two of attempting to defeat
the ends of justice.
Mr Cooper, of Springdale Crescent, Bieldside, Aberdeen, is alleged to have
received the money from Cormack - who is serving 15 years for drugs and
firearms offences - in return for drugs intelligence.
Mr Cooper has lodged a special defence incriminating Mr Grimmer. Asked by
Advocate-depute Alan Turnbull if there was any substance to this incrimination,
Mr Grimmer replied: ``None whatsoever.''
Mr Turnbull then asked Mr Grimmer what he felt when he found out about the
allegation made against him by Mr Cooper.
Mr Grimmer said: ``I was shattered. I just could not believe that he had done
that.''
Later he claimed he and Mr Cooper had discussed the matter in October of this
year at Mr Cooper's house.
``He said he knew that I had nothing to do with the money. He said don't worry
I know you have got nothing to do with taking money,'' Mr Grimmer told the
court.
It was also disclosed that Mr Grimmer had been suspended in January this year
after being arrested along with Mr Cooper and two other officers, and that he
faces separate charges of reset of stolen property and possession of cannabis.
Mr Grimmer said he was friendly with Mr Cooper and had known him since they
were posted to the same police department in 1981.
He said it was information he had received from an informant about Cormack
which set off the inquiry which led to the drug baron's arrest and conviction.
Mr Grimmer said he had never met Cormack and denied passing information either
to him or his associates.
Defence counsel, Mr Kevin Drummond, QC, said he would not be leading any
evidence and both sides retired to prepare their summing up.
The trial, before Judge Lord Macfadyen, continues.
</TEXT>
