<DOCNO>GH951213-000027</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000027</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Guidelines for police over pitch violence on the way</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BENEDICT BROGAN Political Reporter</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913564</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Lord Advocate is to publish guidelines on pitch violence to assist the
police in deciding which offences should be reported to procurators-fiscal. He
is to meet Scotland's chief constables to gather their views.
Mr Donald Mackay QC, the new Lord Advocate - he becomes Lord Mackay today -
yesterday met the all-party Scottish Sports Group of MPs to hear their concerns
following recent clashes at football grounds.
The MPs demanded action to avoid the inconsistencies which they claim have
marked the official response to recent football incidents. They claim
procurators-fiscal have chosen to prosecute for some offences, but not others.
The guidelines, which will be published, will mirror the unofficial ones
currently used by procurators-fiscal in assessing whether an on-pitch incident
warrants prosecution. These are:
q.The seriousness of the offence and whether it causes injury.
q.Whether the offender has any previous convictions.
q.Whether the incident is likely to provoke further violence on the pitch or
among the spectators.
The delegation - which included former Scottish Office Minister Sir Hector
Munro, Labour Front Bench spokesmen John McFall and John McAllion, and Paisley
North MP Irene Adams - was led by Falkirk West MP Dennis Canavan.
Mr Canavan said: ``We realise that players cannot be given immunity from
prosecution just because they are on a football or rugby pitch. We also
condemned the level of violence in sport and emphasised the need for clubs and
the governing bodies of sport to be seen to be taking firm disciplinary action
against players who resort to violence.
``However, there has been concern expressed about apparent inconsistencies in
the decisions of procurators-fiscal as to whether or not to prosecute in
certain cases. We therefore urged the Lord Advocate to issue guidelines which
would help to clarify this matter and hopefully avoid such inconsistencies in
the future.''
A Crown Office spokesman said the meeting had been helpful. ``The MPs accepted
that from time to time it was appropriate for legal authorities to take action
and recognise that the best evidence available should be used, such as video
footage,'' he said.
``We agreed with the MPs that we would be looking to the sporting bodies at
both association and club level to take prompt and effective action in dealing
with incidences of sporting violence.
``We confirm that we will be holding discussions with chief constables with a
view to issuing guidance to the police, and that it should be made public.''
Political concern was raised by the case of Duncan Ferguson, of Everton, and
formerly Rangers, who recently served 44 days in Barlinnie prison over injuries
sustained by Raith Rovers defender John McStay at a match in April 1994.
He has returned to Premiership football pending a court hearing on the merits
of his 12-match suspension imposed by the Scottish Football Association.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951213-000028</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000028</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Gunman `fortunate' not to have been shot by police</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913565</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
POLICE marksmen who surrounded a house in a quiet suburban street during an
armed siege in August showed remarkable restraint by refraining from shooting
the man at the centre of the drama, a court was told yesterday.
Paisley Sheriff Court heard how the incident was so serious there was a real
danger of David Kerr being shot as, armed with a handgun, he threatened to kill
police and blow up his parents' home.
Kerr, 30, turned on all the gas appliances in the house in Drumby Crescent,
Clarkston, and said he would blow up the property.
A tactical firearms unit from Strathclyde Police was sent to the house.
The three-hour drama ended when a skilled negotiator was brought in and Kerr
surrendered.
The court heard how armed police later revealed that Kerr was lucky he wasn't
shot by marksmen.
Depute-fiscal Shona Cook said: ``The situation was so serious that it was
fortunate the officers refrained from shooting him. There was a real danger he
could have been shot.''
Kerr, who has been detained in the Carstairs institution since September to
await his court appearance, admitted unlawful possession of a 7mm revolver,
threatening police officers in the execution of their duty, breach of the
peace, and causing malicious damage to the house.
The court heard how the accused had taken an accidental overdose of
prescription drugs some months prior to the incident while living in England,
and had lapsed into a coma.
His recovery, although described as remarkable, had left him with residual
damage.
He returned to Scotland to live with his parents, who had been trying in vain
to get specialist medical care for him.
On the day in question last August, he had an argument with his mother and she
left the house for help. Minutes later, Kerr shouted out that he had knives and
guns and would use them.
When armed police took up positions, they saw Kerr pointing a handgun in their
direction. They could smell gas coming from the house and saw Kerr was holding
a box of matches.
Neighbours were evacuated when he threatened to blow up the house, and Scottish
Gas workmen were called to cut off supplies to the area while police tried to
calm Kerr.
The court was told the handgun was a vintage weapon which could not have been
used.
Two psychiatric reports from Carstairs indicated that Kerr required a further
period of examination.
Sheriff Colin Higgins imposed an interim hospital order committing Kerr to
Carstairs for a further three months.
He was ordered to return to court on March 5 for updated reports to be
presented.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951213-000029</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000029</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Own goal as Premier shoots at Old Labour</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Stuart Trotter</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>commons sketch</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974913566</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Prime Minister politely thanked his old friend and fellow Chelsea supporter
Mr Tony Banks (Newham North-West - Lab.) for a pleasant social occasion spent
with him recently.
Mr George Foulkes (Carrick. Cumnock and Doon Valley) and Mr Alan Simpson
(Nottingham South) sitting on either side of Mr Banks, ostentatiously edged
away from this Major chum.
The real mystery surrounding the Major-Banks relationship is why two
south-of-the-river boys do not support Crystal Palace. Perhaps something for
the Snobbery in Sport Commission to investigate.
But this outbreak of politeness and goodwill was a cheering diversion from Mr
Major's perpetual efforts to indict New Labour as the unconvincing PR version
of Old Labour.
Mr Blair made the point which seems right as, amid all his indicting, Mr Major
did not get round to denying it, that Government subsidy to the railways
actually will be going up after privatisation.
When Mr Major tried the one about all privatisations turning out great after
being sneered at by Labour, Mr Blair smartly rejoined ``tell that to the
customers of Yorkshire Water''.
Unfortunately, bang on cue Mr Graham Riddick (Colne Valley - Con.) rose with
the decidedly unhelpful request that Mr Major's Government do everything it
could to stop Yorkshire Water cutting off supplies to customers on a rota basis.
Mr Major gave him the undertaking between clenched teeth and moved on to
receive the much more acceptable observation from Miss Jacqui Lait (Hastings
and Rye - Con.) that every Labour MEP had signed a message of support for the
striking French unions who look like doing to Messrs Chirac and Juppe what
their once-mighty British brothers and sisters did to Mr Callaghan.
Did the support not show that ``Labour is still the strikers' friend?'' crowed
Miss Lait.
Mr Major capped this showing that some head at Tory Central Office remains cool
enough to go through the papers each morning.
Not just these unreconstructed exiles in Brussels-Strasbourg, but some nearer
home were perpetrating these vintage Old Labour sentiments, said Mr Major,
happily producing a cutting from the estimable Morning Star.
It contained a statement from the Socialist Campaign Group of Labour MPs here
at Westminster supporting the strikers, he cried. Several Tory MPs uttered
noises of horror and aversion.
Mr Major recited part of the message that ``the struggle going on in France is
one of critical importance to working people throughout Europe''. It went on to
bash capitalism almost along the lines of the heady days of the Foot leadership
and the historic defeat of 1983.
Mr Major's conclusion ``that is real Labour'' had more than a touch of wish
fulfilment about it. He also loyally voiced the latest Central Office smart
line, possibly thought up by an ageing film buff. This possible admirer of the
excellent Henry Fonda movie ``Twelve Angry Men'' may have suggested that the 10
Labour MPs who fought their way past their own whips last week to show what
they thought of the capitalist 1p cut in income tax should be called ``The Ten
Honest Men'' at every possible opportunity.
They are honest, you see, because they openly admit that Labour should oppose
tax cuts and be prepared to increase public spending. This would have been more
impressive if those involved were not what the Opposition Chief Whip dismissed
as ``The Usual Suspects''.
It is probably more the conviction that Mr Blair is going to end nearly two
decades in the wilderness which has produced disciplined abstention and
unnatural silences from all on the left but the ``Honest Ten'' some of whom,
like Messrs Benn and Skinner may actually prefer opposition.
</TEXT>
