<TEXT>
Inverness bans
open-air drinks
A BAN on open-air drinking in public will be enforced next year in Inverness
town centre, to cut drink-related crime. Scottish Office Minister Lord James
Douglas-Hamilton yesterday approved an application for new by-laws made earlier
in the year by councillors on Inverness District Council.
Chief Inspector Tom MacCorquodale said that the new rules, which will come into
force on February 4, would complement the town-centre camera surveillance
system.
Award for doctor
DR ANTHONY Hope, 28, of Dundee University, will receive the Glaxo young
investigator award tomorrow from the British Pharmacological Society, after a
presentation to the society on a study to develop drugs which can lessen the
side-effects of chemotherapy and radiotherapy in the treatment of cancer.
Safety sticker
EVERY primary school pupil in Dundee will issued with a ``Say No To Strangers''
sticker as part of a child safety drive by Dundee Rotary Club. The club is
handing over 14,000 stickers to Dundee City Council.
For the juggler
EDINBURGH District Council's economic development committee approved an
interest-free loan of #5000 to the organisers of a conference to be held in the
city next April. The council is to receive 5% of any profit made by the
organisers, the British Juggling Convention.
</TEXT>
