<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Secrecy row on HMSO sell-off</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GEOFFREY PARKHOUSE Political Editor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913568</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MINISTERS today are reviewing plans to privatise Her Majesty's Stationery
Office in the wake of protests from the Treasury and the Speaker of the Commons.
Mr Roger Freeman told the Commons on Monday that he is reviewing the plan,
worth only about #20m to the Government, and he is expected to announce a
decision this week.
Last night at the Commons it was emerging that much more is at stake for the
Government than the Speaker's concern about the future of the Hansard official
record of Commons' proceedings.
Mr Freeman, deputy to the deputy Prime Minister Michael Heseltine, has been
told by the Treasury that Her Majesty's Stationery Office also publishes the
annual Budget statement.
At stake is Budget secrecy. The Stationery Office so far has been charged with
this, including the all-important Red Book which details Government spending
and taxation plans. If the City got hold of these details from a private
printer, vast sums could be made on the money markets and stock exchanges.
Ministers last night countered that other highly secret Government publications
are already handled by private printers - including defence material and other
sensitive subjects. However, Budget details are another matter.
In the circumstances Mr Freeman is liable to have to get Cabinet approval for
this privatisation before it can go ahead. Speaker Betty Boothroyd is one
important person who is making firm representations to Mr Freeman on the
grounds that the published dissemination of the Commons's deliberations could
be jeopardised.
Behind the scenes there is a big Treasury rethink on this issue. The #20m that
the Chancellor might gain from privatisation is seriously outweighed by the
security involved in publishing his Budget statement efficiently and secretly
in the last few days before he delivers it.
Senior Tory back benchers are also adding their weight to representations
demanding from the Government how these highly sensitive market revelations
could be handled securely by a private printing company.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951213-000032</DOCNO>
