<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Shock killed mutilated girl</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913569</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCHOOLGIRL Naomi Smith died of shock after her throat had been cut by her
killer, an inquest heard yesterday.
The 15-year-old was killed after leaving her home in Ansley Common, Nuneaton,
Warwickshire, to post a letter for her mother just 100 yards away.
Her lifeless body was discovered by her father and her 15-year-old best friend
Emma Jones, lying beneath a children's slide on a recreation ground just three
doors from her home.
She had been sexually mutilated and her throat had been cut.
At a resumed hearing at Nuneaton town hall yesterday, attended by Naomi's
father, Brian, 45, mother, Catherine, 47, and brother, David Freeman, 25,
Warwickshire coroner Michael Coker said a post mortem examination report showed
the schoolgirl had died of shock following the horrific injury to her neck.
Referring to a report by a Home Office pathologist, the coroner said: ``The
cause of death can be described as shock and haemorrhaging due to the slicing
injury to the neck and compression of the neck.''
The coroner asked for an update on the investigation and Detective Inspector
Brian Varriale said: ``On Thursday November 16, a 19-year-old man was arrested
in connection with Naomi's death. He was charged with murder two days later. It
is intended that matter will go to the Crown court.''
Adjourning the inquest until the outcome of that trial, the coroner said that
he could now register Naomi's death, as the police no longer needed to carry
out further tests on her body.
Addressing her family, he said: ``More importantly, it allows me to release her
for her final rites to be carried out.''
Naomi's mother left the court in tears and her son David said the family was
still trying to make arrangements for Naomi's funeral service.
He said: ``We don't have any firm plans about when the service will take place
yet.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951213-000033</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000033</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Pantomime   Sleeping Beauty, Palace Theatre, Kilmarnock</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Mary Brennan</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974913570</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE official panto watchdog, Ofpants, was under a cloud en route to the Palace.
Well vapour more like. Distinctly camphor and eucalyptus ..... As Ofpants
barked and wheezed, I wondered, not for the first time, what this job does to
its personnel.
Some two hours later, still chuckling at various bits of genial japery - this
Sleeping Beauty is a very family-friendly show - and Ofpants had a checklist
dotted with power salutes and little smiley faces.
A lot of this is definitely down to Johnny Beattie's consummate skills as a
dame, no question. But Johnnie Adam (Jingles the Jester) has a good line in
ready patter while Graham MacGregor (King to Anne Field's Queen) is just funny
whether he opens his mouth or not. He's hilarious.
This means comedy of all sorts keeping the pace from flagging, so that the
songs even seem a quite desirable interlude!
But then Leigh Blaney - a personable Beauty - and Sally Logan (Fairy Crystal)
are actually worth listening to. Louise Beattie - this panto is affectionately
called the Baddy versus the Daddy - is a very classy, vampy wicked witch.
Ofpants thoroughly approves of pantos being a family tradition!
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951213-000034</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000034</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Smiling all the way to next century</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Sara Villiers</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974913571</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GULP, I'm feeling grim, unable to muster even the slightest grin to commemorate
the Smile for Safety Week, which was launched yesterday by the British Safety
Council as a combative measure against the perils of that most modern of
diseases, stress.
Forty years ago no-one went around banging on that they were stressed out but
now it affects one in three employees and is one of the main causes of ill
health.
So, the British Safety Council, anxious to stem the 90 million working days
lost through stress-related illness each year which costs British industry
#1.3bn, believe stress can be fought with a big smile, although I reckon two
weeks lazing in Lanzarote sucking up banana Daiquiris would be far more
effective.
Well, you lot can show off your bobby dazzlers all you want. This lady's not
for smiling, certainly not after the announcement earlier this week that men
are about to become a scarce commodity. I'm so shocked I can scarcely muster
the energy to put some lippy on, never mind twist my lips into a simpering
smirk.
This latest scaremongering snippet comes courtesy of Mihir Warty, an economist
at the Centre for Economics and Business Research (CEBR). Having analysed the
population trends for the prime marriage age brackets - 18 to 29 for women and
20 to 31 for men - Mr Warty predicts that chicks will confront a dwindling
number of potential husbands early in the next century.
But hang on a minute. Perhaps this news is not all that it seems. It's tempting
to suspect that there might be a slight case of sour grapes here. Perhaps the
not very attractively monikered economist has been unable to find a woman
willing to become Mrs Warty! I mean, it doesn't sound very alluring, does it?
Perhaps he'll shock marriageable women into dashing out and snapping up the
first available chap before the millennium?
One positive side effect of CEBR's terrifying prediction is that female
participation in the more affluent end of the labour market will allegedly be
boosted. Mr Warty reckons that this is because women will become more career
minded to make themselves more economically attractive to the prime group of
men.
Shucks, sounds like Mr Warty has us babes sussed. He's clocked on to the fact
that we're normally only playing at the career game and are really sitting back
waiting for some guy to show up with a wad and an engagement ring. If he isn't
scheduled to make an appearance then we'll have to pull our finger out and
flaunt our own financial success. Drats. Sounds like too much hard work.
Mr Warty predicts that men will be in the optimum bargaining position in
relationship stakes which, these days, what with prenuptial financial
agreements and all are increasingly taking on the clinical, passionless status
of a contractual arrangement. Writing in the latest CEBR report Mr Warty says:
``When men are scarce they can bid up their price. As the `price' of men rises,
women may have to offer a more attractive package.''
As far as I can see the modern miss is already offering a near superhuman
package, prepared to put in the hours at the office, the home, and the gym,
take an interest in sport and not dare to look for too much commitment while
offering oodles in return. But Mr Warty is busy ticking the
``could-try-harder'' box.
He ventures that women may have to offer to work for longer, to return to the
labour force or - and this is when the tone of the report somewhat suspiciously
slides away from economic jargon - women may ``reduce their insistence on a
long-term commitment''. More alarmingly, he suggests, and now I'm really
starting to smell a (warty) rat, that women might have to ``provide a greater
level of promiscuity''.
Up and down the country economists are no doubt rubbing their hands in glee,
salivating over Mr Warty's vision of the woman of the future. She'll be rich
and successful and drive a racy little sports car - apparently the surge in
female affluency will correspond with rising sales in sports cars, as we
desperately turn to spending our dosh on tempting shag-wagons in an effort to
track the boys down.
The future lass will spend so much time in the office the future lad will be
practically footloose and fancy free. And, of course, even when she's not
working she'll be too scared to make any demands of him, so relieved will she
be that she's managed to get her hands on one of these rare creatures. She'll
be a proper little pussycat but a tiger in the bedroom. She won't mind if he
eats kebabs between the sheets because she'll be so grateful that he's between
the sheets at all. And boy will she show that gratitude. His every wish will be
her desire.
Hmmmm. Get real, boys, and file that image in the fantasy bin. By the start of
the next century if men in the UK are becoming scarce young women will have the
wherewithal and the sense of adventure to head off abroad looking for some
decent specimens.
We're not going to hang around at home becoming overworked doormat girlfriends
who turn a blind eye to promiscuous pursuits. There's plenty more fish in the
sea and, believe me, we'll be out there flirty-fishing. Perhaps we'll hook up
some hunky Alaskan chaps or entice some tasty Ruskies over.
We certainly won't be afraid to put out the bait. It's changed days since Helen
Morrison, a spinster of Manchester, was the first woman to place a lonely
hearts advertisement in a British newspaper.
Following her plea in the Manchester Evening Journal in 1727 the city mayor
responded by confining her to a lunatic asylum. Well, sorry boys, those days
are over. You're all nuts if you think we're going to get stressed out at the
prospect of a hubby famine. The very notion makes me giggle. Looks like I'm
smiling after all.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951213-000035</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000035</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>From disaster to sparkling success story</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Advertising Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974913572</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CARRICK Jewellery saw its future threatened by a disaster which happened half
way around the world. It recoverd enough to build a thriving business in the
UK, but its exporting ideas stayed only pipe dreams until it won a #20,000
award from GDA through the International Executive Scheme.
Set up in 1971, Carrick had specialised in producing traditional Scottish
jewellery for the tourist market. The 1986 Chernobyl disaster and subsequent
environmental paranoia had a devasting effect on tourism and Carrick's market
virtually disappeared overnight.
``The Chernobyl disaster panicked tourists,'' said managing director Eddie
Robertson. ``The downturn in visitors meant that we recorded our first loss
since we started trading in 1971. Sales went down by 22%.
``We knew prospects for sales and serious growth had taken a blow and that it
could take us years to recover if we were going to continue with our exisiting
range of traditonal Scottish jewellery. We had to find new markets - and
quickly.''
A change of tack led to the production of fashion jewellery. The original range
was small, but had been exhaustively researched by Carrick's team of designers.
The eventual product was instantly recognisable as being in the Rennie
Mackintosh style.
The entire first stock sold out in 12 months and the firm went on to develop
and extend the range. By 1988 the company had pulled itself free of financial
disaster and had a turnover of #700,000 a year. In 1989 it saw its first
#1,000,000 turnover. In 1995 the company has pulled in an astonishing #4m.
Last year Carrick invested more than #500,000 in doubling its manufacturing
capacity. Initially the Mackintosh collection was produced for the home market,
but it was not long before Robertson began to investigate the possibilities
offered by exporting. This would not have been possible, however, without the
support of GDA's International Executive Scheme.
``The company had reached bursting point,'' said Robertson. ``I needed someone
working on exports to promote the Collection and liaise with agents and
distributors.
``Financial support from GDA allowed me to take on a Belgian living in Glasgow
who had previously assisted us in translation and export marketing.''
January this year saw Carrick attend the Europacado Show in Belgium, where a
Belgian agent offered to act as a distributor throughout the Benelux countries.
The success of this arrangement encouraged Carrick to be present at further
exhibitions, and in September a visit to the Bijochar Exhibition in Paris led
to more international business - only 20% of which was from French firms. In
fact, Carrick's largest order from that exhibition came from Japan.
The award from the GDA has meant that Carrick can afford to attend exbhibitions
all over the world and pay for a full-time export executive. ``It has offered
us direct support, exactly where and when it was needed,'' said Robertson.
``This is the sort of assistance small firms need. There are a lot of people
ready to sell you advice, but at the end of the day it's support like this that
makes the real difference.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951213-000036</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000036</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Bright sparks playing with fire</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MARK FISHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974913573</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MARK FISHER discovers an impromptu gathering which could set the theatre world
alight
THE fax proclaimed: ``Nigel Osborne's Alternative Christmas Circus.'' Down at
Richard Demarco's place in York Lane, Edinburgh. The arts editor was on to me
as soon as the fax reached his desk. ``Well, it's starting on December 5,'' he
said. ``Which is today. And the first event appears to be at 1pm.'' Brief
pause. ``Which is now.''
The underpublicised Alternative Christmas Circus transpired to be not a rolling
programme of pre-Yuletide events, but a 24-hour marathon feast of music, visual
art, theatre, and cabaret put together by Osborne, the composer and university
lecturer, with his students and pals including George Wylie (who'd sailed his
paper boat from land-locked Kosovo in the former Yugoslavia specially for the
occasion).
I made it along for 8.30pm when a production called Journey to Delphi (``A
meeting with Macbeth'') by a company of Scots and Poles was scheduled.
Before now, the Demarco Arts Foundation in the converted St Mary's School had
only really been active during the Edinburgh Fringe in August. But in dark
December it came as a shock to find myself in an all but deserted building,
with various handwritten signs indicating that something should be happening in
the vicinity.
Macbeth was due to go on outdoors in the courtyard. This on the day The Herald
had promised ``snow, frost and bitter winds from Siberia''. Suddenly a group of
people appeared and forced its way through an unlit doorway into the murky
shadows of the courtyard.
This, I try to remind myself, is how the best theatre happens, unexpected,
hidden, done for the love of it, not for the comfort of the audience. And here,
as a supermarket trolley full of wood was set alight, spitting sparks and ash
at the audience; as Macbeth's witches performed exaggerated angular dances or
bellowed down from the surrounding rooftops; and, as earnest Eastern Europeans
mused on the cyclical pattern of violence, revolution, and power struggle
across our continent, there was an invigorating sense of theatre as a real,
living, communicating, important medium.
Rehearsed in only a day and lasting just 15 minutes, it is not the most
coherent piece I've ever seen, but there's a passion and an energy there that's
worth nurturing. Young director Toby Gough was behind the show (and he himself
has only been given a day's notice - ``Hey, Toby you're playing the lead in
Macbeth tomorrow night,'' may be the stuff of most actors' darkest nightmares,
but it is the way this director flourishes).
He brought us Grimm, which won a Guardian Student Award a few years back, and
then Linnaeus, Prince of Flowers, an outdoor spectacle performed in the
Botanical Gardens in both Edinburgh and Glasgow and which he will recreate in
New Zealand in January.
In between he's been journeying through Africa to research a play about David
Livingstone, working in Sarajevo with local schoolchildren, and organising a
deputation of helping to get a package of leading British directors over to
Denmark for Copenhagen's Year of Culture.
The Macbeth project was on the cards for three years, and it is the ambition of
his collaborator, Zdislaw Hejduk of Poland's Teatr 77, to get a full production
put on in Scotland, possibly with the collaboration of Vaclav Havel and Gunter
Grass. Let's hope they pull it off.
By this time we were back inside, having wandered round the gallery spaces,
some displaying the work of the inmates in Saughton Prison, others of the
children from Preston Street Primary School, others still with Nigel Osborne's
Edinburgh University music students performing scratch improvisations next to
the installations.
In the bar, Caledonian Scouser Mitch Benn launched into his stand-up comedy act
with only his acoustic guitar and acerbic observations for protection.
So far, so 1995. It was then that Osborne's time machine started revving up.
Out came the ``anthropomorphic'' instruments - odd-shaped home-made
contraptions, a distorted violin, a box with protruding nails, which made the
kind of plucky, strummy and rattly cacophony that would have made any late-60s
acid trip seem seriously freaky.
But barely had we had a chance to find our feet in 1968, before we were dragged
back another decade. Not just improvised music this time, but simultaneous
action painting. You know, splattering colour on to the walls as the mood of
the music takes you. And take them it did.
I left them to their night of happenings, rather glad there were still people
prepared to behave like this in the otherwise straight and sensible nineties.
If Richard Demarco ever manages to get his venue operating in such a way all
year round, Edinburgh will indeed become a jollier more curious place.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951213-000037</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000037</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Pantomime   Vassalissa and the Baba Yaga, Theatre Workshop, Edinburgh</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Mary Brennan</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974913574</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A melodious tale
casts its spell
I SUSPECT that taking over the directorship of Theatre Workshop is rather like
coming face to face with the demanding Baba Yaga - you have to have the right
answers to the right questions and accomplish certain tricky tasks......
New director Robert Rae has, however, leapt the crucial hurdle of the Christmas
show with style: Vassalissa and the Baba Yaga succeeds in maintaining the
venue's best traditions of a rattling good tale with strong appeal for younger
children, while having more than enough dash and detail to hold the attention
of any accompanying adult too.
Based on an old Russian folk tale, Vassalissa brings together various abiding
themes: lonely girl mistreated by stepmother and stepsisters (shades of
Cinderella), a wily witch who asks riddles and eats children (the Sphinx meets
Hansel and Gretel!), and a magic doll who comes to life - every child's
cherished dream at some point - and ensures a happy ending for our heroine. It
may sound complicated, but the text and the playing make it easy and exciting
to follow.
There's also a lovely use of Eastern European influences lending a strange,
exotic edge to the magical, scary goings-on - the music (if not the singing!)
is thrillingly atmospheric. A wooden set on two levels has sudden windows and
an unexpected table.
The folk-costumes take on dramatic swagger in the case of the witch and the
mysterious, pennanted knights who guard the gates of her house of bones. Vari
Sylvester's Baba Yaga is slinkily malevolent, Mari Binnie's Vassalissa is
goodness without cheesiness, while Gillian Kerr and Shonagh Price provide the
necessary element of broad comedy throughout their various cantrips as the
self-centred, stupid step-sisters. An hour of quality enchantment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951213-000038</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000038</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<FLAG>NEWS DIGEST</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974913575</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Air fares war
is stepped up
THE cut-throat competition on the Glasgow-London air route intensified
yesterday. EasyJet, which began its cheap services to Luton last month, is to
freeze all fares between now and Christmas Eve at #29.
The company has offered a limited number of #29 fares since launching, but
these were on a first-come first-served basis and the remainder were priced at
#39, #49 and #59.
Body identified
A BODY found by police at waste ground on the A82 Loch Lomond road on Monday
was identified yesterday as that of Roderick Martin Campbell, 21, of Gladsmuir
Road, Hillington, Glasgow, who was reported missing on November 21. A
28-year-old man is the subject of a report to the procurator-fiscal.
Popular sentence
MORE than 5600 offenders were required to do community service by Scottish
courts in 1993. Lord James Douglas-Hamilton, the Scottish Home Affairs
Minister, said the figures reinforced the Government's commitment to the
development of community service as a tough and challenging disposal for the
courts.
#100,000 Turner
LANDSCAPE with a Rainbow, a painting identified as a work by J M Turner from a
fingerprint on it, fetched #100,500 yesterday at Phillips' auction rooms in
London.
Ice cream raid
AN armed man last night robbed an ice cream van in Paisley and escaped with the
takings, believed to be a three figure sum. The van salesman, a 26-year-old,
was threatened with a handgun but unhurt. Police hunting the raider said he was
in his early 20s, medium height and with red stubble on his face.
Drugs sentence
TEENAGER Dominic Russell, of Prestonpans, was sentenced to three years in a
young offenders' institution at Haddington yesterday for having drugs with
intent to supply.
Ram raid plea
POLICE are appealing for witnesses to a ram raid at the Kinnaird Park shopping
complex in Edinburgh early yesterday. A blue Ford Fiesta rammed the window of
Olympus Sport, and two men stole sportswear and equipment valued at #500.
Blaze death
A MAN was found dead yesterday after a fire in a house in Hartfield Crescent,
Neilston. Police said there were no suspicious circumstances and a report would
be sent to the procurator-fiscal.
Minder fined
ALAN Hannah, 42, was fined #300 at Haddington yesterday for assaulting and
ill-treating a six-year-old boy he had been minding at a house in East Lothian
where he was lodging.
Health trust plea
LABOUR MP Tommy Graham has written to Health Secretary Stephen Dorrell, calling
for him to stop a restructuring exercise at Renfrewshire Health Care Trust. Mr
Graham said he was appalled at the speed at which the move had been ``steam
rollered'' ahead.
Cue for inquiry
SHERIFF Andrew Bell yesterday called for police to investigate claims by
witnesses at Edinburgh Sheriff Court that staff in a city pub refused to call
an ambulance for a man who was assaulted with a pool cue.
Gretna record
AT least 3600 couples will have married at the register office in Gretna by the
end of this month. Last year's record figure of 3522 will be passed on December
23.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951213-000039</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000039</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Major to urge rethink over single currency at summit</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STUART TROTTER Political Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974913576</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DIVISIONS over Europe within the Tory Party re-emerged yesterday as the Prime
Minister indicated that he will use this weekend's Madrid EU summit to urge
Britain's partners to think again about a speedy move to a single currency.
His leadership challenger in July, Mr John Redwood, raised the temperature by
launching a campaign against replacing the pound with a single currency and
called for the next Conservative election manifesto to rule out Britain joining
in the lifetime of the next Parliament, which could run up to 2002.
In a swift and angry response, the pro-Europeans led by former Foreign
Secretary Lord Howe, denounced his proposal as ``a fatal mistake.''
However, in Commons exchanges, Mr Major made clear that he will be taking a
Euro-sceptic stance on European Monetary Union up to and during the election
campaign.
Mr Redwood had welcomed his questioning of assumptions behind the drive for a
single currency at his recent meeting with the Italian Prime Minister. He asked
if he intended to pursue the points he had raised in Madrid where the heads of
government are due to discuss the agenda for next year's intergovernmental
summit on the future direction of Europe, nicknamed ``Maastricht Two.''
Mr Major told him he would following up the points he had made about ``the
problems that might occur were a single currency to proceed with a small
minority of countries in it and a larger majority of countries outside it.'' He
added: ``I believe it raises a whole range of issues that have not yet been
properly considered and I will be seeking further consideration.''
This pleased the Euro-sceptics but further alarmed the pro-Europeans already
enraged by Mr Redwood's move to commit the party against backing a single
currency, a move which some said privately could tear the party apart.
Last night, a group of them warned Mr Major that he should ``never say never''
to a single currency. Mr Redwood's intention to conduct a national campaign in
defence of the pound raises the nightmare prospect for them of an end to the
party's fragile ceasfire on Europe.
At his news conference, Mr Redwood said the entire grand design for a Euro
currency was already ``in crisis'' and would founder altogether if the French
people turned against it.
A pro-European group led by Lord Howe and EC Commissioner Sir Leon Brittan and
including Lord Kingsdown, a former Governor of the Bank of England, issued a
joint statement saying: ``Any Conservative manifesto commitment against a
single currency would inevitably divide the party, fuelling its electoral
difficulties.
``It would set the Conservative Party leadership against major parts of the UK
business and finance community, undermining the party's political base.''
Shadow Foreign Secretary Robin Cook said: ``The civil war in the Tory party
gets worse as the day goes on.'' He called on the Prime Minister to clear up
whether he agreed with Mr Redwood or not.
``As the rifts inside the Tory Party grow, it will become more necessary for Mr
Major to come down on one side or the other.''
Price of aloofness.....................13
Leader Comment......................14
</TEXT>
