<HEADLINE>Trust is called on to explain</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DUNCAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913577</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Scottish Office has demanded an explanation from the Lanarkshire Healthcare
NHS Trust over apparent ``weaknesses'' in the management of a pilot computing
project.
According to a report on BBC Scotland yesterday, the trust spent #100,000 on
the information technology project without competitive tendering or signing a
contract. The report further claimed that the trust had no rights to the
computer software and had broken European rules governing competition.
The BBC alleged that an internal investigation in August had criticised the
management of the project on a number of counts.
The news report stated that the trust's director of nursing and its computer
adviser had earlier given the pilot overwhelming approval and costed a
three-year expansion of the scheme at just over #1m. But this was now in
dispute because the trust had no copyright control over the software developed.
The report named Master Applications, based at a business centre in Milngavie,
near Glasgow, as the computer company involved in the pilot.
In response to the claims, the trust yesterday issued a statement explaining
that it had invited Master Applications to work with it to develop computer
applications for community nursing and physiotherapy information systems.
The trust said it had already acted upon the recommendations of the audit
review. The pilot phase had been concluded and the trust had no continuing
contractual relationship with Master Applications.
A spokesman for the Scottish Office said last nignt: ``We have asked the trust
for a report giving us full details.''
</TEXT>
