<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Voyage of discovery making South Side story</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Tom Shields</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>Diary</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974913578</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE cross-cultural nature of Glasgow life is about to be captured on celluloid.
The rich texture of the Scottish-Asian community is the subject of a film
called The Making of Ronnie Singh which is based on the story of Glasgow actor
Subash Singh Pall.
With a name like Pall, it was always likely that Subash Singh would be a very
Glasgow kind of character. His career so far has ranged from running the Alien
Arts drama company in Kinning Park, through creating Banghra music with a
Scottish accent, to a role in Taggart.
So far, the film is still at the development stage. But now it is looking more
likely to come to fruition. The script has been written by Stuart Hepburn,
whose film McCallum about a Scottish pathologist in London hits our TV screens
this Christmas.
Shekhar Kapur, one of India's best-known film directors, has been approached to
make the movie. After a weekend on location in Glasgow to get a feel for the
story, Shekhar Kapur is very enthusiastic about the project.
Kapur hit the headlines with his film Bandit Queen. It is the uncompromising
true story of Phoolan Devi, a low-caste Indian who was gang-raped and
brutalised into a life of crime and goes on to become a bandit leader. The film
caused a storm of political controversy in India.
The Making of Ronnie Singh is a somewhat gentler story set in the South Side of
Glasgow. Among the delights enjoyed by Mr Kapur on his voyage of discovery
round Glasgow was the Govan shipyard where Subash Singh was an apprentice and
Ibrox Park for Saturday's match against Partick Thistle. (Yes, Subash was a
bluenose in his early days.)
Peter Broughan, the film producer behind Rob Roy the movie, has become involved
in the Ronnie Singh project. ``It will be the first-ever Scottish-Asian
movie,'' he says enthusiastically. There is a rumour, however, that Broughan's
enthusiasm may not be unconnected with his love of curries. In three days
showing director Kapur around Glasgow, he managed to fit in meals at Mother
India, Mr Singh's, and the Ashoka - three of Glasgow's finest Indian food
establishments.
Don't look back
IN our mailbag we find the top from a tin of Felix cat food emblazoned with
details of a special offer. Send #2.99 and you will receive an extremely cute
Felix 1996 calendar. Very straightforward except for the bit that says:
``Applications to arrive by 31-12-97.'' We always suspected that cat-owners had
flipped heir lids.
Dim view
MICHAEL Grade, chief executive of Channel 4, is a very nice man apart from an
irritating habit of always smoking bigger and better cigars than anyone else in
the world with the possible exception of his uncle Sir Lew Grade or Fidel
Castro. Mr Grade also talks about television all the time. So it was nice to
hear that he attended a business women's lunch this week in Dunbar and was
seated next to a lady who told him she hadn't watched a TV programme since the
coverage of the royal wedding in 1982. Perhaps they talked about cigars.
Down to earth
WE hear of a conversation between a country lady who lives a sheltered life and
a chap who is a keen member of the Territorial Army. He is telling her about
the coming weekend when he would be going parachuting. ``I didn't know there
was a place in Scotland where you could shoot parrots,'' she replied.
Nothing special
EDINBURGH has stolen something of a march on Glasgow with its Hogmanay
entertainment. The capital has three days and nights of events. The dear green
place has a party in George Square lasting three hours.
Edinburgh has concerts with the Kinks, Edwyn Collins, Gary Glitter, and Big
Country. Glasgow offers the Gyres, Swiss Family Orbison, Captain Shifty. Oh,
and the Bay City Rollers.
It is hardly surprising that visitors are heading east for New Year. But the
newly announced Glasgow programme does have one intriguing listing.
For the 15,000 who gather in George Square for the free party it promises
something called ``Performance intervention within the crowd''. Or, in other
words, a normal Hogmanay in Glasgow.
Biting comedy
STAND-UP comedians specialise in turning the events of everyday life into
vignettes for their performance. Phil Kay had plenty to tell his audience at
The Stand comedy club in Edinburgh earlier this week.
It was a topical Christmas story about his front teeth. How he lost three of
them (two real, one false) when his face came into contact with the forehead of
a bouncer at a Glasgow club. (Tales of blood and teeth on Glasgow pavements
seem to go down quite well in Edinburgh.)
As a complete contrast The Stand has another West of Scotland person topping
the bill on Sunday. He is Bruce Morton who, as far as we know, has all his
teeth - but almost no hair.
Twist in the tale
THE Langs Supreme Whisky Fourth Wise Man competition continues. And who is this
turning up at the stable in Bethlehem? David Thorburn of Clydebank suggests it
might be the innkeeper himself who is about to spoil the whole Christmas story
by saying he has had a cancellation and is now in a position to offer Joseph
and Mary a family suite.
Jack Lovie of Irvine nominates financial fraudster Nick Leeson who might turn
up bearing (if you'll pardon the pun) a gift of a baby bond.
</TEXT>
