<HEADLINE>Phoenix rises from  a poetic time warp</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANN DONALD</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974913579</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Combining poetry and music gives a new meaning to the spoken word, as ANN
DONALD discovers
GLASGOW may be rather smug when it comes to boasting Booker and McVitie winners
but when it comes to the ascending art form of performance poetry the former
city of culture has been lagging sadly behind its east coast cousin.
For the past two years Edinburgh has been reclaiming the goatee-stroking world
of poetry via the determinedly youthful club-inspired and buzzing atmospheres
of Rebel Inc magazine and Yellow Cafe's big nights out, while Glasgow stayed in
a time warp of middle-aged Arran jerseys and pints of bitter.
Thanks to Rebel Inc's natural successor, the innovative west coast literary
magazine Cutting Teeth, and the CCA's equally innovative events policy, this is
set to change with the dynamic Motor Mouths series. For Margaret Ritchie, the
CCA's events co-ordinator, the aim of the four nights - embracing everyone from
John Cooper Clarke to Mancunian Lemn Sissay and the Nuyorican Poets - is to
explode the preconceived notions most people still retain from being force-fed
Wordsworth and Keats at school.
``It's not about sweating blood and trying to decode a poem on the page but
rather the poetry jumping off the page and hitting us smack between the eyes
and ears. It's a celebratory, dynamic and thought-provoking thing and not an `I
wandered lonely as a cloud' thing at all,'' she says.
One notable factor underpinning the Motor Mouth poets' work is the close
relationship with music and its ability to reach an audience for whom the word
``poetry'' had previously induced a shudder of distaste or stream of bored
groans and sighs.
In America this combination of music and performance poetry has proved to be
potently commercial with poets appearing on compilation albums alongside
Nirvana and Pearl Jam, regular spots on MTV, and endorsing everything from Nike
to jeans from The Gap.
Bobby Millar, Samantha Coerbell and Alan Kaufman who launched the Motor Mouth
series on Saturday with an impressive display of verbal pyrotechnics, are all
regulars at the Nuyorican (New York Puerto Ricans) Poet's Cafe in New York's
Lower East Side.
Kaufmann explains the Spoken Word phenomena sweeping America: ``The scene rose
from the ashes of the stand-up comedy scene because many of the poets were
addressing subjects in a humorous way. Also every art form bar poetry had been
exhausted.''
What clinched it though were the infamous poetry Slams which take the form of a
league match where poets lock together in verbal gladiatoral combat competing
one-on-one for cash prizes, judged by the audience on a point system. ``I
remember walking into the Cafe for the first time,'' recounts Kaufmann. ``There
were 200 people dancing and then the music stopped, the lights went up and the
poetry slam was announced by a vaudevillian guy sliding across the stage. Four
poets appeared and the audience judged them, booed them and cheered them. This
mix of music, dancing and spoken word went on to 4am. It was a revolution!''
</TEXT>
