<HEADLINE>Widow hopes murder will not be in vain</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Raymond Duncan</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974913580</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE widow of murdered headmaster Philip Lawrence said yesterday she hoped his
death would not be in vain.
Mrs Frances Lawrence said she hoped his pupils would grow up knowing right from
wrong and with a firm belief that love must triumph over hatred.
She broke her silence, for the first time since her husband was stabbed to
death on Friday, in an open letter to the children of St George's, Maida Vale,
west London, to say how much comfort they had given her.
``Your sweet letters to me recognise that, in that moment, the world was
deprived of a man of great strength, tenderness, and profound understanding,''
she said.
Mr Lawrence, 48, a father of four, was stabbed as he intervened to stop a pupil
being beaten up by a gang outside the Roman Catholic school.
``Violence is not a knife in the hand. It grows, like a poison tree, inside
people who, unlike yourselves, have not learned to value other human beings,''
she said.
``Now, I trust you to work as hard as you can, in school and at home, to create
a world in which goodness is never again destroyed by evil.''
At her home in Ealing, west London, Mrs Lawrence said she had been moved by the
thoughts and wishes of the hundreds of people who had written to her.
She wrote to the pupils: ``You tell me how he gave you pride in your school
and, even more importantly, in yourselves. You speak of his friendliness and
humour.
``At home, he would share with me and the children his delight in your daily
progress and his conviction that each one of you is a fine human being who has
the potential to achieve great things.
``I share that conviction.
``Through your loving letters, I can see how much you care about other people.
I can see that you understand the difference between right and wrong and your
belief that love should always overcome hatred.
``Your headteacher's - my husband's - death will not be in vain if you grow up
with these ideals firmly rooted in your hearts.
``I have heard so much about you all. I have found great comfort in your
letters and comments. I should like to visit you in the new year.''
Detective Superintendent Brian Edwards, leading the inquiry, made a direct
appeal to the family, relatives, and friends of the youths involved in the
murder to contact police with any information they had.
He said no-one should be deterred from coming forward by speculative reports on
the inquiry.
Scotland Yard has denounced reports that the murder team was on the verge of
making arrests.
``It's unhelpful to us. It causes distress to the family. It's just inaccurate.
It raises false expectations,'' a spokesman said.
A team of 24 detectives is sifting nearly 200 statements from pupils, staff,
and others, and Mr Edwards said they had had a ``wonderful'' response from the
public.
Mr Ian Hamerton, administration manager at St George's, said classes were
running as normal although an air of grief continued to hang over the school.
``While there may well be tears inside, we still have jobs to do,'' he said.
For the second day children arrived for school with flowers in memory of Mr
Lawrence, and Mr Hamerton said they had been deluged with calls and letters
from well-wishers.
``We're treating the situation with care and dignity, which has reduced the
need for counselling, but we still need some,'' he said.
``Pupils have freedom throughout this week to see counsellors at any time they
wish. We have many locations throughout the school when we can have either
group or individual counselling as the need requires.''
He knew of no pupils who were too distressed to attend school.
``There's been a determination on the part of some of the children to come in.
There were pupils in yesterday who would not have normally come in because they
were not well.''
</TEXT>
