<HEADLINE>Ford workers to ballot on action</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROY ROGERS Industrial Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913581</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FORD'S 22,000 manual workers are to be balloted on industrial action in the new
year after union leaders yesterday confirmed their rejection of the company's
``final'' pay offer.
Union officials will seek an urgent meeting with Ford in a last-ditch effort to
head off a dispute. Meanwhile, local officers will be told to prepare for a
postal ballot on industrial action in protest at the offer, which is worth
about 9.25% over the next two years.
Mr Tony Woodley, the Transport and General Workers' Union's national secretary
for the motor industry, said a ballot was the next logical stage, although he
declared himself optimistic that industrial action could be avoided, if Ford
returned to the negotiating table and improved its offer.
Mr Jimmy Airlie, chief Ford negotiator for the Amalgamated Engineering and
Electrical Union, said: ``The company can be under no illusion that, unless
significant improvements are forthcoming, the unions are determined to conduct
a massive campaign for a yes vote in the ballot on industrial action.''
Ford unions are seeking a rise of 10% to compensate for huge productivity gains
and are very keen to win a two-hour cut in the 39-hour week, although Ford has
said it will not concede reduced hours.
A Ford spokesman said the company would wait to be officially notified by the
unions about the decision before making any comment.
Meanwhile, negotiations are set to resume tomorrow over broadly similar demands
for Vauxhall's 9000 blue-collar workers, who are banning overtime and taking
Friday afternoons off after rejecting an offer of 3.5% this year and the rate
of inflation next year.
They, too, are being denied any reduction in their 39-hour week, and are in
effect seizing a two-hour cut by leaving work at lunchtime each Friday.
</TEXT>
