<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Management buy-in team led by ACS plans to diversify following #20m deal Philips sells Airdrie factory</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Robert Powell</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913582</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PHILIPS, the Dutch electronics giant, has agreed to sell its Airdrie telephone
factory to a management buy-in team in a deal worth more than #20m.
The buy-in is led by David Boyce, an English businessman who formerly worked
for Canadian and US manufacturers of telecommunications equipment.
His company, ACS Communications, will take over the factory with 400 employees
once the deal is completed later this month.
ACS will continue making telephone equipment for Philips for at least five
years, but it also plans to manufacture for other original equipment
manufacturers (OEMs) and develop own-brand products for sale direct to
retailers and telephone installers.
ACS will create about 20 new jobs in sales and marketing at the factory. Mr
Boyce said there were no plans to reduce the shop floor workforce, which should
be kept busy for the forseeable future.
ACS signed a letter of intent to buy the factory yesterday, but details are
being kept under wraps while it ties up a financing package.
Mr Boyce, his partner Sandy Ellis, and several top managers at Airdrie who have
joined the buy-in, will provide a considerable chunk of equity with the help of
a large bank loan.
Murray Johnstone Private Equity in Glasgow will complete the deal with several
million pounds of venture capital.
``The total funds being raised for the acquisition and for on-going development
of the product range will almost certainly be in excess of #20m,'' said Graham
Miller of Murray Johnstone.
Only part of this sum will be paid to Philips. The rest will be working capital
for ACS, which plans to diversify Airdrie's client base and product range
rapidly.
At present the factory produces telephone equipment for small offices,
including exchanges with up to 100 lines, exclusively for Philips.
Mr Boyce, a Londoner who is chief executive of ACS, said that within three
years Philips should represent only a quarter of the company's business.
``We have been negotiating with other OEMS and we have reached some heads of
agreement which are confidential,'' he said.
ACS is buying not only the factory, but also the intellectual property rights
to the telephone products manufactured there. ``We are acquiring an enormous
kitbag of technology that we can use to develop other products,'' he said.
Philips announced several months ago that it wanted to sell the Airdrie plant
so it could concentrate on manufacturing telephone equipment at the larger end
of the market.
Eventually, it attracted Mr Boyce, who had been looking for a small
telecommunications business in the UK to buy into.
After studying engineering and business studies at Bradford University, he
worked for the Canadian firm Northern Telecommunications for 14 years in both
North America and Europe.
Mr Boyce then became head of overseas business for Texas-based BSC
Communications in Dallas for four years. He left in 1994 to set up his company.
Glasgow-born Mr Ellis, the finance director of ACS, is an old friend of Mr
Boyce who worked alongside him in both his previous jobs.
</TEXT>
