<DOCNO>GH951213-000046</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000046</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Safe alcohol limits Medical opinion divided</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE></BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Leader</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974913583</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NOBODY promised us an easy life or a safe one. If you drive you face the risk
of an accident and if you smoke your lungs will be polluted and possibly
destroyed. If you drink alcohol you encounter a substance which can be a
civilised pleasure or a corrosive addiction. This spectrum, ranging from
pleasure to pain, is not a single jump but a continuum. Where you find yourself
on it depends on an array of elements which include your state of health, what
you drink, how much you drink, and how you drink. There may also be a genetic
disposition to excess. All this is set down, not that readers may be confused
but that there may be a very real appreciation of the fact that safe drinking
is not a matter for generalisations but must be composed of a reasoned
assessment of the benefits and dangers in the light of personal experience and
circumstances. Those who make such an assessment with the aid of the best
advice possible will survive and maybe even flourish from moderate consumption
of alcohol; the unheeding will damage themselves and may die.
Where this leaves the Government's attempts to set safe limits for alcohol is
not entirely clear. It can be argued that it is the duty of a Government to
advise citizens on matters like this and, perhaps more importantly, thereby to
reduce the burden of coping with the consequences for the National Health
Service of unwise consumption. If that is the starting point the method of
accomplishing it is exceedingly difficult. Safe levels of alcohol are given in
units, but a unit of strong beer will have more effect that a unit of weak beer
and the same applies to wine. Careful drinkers will work this out; careless
drinkers would not know a unit if it bit them, which assuredly it will in time.
Mr Dorrell's latest attempt at explanation, and his amendment upwards of the
safe limit, is not particularly helpful. The timing is crass, even if you
acknowledge that safe drinking and driving and safe drinking are separate
issues. Mr Dorrell does not make enough of the fact that medical opinion on the
new limit is divided. The safe limit is now estimated at 28 units of alcohol
per week for men, but the report also points out that those who drink four or
more units a day may suffer a health risk. What is abundantly clear is the risk
of bingeing. Spread your weekly units evenly over the week and you may be safe.
Pack them into a weekend, or one unwise evening, and you could be in serious
trouble; that is why the new safe limit is expressed in daily rather than
weekly units. Well and good, but the real task is to persuade everyone to sit
down and think seriously about what they are doing and to refer any problems or
questions to a doctor. Guidelines are fine, but they are no substitute for
personal responsibility.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951213-000047</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000047</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Price of aloofness is dawning on Major</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Murray Ritchie</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974913584</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
JOHN MAJOR arrives in Madrid tomorrow night preparing finally to confront the
vexed issue of the European single currency at the EU summit. Playing on his
mind will be the increasingly alarming thought that on this, the biggest
political initiative in the 40-year history of the European Union, the British
Government might just have got it all terribly wrong.
A new air of anxiety is noticeable among British Ministers and their senior
officials when the subject is raised these days. Plainly, things are not going
their way.
For the moment, the back-bench Tory Eurosceptic rebels are quiet, except when
they step out of character to cheer on the French strikers protesting against
the unpopular disciplines France must take to join the single currency. But
supporters of economic and monetary union (Emu) can take heart. With luck, the
French street disorders will soon be history and the Emu project should be back
on course.
Between the biggest players in Paris and Bonn there is, on the surface,
complete agreement that Emu must and will succeed - and on schedule. The
European Commission, although privately split on the timing, insists the great
dream will come true. No-one - anywhere - seriously believes the single
currency is mere fantasy.
All of which explains why the rising tension in British Government circles
where the most senior figures are now talking apprehensively about what will
happen to those countries who are unwilling or unable to join the single
currency on Day One.
John Major's difficulty is that his famous negotiating triumph at Maastricht,
when he won the right for Britain to opt-out of a single currency, looks as
though it has rebounded on him. He won his standing ovation in the Commons at
the time but the short-term party political advantage has long since
disappeared. Emu's progress might be tortuous but it is undeniable. Now the
Prime Minister faces Edward Heath's gloomy apocalypse of a Britain locked
outside Europe while others take the real decisions inside.
British Government leaders are fretting as never before that countries opting
into the single currency will celebrate their own boldness by taking the
unification process a step too far. This would involve them forming unofficial
voting blocs on vital political issues while ignoring member states which
retain their own currencies.
This action would be justified by their claim to be the true standard-bearers
of European unification and that they had proved themselves with their
commitment to the single currency, the jewel in the European Union's crown.
British officials are punting a new phrase for this eventuality. They are
talking grimly of other countries beginning to engage in a ``radical
undermining of the European Union''. In today's atmosphere in the European
Union, where Britain is isolated on so many issues, this is Apache talk.
John Major cannot abide the thought of Day One inner-core members of the single
currency - who will almost certainly include Germany, the Benelux states and
Austria, and perhaps France - hijacking the EU's economic and political agenda
in this manner. How dare they?
This nightmare is of John Major's own making. He could make the best of things
and boast to his Eurosceptics that he is his own man, determined to ensure that
Britain remains independent and sovereign with its shrunken pound. A
Eurosceptic General Election campaign might help. The political cost is, of
course, high: he must then test the patience of the majority of his own party
who are pro-Europe and he must be content to watch European decision-making
being run increasingly by a small group in which Britain has no influence.
Alternatively, he could join in the debate now about the effects of the new
money on excluded currencies and perhaps warm publicly to the idea of founder
British membership. But that would be seen as a U-turn of possibly fatal
proportions. Mr Major has got himself in a bind which is becoming daily more
painful.
The British pound will probably meet the Maastricht criteria for joining the
single currency from the start. A decision by Britain not to support this most
European of European aspirations will not go down well with others in the
community - especially big countries like Spain, for example, which is
desperate to join a single currency but simply cannot meet the Maastricht
conditions. Much more sympathy will be extended to the Spanish and others like
them, including the strongly pro-EU Italians, with their limping lira, who are
also keen to join as soon as they possibly can. Only now, it seems, is the
price of remaining aloof dawning on Mr Major as the rest of the EU gets serious
about abandoning its separate, competing currencies. In Madrid, they will
choose a name for the new money and have a tough discussion on so-called
``monetary cohabitation'' which is horrible Eurojargon for the relationship
between currencies which stay out and those which merge.
Chancellor Helmut Kohl of Germany, for whom the march towards Emu is a crusade,
will demand safeguards for the single currency against voluntary competitive
devaluations from those on the outside. He will have by his side the faithful
French whose President, Jacques Chirac, has sworn to join Emu as a founder
member. The strength of Chirac's commitment and his solidarity with Kohl have
also taken British observers by surprise.
Suddenly the British are sounding urgent about the need to study the effects of
the single currency on those remaining outside. ``It would be wrong just to
wait and see how it works,'' a British official reasoned yesterday. Observers
could be forgiven for wondering why this thought did not command more attention
from John Major several years ago.
For no-one in Britain has done more to suppress the debate on the single
currency and its effects than the Prime Minister. His former Foreign Secretary,
Douglas Hurd, called for a widespread public debate on the issue. Mr Major
later slapped him down along with the entire British Government.
Mr Hurd called himself an agnostic on the subject - and even that diplomatic
sidestep would be a touch too outspoken for his famously pragmatic successor,
Mr Rifkind. Can anyone recall a British Minister giving a strong opinion,
either for or against the single currency, in public recently?
There is a simple explanation for this unedifying abandonment of
responsibility. Mr Major used his opt-out - successfully - for party political
consumption. But now the real world has caught up.
The Prime Minister cannot expect to be taken seriously when in one breath he
says it is too soon for a public debate on the single currency and in the other
that we must first know the advantages and disadvantages of joining it before
we take a decision.
As Europe's leaders head for a summit on the single currency, John Major could
find he has condemned Britain to being a sideshow, reports Murray Ritchie
</TEXT>
</DOC>
