<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>INVESTMENT AND DEVELOPMENT Pillar given the green light for Broomielaw development</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRIS STONE City Editor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974913585</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PILLAR Property Investment, the investment and development company floated on
the stock market in August 1994, has received planning consent for the first
phase of 130,000.sq.ft of its Broomielaw development site where most of the
demolition and clearance has been completed.
Chairman Raymond Mould, unveiling the company's half-year results yesterday,
including a first-ever interim dividend of 1.5p, commented: ``While it is not
our intention to commence speculative development, we are encouraged by the
extent of interest in possible pre-lets which would then enable construction to
commence.''
Pillar bought the second phase of the Broomielaw site in July 1994 for #4.25m.
It permits 920,000.sq.ft of office development over a period of years.
The first phase, comprising 280,000.sq.ft of offices, was developed in the late
eighties by Scottish developer Bellhouse Joseph and Kumagai Gumi of Japan. In
the present construction phase, Pillar is working in partnership with Bellhouse
Joseph.
Just how long the development of the whole site will take must depend on the
state of the Glasgow property market, which has only seen a little improvement,
according to chief executive Patrick Vaughan, but will take several years. As
the company stresses, it is only interested in pre-lets.
Meanwhile, pre-tax profits grew from #34,000 to #1.1m after charging #852,000
in respect of the deficit over book value arising on the sale of Tower
Ramparts, Ipswich, earlier in the year. This investment was acquired for #16.5m
in 1991 and its sale contributed a surplus of #4.8m to distributable reserves.
The surplus earned on the sale of Ipswich, together with the trading profit for
the period, more than covers the interim dividend.
Looking ahead, the chairman said that at the beginning of the calender year
there were high expectations of rental growth in the property sector but this
had not materialised across the board. However, there had been strong rental
growth in retail park investments and in the company's shopping centres. There
were also indications of improvements coming on a broader front, he said.
The investment market has been dull and given this background, it is pleased
with the sales and purchases which have been concluded this year.
Pillar continues to have high gearing though it remains confident this is at a
``sustainable'' level. However, close attention continues to be paid to the
cost of debt and every opportunity is taken to minimise financing costs with
all investments financed so that rents more than cover interest. Cost capping
and longer maturities are also part of its armoury.
The shares dipped 2p to 142p.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
