<DOCNO>GH951213-000049</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000049</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Cray slumps into the red</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<FLAG>business digest</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974913586</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Cray slumps
into the red
CRAY Electronics shareholders will not receive an interim dividend payout after
the group reported a slump into the red yesterday.
Restructuring and rationalisation costs of #9.3m in the group's principal
communications division were largely responsible for sending the company diving
to a pre-tax loss of #14.6m for the six months to the end of October.
That compared with a taxable profit of #10.1m in the corresponding period last
year when it paid out a 1p interim dividend.
Earnings per share last time of 3p were converted to losses of 6.3p.
Wood contract
JOHN Wood Group, the Aberdeen offshore services company, has won a three-year
contract to provide maintenance services for Total Oil Marine's North Alwyn
platform in the North Sea for a further three years. The #3m contract will
involve 33 Wood Group staff working on the platform, which Wood Group has been
associated with since it was commissioned in 1985.
Tunnel directors
ROY Chapman, retired senior partner of accountant Arthur Andersen in the UK,
Keith Edelman, chief executive of Storehouse, and Chris Green, chief executive
of English Heritage, have joined the board of Eurotunnel as non-executive
directors.
Dana float
DANA Petroleum, an independent oil production company with operations in
western Siberia, is to seek a full listing on the London and Irish stock
exchanges.
On board
PATRICIA Mann, a vice-president international of advertising group J Walter
Thompson, has been appointed a non-executive director of British Gas.
BET swap
INDUSTRIAL services group BET has exchanged its manned guarding business,
Shorrock Guards, for Securicor's electronic security business Securicor Alarms.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
