<DOCNO>GH951213-000050</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000050</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Survey shows Scots really are canny with the cash</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913587</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT'S not a myth - Scots really do put away the most money for a rainy day,
according to the results of a lifestyles survey published yesterday.
It shows that investors north of the Border put an average 15.4% of their money
into savings and investments.
The average for the rest of the UK is only 10.3% - except for London and
South-east England, where it drops to between 5% and 7%.
However, the report says that when the Scots do splash out, they like to spend
their money on having a good time, with holidays among their priorities.
The report, by analysts Mintel, shows that the north-south divide is narrowing,
with the traditionally rich South-east of England worst hit by the recession.
Other regional patterns show that Londoners spend least on cigarettes, while
Northern Ireland, with the lowest property prices, spends the most on fuel
bills and groceries.
People in the North-west of England prefer to spend money on booze, while Scots
and Geordies put cigarettes high on their list of priorities.
The quality of life in London is improved by owning your own home - but people
in South-east England look to luxury items to improve their lot.
In Anglia and the Midlands having a good pension was more important, but those
in South-west England and Wales listed health insurance.
The Scots just want money, holidays, a TV washing machine, and the chance to
smoke in peace.
A Mintel spokesman said: ``The canny Scottish saver is not just a myth, they
really do save the most. They tend to be cautious with finances and look for
safe investments.''
The report is based on surveying 1519 adults throughout Britain.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951213-000051</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000051</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Housing cuts could mean 10% rent rise 400 council jobs at risk in cash crisis</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOHN MacCALMAN Municipal Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913588</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A CASH crisis could mean a 10% increase in Glasgow District Council rents and
the loss of more than 400 jobs.
A combination of circumstances, including an anticipated #33m cut in the city's
housing capital allocation from the Scottish Office, has left Labour
councillors with agonising decisions to make prior to the Christmas break.
And it means the new City of Glasgow Council will take over the running of the
city in April in an atmosphere of deepening financial gloom.
Crucial to the situation is the Government's imminent announcement on housing
capital allocations - permission to borrow - which officials expect to be cut
from #98m in the current financial year to #64.4m.
According to council sources, it would mean no new housing starts in the next
financial year and no new programmes to tackle housing problems.
It is understood the anticipated Government cut, together with factors related
to the loss of prime housing stock in Rutherglen and Cambuslang to the new
South Lanarkshire Council, could mean a rent increase of #3.56p per week and
400 job losses in housing, building services and property services.
The average rent in Glasgow is currently #33.23p per week.
Another factor in the financal crisis is the practice of capitalising staff
salaries. This is currently running at around #12.5m and is likely to be
halved, putting more pressure on the revenue account - the rents.
But the final kick in the teeth for many councillors was the recent Scottish
Office announcement that 25% of all capital generated by council house sales
will be clawed back to pay off local authorities' capital debts.
The situation could be more acute in future years if the Scottish Office
implements its intention to increase the clawback to 50%.
Meanwhile, a financial expert warned yesterday that thousands of tenants in
homes owned by Scottish housing associations could face rent rises because of a
little-noticed proposal in last month's Budget.
The move, if ratified by the Scottish Office, would end the associations'
effective exemption from corporation tax and leave them facing annual bills
totalling more than #2m.
Mr Mike Blyth, the Scottish managing partner of chartered accountants Kidsons
Impey, said the change would force housing associations to raise their rents,
or put off maintenance on homes.
In Scotland, non-charitable associations have traditionally received a full
reimbursement of any corporation tax from the Scottish Office, via funding
agency Scottish Homes.
Mr Blyth said:``The Chancellor has adopted a back-door method to save cash by
taking away grant aid that was extremely important to the majority of housing
associations.
``For many tenants, this move will, almost certainly, more than offset the
personal tax reductions offered in the Chancellor's speech.''
Mr David Orr, the director of the Scottish Federation of Housing Associations,
said: ``This proposal is a body blow to Scottish housing associations and has
no justification.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951213-000052</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000052</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Children of courage meet celebrities</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974913589</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LEUKEMIA victim Jaymee Bowen - formerly identified in court battles only as
Child B - was rewarded yesterday for her courage in fighting the disease.
She was one of eight children who picked up Woman's Own Children of Courage
accolades.
Four-year-old Susanne Shepherd from Beith, Ayrshire, was cited for her courage
in enduring many excruciating operations, including one failed transplant, for
a rare kidney condition.
Eleven-year-old Jaymee admitted she was ``embarrassed'' to win one of this
year's medals.
``It's quite normal to get ill and try to fight off the bug. I don't think I've
done anything special,'' Jaymee shrugged before collecting her award from the
Duchess of Kent at Westminster Abbey in front of a gallery of celebrities.
Jaymee's plight was highlighted after Cambridgeshire Health Authority refused
her treatment on the NHS believing her condition to be beyond medical help and
her father launched a court case.
But after private treatment she is back at school in Hertfordshire and she said
yesterday: ``I feel fine.I hope to do games at school soon.''
During the presentation of engraved medallions, actor Anthony Andrews read the
citations and actress Gemma Bissix - Clare Tyler in EastEnders - read a lesson.
Other celebrities taking part were Big Breakfast star Gaby Roslin, Coronation
Street actress Sherrie Hewson, Sean Blowers from London's Burning, pop group
Deuce, and children's BBC presenter Josie D'Arby.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951213-000053</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000053</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Murderer dies in prison</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<FLAG>news digest</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974913590</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Murderer dies
in prison
A PAISLEY man who beat a stranger to death 19 years ago for two packets of
crisps and 35p died yesterday in Saughton Prison, Edinburgh, where he was
serving a life sentence.
Allan Gowdy, 40, is believed to have died from a severe asthma attack in his
cell. In 1976, at the High Court in Glasgow, Gowdy was jailed for life for
murdering a 57-year-old man.
Housing group
AN umbrella group, Helensburgh and District Housing Federation, has been formed
to represent six local groups when Argyll and Bute Council takes over in April.
The group was previously linked with Dumbarton District Council.
Vandals at risk
TEENAGE vandals are risking their lives by removing electrical parts from
street lights in Argyll. The police warning follows reports that live parts,
carrying mains power, are being taken from lights in Lochgilphead and nearby
Ardrishaig and that someone could be electrocuted.
Youth jailed
A TEENAGER was ordered to be detained for 2!s years yesterday for a knife
assault. Kenneth Allan, 18, of Hamilton, admitted stabbing another youth twice
in the body during a fight last year. Allan's victim made a full recovery after
nine days in hospital, the court heard.
Ring robbery
WEDDING rings valued at more than #20,000 were stolen during a break-in at Fred
Hill the Jewellers in Argyle Arcade, Glasgow, on Monday, police said yesterday.
No tribute
HOUSE-building giant Barratt has angered a councillor in Newmains, Lanarkshire,
by refusing to donate to a memorial for boxer Jim Murray. David McKendrick was
so irate at the builder's claims of poverty yesterday that he sent company boss
Sir Lawrence Barratt a #10 postal order ``to help him get over the recession''.
New assessor
THE Glasgow-based Student Loans Company has appointed Mr Graham Chandler, who
recently retired as registrar of Nottingham University, as its new independent
assessor. He takes over from Mr David Birrell, who is retiring.
Thunderbirds go
AN anonymous Thunderbirds fan paid #23,000 yesterday for Lady Penelope's cerise
Rolls-Royce at Phillips auction house in London, then a further #20,000 for the
original 12in model of Parker, its cockney chauffeur. The lady herself is going
down under, snapped up for a bargain #14,000 by an unnamed Australian.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951213-000054</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000054</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Builder refuses memorial gift</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<FLAG>news digest</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974913591</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Builder refuses
memorial gift
HOUSE-building giant Barratt has angered a councillor in Newmains, Lanarshire,
by refusing to donate to the menorial of boxer Jim Murray. Local councillor
David McKendrick was so irate at the builder's claims of poverty yesterday that
he sent company boss Sir Lawrence Barratt a #10 postal order ``to help him get
over the recession''.
Bantamweight Murray, 25, died after a title fight with Drew Docherty in
Glasgow's Hospitality Inn in October.
#7m development
A #7M PLAN to develop a former bakery site into a 100,000sq.ft non-food retail
unit with 500 parking spaces could create more than 150 jobs in Dundee. The
application, by Grantchester Group plc, to build the unit opposite the Kingsway
retail park will be made at the next meeting of Dundee District Council's
planning committee.
Plans for Tweed
MORE than #2m in funding is being sought from the Millennium Commission to
develop the Tweed estuary at Berwick. Planned projects include an innovative
walkway into the river; a small-craft marina; a special hospital to treat of
swans and other wildlife; and dock entrance improvements.
Plant approved
A CONTROVERSIAL giant #12.5m sewage works near Lossiemouth has been given the
go-ahead by Grampian Regional Council, and will be built if Moray District
Council approves. The unanimous decision yesterday was made despite opposition
from the Lossiemouth Action Group, which is now considering a petition.
Head fined
HEADMISTRESS Murial Macleod Macdonald of Bragar School, Lewis, was fined #400
and disqualified for 15 months at Stornoway Sheriff Court yesterday for driving
with an excess of alcohol. Macdonald, 34, admitted the offence and had
not-guilty pleas on four other traffic offences accepted.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951213-000055</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000055</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>A wee dash o' Doric in TV Nativity</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913592</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MORE than two million day time TV viewers across Britain will be treated to a
dash o' Doric on Friday.
Fourteen pupils from Drumblade primary school in Aberdeenshire have been picked
to perform their Nativity play on This Morning.
But the children, aged between five and seven, will not alter the dialect for
viewers.
The three-minute play includes the line, ``Cwid we hae a wee keek at the
bairn,'' spoken by farmer's son Sandy Hunter, six.
The play ends with Sandy saying: ``I'll gie him ma' crook. It's nae muckle but
it's a' I've got.''
Programme producer Peter Trollope said: ``It's just what we want. I'm sure
people will get the jist. We picked Drumblade because it sounded a great
school.''
Mrs Aileen Ingram, whose seven-year-old daughter Emma is one of the cast, wrote
to the programme after she saw the appeal for plays. ``I told them that Edna
Smith, their teacher, was retiring next year and she had been producing the
little ones' nativity plays at Drumblade for more than 30 years and it would be
a great tribute to her and the children.''
The children travel to Liverpool by coach on Thursday. Their play will go out
live on Friday between 10.30am and 12.30pm.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951213-000056</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000056</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Company disputes NHS ban</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913593</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MAKERS of gel-filled capsules of Temazepam yesterday launched an urgent High
Court challenge against Health Secretary Stephen Dorrell's decision to ban its
top-selling product from the NHS.
Mr Dorrell acted after misuse of the capsules was linked to the deaths of drug
addicts.
Yesterday Mr Anthony Scrivener QC, appearing for the pharmaceutical company R P
Scherer Ltd, argued the Minister had exercised his powers unlawfully.
He said almost the entire prescription of Temazepam in the UK was to NHS
patients, and Scherer had a 67% market share as the sole manufacturer in the
country of gel-filled capsules.
If the ban was implemented, the company stood to suffer ``severe losses''.
The QC won permission to seek judicial review of Mr Dorrell's decision.
GPs will still be able to prescribe the less popular tablet and elixir forms of
the drug.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951213-000057</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000057</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Nurse who stole from patients struck off</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Christopher Reekie</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913594</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
By CHRISTOPHER REEKIE
A NURSE who admitted stealing #1515 belonging to patients at Lennox Castle
Hospital was struck off the register with immediate effect by the professional
conduct committee of the UK Central Council for Nursing, Midwifery and Health
Visiting in Edinburgh yesterday.
Mrs Margaret Main Brady admitted three charges of misconduct while she was
employed by Greater Glasgow Health Board and was working as an enrolled nurse
at the hospital in Lennoxtown, near Glasgow.
She admitted misappropriating #1515 of patients' funds by six unauthorised
withdrawals between October 5 and December 30, 1992, attempting to
misappropriate a further #354 of patients' funds on January 25, 1993, and
forging the signatures of four nurses and two managers in furtherance of the
two earlier offences.
The offences came to light after an audit in January, 1993, and she was
dismissed on February 10.
Mr Dave Watson, regional officer for Unison Scotland, for Mrs Brady, in a plea
of mitigation, asked the council to accept that her offences were isolated and
uncharacteristic.
At the time of the offence, Mrs Brady had been under considerable stress
because one of her children was ill and her husband had left her. Fortunately
her son was now much better and she was reunited with her husband.
Mr Watson said Mrs Brady had 11 years of exemplary service as an enrolled nurse
before this incident, and she had a good work record since. She now works at
Campsie View Nursing Home, Kirkintilloch.
After a recess of 55 minutes, Mrs Elizabeth Rush, chairman, said it had been
decided to remove Mrs Brady's name from the register with immediate effect.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951213-000058</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000058</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Dunedin questions The shape of things to come</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE></BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Leader</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974913595</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MANAGING millions excites the popular imagination even when the millions
represent a weak currency rather than, say, the Swiss franc. To laymen the
intricacies of contemporary capitalism touch the margins of magic and romance,
areas of unreason. To professionals these are the areas where reason is most in
demand and the whole process demands the coolest mental qualities whether it is
futures (of various kinds), currencies, bonds, or stocks and shares which are
being managed. The Leeson affair attracted so much attention because all the
numbers involved seemed staggering. Those who manage monies and investments
come to take the sums involved for granted. It requires much industry and rare
qualities all the same, and imposes a fair amount of stress. The practitioners
really operate at a point where art and industry fuse and the least that can be
said to explain the goings on at Dunedin Fund Managers is that such fusion
imposes great tension, and that even the most detached intelligences can
abruptly seek to change jobs. A goodly clutch of its top investment managers
have recently quit the Edinburgh company. How much their going has damaged the
company is a matter of guesswork, though they have taken a large part of their
customers with them from what is a multi-million dollar client base. It is a
reminder of how this sort of work has soared in Edinburgh in the past two
decades as well as how important pension fund asset management has become to
the Scottish investment community.
What precisely went wrong at Dunedin remains to be explained but such events
may well become more, rather than less, common in the future. We are producing
more companies engaged in managing international investments all the time. It
seems to be something at which we are rather good; something where Scotland's
reputation for monetary prudence and probity has evoked a considerable
following which crosses international frontiers. It needs to be protected from
upheaval.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951213-000059</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000059</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Father tells of drugs death</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913597</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A FATHER told last night how he learned from a call on a mobile phone that his
21-year-old son had become the latest statistic on Strathclyde's drugs death
toll. Mr Frederick Hutcheson was on his way to work when his wife telephoned to
say his son, Mark, had become ill.
As Mr Hutcheson returned home to Barra Crescent, Old Kilpatrick,
Dunbartonshire, he was held up by motorway traffic and called his family, only
to hear his son had died.
It is thought to be the 100th drugs-related death in Strathclyde this year,
although this has yet to be confirmed by a post-mortem examination. There were
97 such deaths in Strathclyde last year, 43 in 1993, 73 in 1992, and 21 in 1991.
His father said in a local radio interview last night: ``Once I got five
minutes away from home I phoned to see how he was. My daughter answered the
phone and said he had died. I could not believe it. When I came home he was
just lying on the floor.
``Twenty-one years of age and he had never done any harm to anybody in his
life.''
His son had told his family he had a drugs problem and they had taken him to
the charity Turning Point for counselling. However, on Saturday night Mark said
the problem was ``desperate'' and since then he had remained inside the family
home in Old Kilpatrick.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951213-000060</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000060</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Consistent formula needed</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974913598</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Laggan community's chance to buy their local forest from the Forestry
Commission is a surprising and most welcome decision by the Secretary of State
for Scotland.
Given the opposition he is meeting from the Forestry Commission and the deep
dissatisfaction of local people with that body in other areas of the country
perhaps Geoff Fagan, of the Conservation and Development of Sparsely Populated
Areas department at Strathclyde University, should be a bit more streetwise
about the issue (December 8).
The SNP has long seen a transfer of land and forest resources to the local,
resident population as the essential catalyst to a revitalised countryside. The
Laggan community deserves every public support to set up its pilot project of
local forest management.
But the nation as a whole needs consistent, long-term commitments in such a
policy shift. I hope Mr Fagan will join me in calling for the Scottish Office
to lay down a formula for purchase of forests by local communities along the
lines which agricultural tenants can negotiate to buy their farms.
This could create a price structure far below the Treasury's clawback target on
the sale of public forest assets to private, absentee speculators.
Councillor Rob Gibson,
8 Culcairn Road,
Evanton.
I AM astonished that no-one seems to have realised the main reason why the
Secretary of State is so willing to pass over to community ownership
substantial areas of publicly-owned land such as crofting estates.
This is because it will reduce public expenditure, such as the cost of estates
offices and other landlord costs. In the case of many private landlords their
decision will also be made on the same basis, ie, will it save or cost them
money?
The Government's repeated claim that there is some predetermined level of
public expenditure which is essential to economic prosperity is nonsense.
Part of that expenditure is simply a transfer of money from some people to
others. The other part, related to real goods, services, and investment, is
what matters.
When a large part of the assets built up by this part of public expenditure is
sold off at knock-down prices this is further proof that the Government neither
knows nor cares what are the real values of publicly-owned assets or
publicly-funded services and investment.
Except, of course, when owning these assets costs them money.
G Houston,
Strachur,
Argyll.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951213-000061</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000061</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Real strains that lie behind the Forsyth budget</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Alex Salmond</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974913599</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SECRETARY of State for Scotland or against Scotland, Santa or Scrooge, white
knight or black prince? In six months in office Michael Forsyth has shown
Scotland more faces than a 50p piece.
He was at it again yesterday in a new format for the Scottish Grand Committee
which seems mainly designed to allow him to make a long speech and then have
equal time with everyone else answering questions.
A small tip here for George Robertson. One of the reasons that Forsyth runs
rings around you is that he chooses political battlefields where Labour's
lumbering army are at a disadvantage rather than an advantage.
Another reason is that Forsyth has put the Government machine in Scotland into
gear in a way which his predecessors would have considered slightly offside. Of
course Messrs Younger, Rifkind, and Lang, although gentlemen all, were not
above a bit of politics. We know that from the now-celebrated leaked memo from
Lang to the Prime Minister on March 3, 1992, which revealed that the Scottish
Office income and expenditure statement for Scotland was something he had
``prepared and printed'' as part of ``our campaign to undermine the other
parties''.
This was the forerunner to the statement which Forsyth has been claiming this
year as an ``independent and objective'' exercise. Of course, as one of his
officials confided to me cheerfully yesterday, the difference is that under
Forsyth's Scottish Office such a revealing memo would not have been allowed to
leak!
I am not so sure about that. I have known Michael Forsyth for a long time right
back to St Andrews University - lo even unto the days before he was a
Thatcherite. Since then his public presentation has improved beyond all measure
although occasionally the mask is allowed to slip.
However, then and now his real talent has been for ferocious backroom
organisation. First a determination to pick an opponent's weakness and then
devote all resources to pursuing ruthlessly the point to destruction, and
secondly the iron insistence that everyone else in his team sings from exactly
his song-book - or else.
The first is an impressive talent as his pursuit of the Convention on their
``aunt Sally'' proposal of 3p variation in income tax indicates. However, the
second has brought him into difficulties before and is likely to do so again.
When his tenure as Tory chairman in Scotland ended in total disarray some years
ago the key problem was his inability to persuade all Tories to abandon
independent thought and gear their minds into ``Forsyth speak''. Now the Tories
are more desperate and more malleable. They are unlikely to present any
problems at any level which require to be taken seriously.
But what about the Scottish Office and wider than that? Is it possible to
control every public servant in Scotland and recruit them as cogs in the Tory
propaganda machine?
Some will be easier to recruit than others. MPs were told yesterday that the
Chairman of Scottish Enterprise, Professor Donald Mackay, had effectively
volunteered a #33m cut in his budget.
This story was loyally backed up by Scottish Enterprise but is subject to
serious problems.
First all of the Local Enterprise Companies will have to be carried along with
this merry tale of being able to fulfil their responsibilities within a much
lower budget.
Secondly it seems remarkable that Highland and Island Enterprise seem to have
simultaneously reached an identical conclusion that a budget cut of exactly the
same magnitude was possible.
My guess is that this story of enterprise agencies happily falling on their
financial swords will start to come apart as the year progresses.
And elsewhere the cracks will begin to show or be leaked. The reality is that
the Scottish Office budget is planned to decline in real terms by around 5%
over the next three years or the equivalent of #600m. No amount of sharp
politicking is going to camouflage long the real political strains that result
from that grim reality.
The political appointments in the Scottish Office will be resented by career
civil servants. The problems following spending cuts will start to dominate the
agenda not just in the big losers like housing and industry but also in health
and education where the settlement is less favourable than in England and Wales.
In one of his less-than-inspired moments yesterday Forsyth said that in an
independent Scotland we would all be living in ``mud huts''. This makes an
interesting contrast with his Prime Minister who two weeks ago described the
same constitutional prospect as ``perfectly credible''.
The fact is that in an independent Scotland we could reasonably aspire to the
same standard of living and rate of growth enjoyed by other comparable small
European countries. That is higher than anything which can be expected under
Michael Forsyth.
We would also have the satisfaction of living in a democracy where people not
only choose who should lead the country but where public servants are allowed
to recognise the difference between factual information and political
propaganda.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
