<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951213-000063</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000063</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Missing child Ben `found' in Greece</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913601</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Foreign Office was last night checking a report that British youngster Ben
Needham, who disappeared during a holiday in Greece more than four years ago,
has been found safe and well.
Ben, who would have been six years old two months ago, was found with a gipsy
man who had a history of abduction, according to the Greek TV station Antenna.
The claim was reported in the Daily Mail.
A Greek policeman was quoted as saying: ``A child has been found and it is
believed to be Ben Needham. I don't know exact details at this stage of who
found him, but I think it was a private investigator and police colleagues
believe it is definitely him.''
The blonde youngster went missing at the age of 21 months during a holiday in
July 1991 on the island of Kos with his parents Simon Ward and Kerry Needham of
Sheffield.
A Foreign Office spokesman said: ``So far we have been told nothing by the
Greek police to indicate this report is true but are continuing to look into it.
``Over the years a number of reports of sightings of Ben Needham have been
reported and they have all proved to be inaccurate.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951213-000064</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000064</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>INVESTMENT TRUSTS Dunedin Smaller Companies lifts net asset value</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913602</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A CREDITABLE performance has been turned in by one of the six investment trusts
in the troubled Dunedin Fund Managers' stable.
Net asset value at Dunedin Smaller Companies rose by 11.2% to 350.3p per share
in     the year to October 31, after          a strong performance in the
second half. The #64m trust    out-performed its bench-      mark index. The
FTSE Small Cap index rose by 10.1%, but the more broadly based All-Share index
was 12.9% to the good.
Borrowings were maintained at #5m during the year, and this assisted the
performance of the trust, which was managed by Neill Pirie until the recent
exodus from Dunedin. Stewart Methven has taken over as fund manager.
At the end of the year total investments represented 109% of shareholders'
funds. Recognising the vulnerability of the smallest companies to the slowdown
in activity, Dunedin has reduced the weighting of stocks capitalised at below
#50m from 42% to 26% over the last two years.
It said the dividend income from the trust's portfolio continued to rise, but
earnings per share fell from 8.96p to 7.78p. This was blamed on the profit and
loss account having to bear a full year's interest charge on the borrowings.
A final dividend of 6p means the total for the year will be held at 9p.
n.SLUGGISH Japanese equities and under-investment in the robust US markets
drove Dunedin Worldwide Investment Trust to underperform its benchmark index by
more than 6% in the year to October 31.
The trust, managed by Edinburgh-based Dunedin Fund Managers, saw net assets per
share increase 5% to 877.3p. That compared unfavourably to an 11.2% rise in the
Morgan Stanley Capital International World index, the trust's benchmark.
n.SECURITIES Trust of Scotland has become the latest Martin Currie investment
trust to borrow cheaply in yen to boost its Japanese share portfolio.
The #347m trust has arranged a one-year 2000m yen (#12.8m) loan to boost its
Japanese equities portfolio from 1% to 5% of gross assets.
Last week, Martin Currie's #790m Scottish Eastern Trust borrowed 4650m yen
(#30m) to boost its own Japanese share portfolio.
The yen loan raises Securities Trust of Scotland's gearing to 18% from 16%.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
