<DOCNO>GH951213-000065</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000065</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Lothian Health to offer IVF</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROB ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913603</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LOTHIAN Health is to offer in-vitro fertilisation to childless couples for the
first time.
Directors have agreed that up to #200,000 can be spent next year and the same
amount in 1997/98 to provide three cycles of IVF to about 40 women a year who
meet specified criteria. Thereafter up to #100,000 a year will be available to
provide IVF to about 20 women a year.
The extra money for the first two years is to take account of couples whose
names have been held on file while a review of the board's policy takes place.
Director of public health, Doctor Helen Zealley, explained that IVF was now the
most effective treatment option for approximately half of all subfertile
couples referred for treatment.
A Lothian Health spokesman said it had a list of 50 couples waiting for
treatment but at this stage it was unclear how many of them would be eligible
under the new criteria.
Candidates must be childless, resident in Lothian, and in a stable heterosexual
relationship where the female is not older than 37. They must be subfertile for
three years, or four years where the cause is unknown, and be suitable for IVF
treatment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951213-000066</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000066</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Court slashes libel award</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974913604</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A #350,000 libel victory won by rock superstar Elton John two years ago was
slashed to #75,000 yesterday in a landmark Court of Appeal ruling which is set
to put an end to excessive awards for defamation.
Until now, libel judges and lawyers had been largely barred from mentioning
actual figures to the jury to help them decide how much to award.
But in yesterday's judgment, which has immediate effect, three appeal judges
held that counsel on both sides of a case and the trial judge can put figures
to the jury ``to reflect the upper and lower bounds of a realistic bracket''.
And the jury's attention should be drawn to damages awarded in personal injury
cases, said the Master of the Rolls, Sir Thomas Bingham, sitting with Lords
Justices Neill and Hirst.
``It is in our view offensive to public opinion, and rightly so, that a
defamation plaintiff should recover damages for injury to reputation greater,
perhaps by a significant factor, than if that same plaintiff had been rendered
a helpless cripple or an insensate vegetable,'' he said.
``It serves no public purpose to encourage plaintiffs to regard a successful
libel action, risky though the process undoubtedly is, as a road to untaxed
riches. Nor is it healthy if any legal process fails to command the respect of
lawyer and layman alike, as is regrettably true of the assessment of damages by
libel juries.''
The judges said that mentioning figures, far from developing into an
``auction'', would ``induce a mood of realism on both sides''.
The award to Elton John in November 1993 included #275,000 ``exemplary''
damages to punish the Sunday Mirror for publishing a totally untrue story that
the singer-songwriter was hooked on a bizarre ``diet of death'' which was a
form of the slimmers' disease bulimia.
Jurors accepted his claim that the story was printed recklessly without regard
to the truth and with the main eye on boosting sales of the newspaper for
profit.
But payment of the rarely-awarded punitive damages was suspended pending an
appeal by Mirror Group Newspapers, and yesterday the appeal judges held that
the total award was ``manifestly excessive''.
They cut the exemplary award to #50,000. This, they said, was sufficient to
reflect the gravity of the newspaper's conduct and deter others.
They also reduced the remaining #75,000 compensatory award to #25,000. Although
the article was false, offensive and distressing, it did not attack the star's
personal integrity or damage his reputation as an artist, the court ruled.
The 48-year-old star, said yesterday the case had left him out of pocket.
His legal fees amounted to #160,000 against damages of #75,000, leaving him
with a bill of #85,000.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951213-000067</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000067</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Church urges Macleod to go  on leave</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>LYNNE ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913605</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE prominent Free Church theologian Professor Donald Macleod was last night
strongly urged by his Church to seek paid leave of absence until criminal
proceedings against him had been resolved.
Professor Macleod, 54, of Morningside, Edinburgh, has been charged with six
counts of indecent assault involving five women over an eight-year period. The
case is due to be called again today at Edinburgh Sheriff Court.
A special commission of the Church's general assembly, attended by an estimated
60 ministers and elders, was convened in Edinburgh last night.
After five hours of what appeared to be heated debate behind closed doors at
the headquarters of the Church, the chairman of its natural law advisory
committee, Mr John Sutherland, emerged with a prepared statement.
He said: ``The commission of the assembly strongly advise the Rev Professor
Donald Macleod to seek paid leave of absence and to seek the discharge of his
duties as professor of systematic theology in Free Church College until such
time as the matters that are the subject of criminal proceedings against him
are finally resolved.''
He stressed this was not a disciplinary procedure nor a vote of no confidence
in Professor Macleod, a father of three. ``He has been asked to take leave of
absence with no stigma attached,'' he said.
Mr Sutherland said the assembly still stood by its decision in May when it
cleared Professor Macleod of misconduct and said at that time the matter was
closed.
Asked how much support the eminent theologian had received from the assembly,
Mr Sutherland said: ``I don't think it would be appropriate or in any way
helpful if I were to discuss matters which were held in a private session.''
He said there were bound to be divisions in any Church of democratic society
and said it was vital all aspects were debated.
From his home late last night, Professor Macleod, issued a statement in
response to the decision which said: ``This calls into question my whole
relationship with the Church and leaves me asking is this Christianity?''
He did not attend the meeting personally and was represented by the Rev Alex
MacDonald, of Buccleugh and Greyfriars Free Church.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951213-000068</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000068</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Self-indulgent nonsense</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974913606</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
JACK McLean seems to imply that any donations to the Prince and Princess of
Wales Hospice would go towards keeping Princess Diana in expensive underwear
(December 8). This is a piece of fatuous self-indulgent nonsense.
The work of the staff of the Prince and Princess of Wales Hospice has brought
loving support to hundreds of the dying and their families (including my own)
and Jack McLean's disapproval of the Princess of Wales's lifestyle is no sound
reason for not supporting this and other hospices throughout the city.
The Prince and Princess of Wales Hospice has already had to cut back on
staffing levels and has had to leave unused a fully equipped eight-bedded ward,
ready for more than a year, because it cannot afford to employ the necessary
staff.
Glasgow needs this kind of dedicated service and all the generous support it
can get. If Jack McLean has any real concern for the ``old and dying'' he
should be giving this institution, and similar bodies, his wholehearted support
instead of getting his knickers in a twist over one of the nominal patrons of
the hospice.
Ian McDonald,
147 Nithsdale Road,
Glasgow.
THE Princess of Wales, it seems, is not only ``paranoiac'' but, and this is so
much worse, ``impolitic''.
Her Majesty the Queen, mother of her people, has not found it necessary to make
comments upon the homeless sleeping on the streets in all weathers, which could
imply criticism of a Government led, as we all know, by a man committed to a
classless society.
Of course, there will be those, not only at home, but in the Commonwealth, who
will feel such comment, however impolitic, has some merit. I can hear the
rebellious Aussies saying, ``Good on you, Diana!''.
Martin Baillie,
2 North Park Villas,
Summerlea Road,
Thornliebank,  Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951213-000069</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000069</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Record number of operations</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913607</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HOSPITALS in Scotland carried out a record number of operations last year with
fewer beds but more staff.
According to the Scottish Health Statistics 1995, published today, the total
number of operations, 757,000, was 6% higher in 1994/95 than in the previous
year.
The average available bed complement was 42,351, 1800 less than the previous
year, but average stay dropped from 13.8 days to 13.1 and the number of
in-patients treated rose from 952,256 to 959,921. There were 200 more doctors
and dentists and 100 more nurses.
The total number of patients on the waiting list fell from 82,065 at March 31,
1994 to 79,703 at March 31, 1995.
Lord James Douglas-Hamilton, the Scottish Health Minister, said: ``The NHS in
Scotland is performing well and providing an excellent standard of patient care
for the people of Scotland. The total number of patients treated in hospital
increased by 50,000 in 1994-95, and now stands at a record level. This includes
an additional 43,000 operations.''
The report showed that food poisioning continued to rise, from 3255 cases in
1993 to 4056 last year.
Deaths from heart disease continued their downward trend, while cancer deaths
overall remained stable.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951213-000070</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000070</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Overmanning</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974913608</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ALTHOUGH politicians of all parties and levels profess to be zealous in
spending our tax money wisely they signally fail to consider their own
activities as being poor value for money.
In the US Congress has 435 Representatives and 100 Senators for some 250
million of a population. The European Parliament has 410 MEPs for a population
of over 300 million. The UK Parliament has 652 MPs and untold numbers in the
Lords for under 55 million.
A reduction of 60% or better of the Commons incumbents and the elimination of
the Lords, at least as presently constituted, would result in a considerable
saving when taking in the support cast and backstage workers. More money for
the health service and education, etc?
As far as Scotland goes if we really really must have another layer of
government in Edinburgh, give the jobs to the girls rather than the boys for a
change, no more than 40 to 50 of them, and see if they can show more common
sense.
A C Paton,
Edgeholm,
North Campbell Road,
Innellan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951213-000071</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000071</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>FORUM Prince's call to business</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913609</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Prince of Wales yesterday urged companies to do more to help the community
in countries where they are operating.
He told a gathering of 200 senior business, government and voluntary agency
figures at St James's Palace, ``The greatest challenge for business is to
encourage managers to play an active part in the communities where they are
based.''
This could involve helping with education, employment opportunities, assistance
with delivering health care or strengthening community organisations, he said.
The prince was marking the fifth anniversary of his international trust, the
Prince of Wales Business Leaders Forum, which was founded to promote the role
of business as a partner in the development of emerging and other economies.
The prince said there were many remarkable examples of how co-operation by
business had brought about ``sustained development'' of these communities.
He said support from business had ``snowballed'' and asked his audience: ``Do
we always have to wait for disasters or crises before we recognise the
importance of getting together to address the priorities of sustainable
development?''
And there was a strong business case for companies to become involved in the
communities where they were working.
It should be seen not just as philanthropy, but mainstream business practice.
A recent survey carried out by the forum has found that almost 70% of business
students - tomorrow's managers - believed being involved in communities was an
essential part of modern business practice, he added.
``The real challenge, it seems to me, is for many more companies and many more
partners to become involved, to communicate more widely the ideas which may
have started as experiments, but now seem so much more part of the mainstream.''
It was only through the survival of communities, and the cultural and spiritual
values that they enshrined, that a truly sustainable approach to our existence
on the planet could be achieved.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951213-000072</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000072</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Probation for nurse who put insulin in son's drip</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913610</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A NURSE who gave her ten-year-old son a potentially fatal dose of insulin was
put on probation for three years at the High Court in Glasgow yesterday.
The woman pled guilty last month at the High Court in Edinburgh to two charges
of assaulting the boy, in the family home in Fife and in Edinburgh's Royal
Hospital for Sick Children, by administering insulin to him to his severe
injury and the danger of his life.
She also admitted stealing insulin and syringes from a Fife hospital where she
worked.
The woman was originally charged with attempted murder, but her plea of not
guilty was accepted by the Crown.
The court heard earlier how she put insulin into her epileptic son's drip in
the Edinburgh hospital where doctors were battling to stablise his condition.
She told police the boy, who cannot be named for legal reasons, had begged her
to ``give him a bit of peace''.
However, the judge, Lord Johnston, was told that when the boy recovered he
denied this.
The court heard that the boy suffered an injury at birth which led to epilepsy
at the age of five and that he suffered migraines and would fly into
cataclysmic rage reactions.
Advocate-depute James Campbell told the court that the mother gave colleagues
at her hospital the impression that her son's case was terminal and asked if
insulin could be detected at a post mortem examination.
The boy was taken to hospital in Edinburgh in March this year after his mother
gave him pain killers when he complained of headaches. Doctors at the hospital
discoverd he had a high insulin level.
Later medical staff at the mother's hospital contacted the Edinburgh hospital
to say they saw her with the keys to the drug fridge and with syringes and
ampules of adrenalin.
A doctor checked the boy's condition in hospital and concluded that it was
``fairly possible'' that insulin had been administered to the child in hospital.
The woman told police: ``I didn't try to murder him. I just wanted to do what
he wanted me to do. He just begged me and begged me.
``I love him more than anything else in the world, but I hate to see him
suffering.''
Mr Campbell said that when the boy was admitted to hospital his condition was
``life-threatening''. Without treatment it would have proved fatal or left him
with brain damage.
Mr Gordon Jackson QC, defending, said: `It's difficult for us to understand the
pressure on this woman. It seems clear she simply became mentally ill and had a
breakdown.
``There is no rational explanation for what she did. It appears it was a cry
for help.''
Lord Johnston told the mother yesterday he was ``heartened'' by background and
medical reports.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951213-000073</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000073</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Region loses appeal against racial discrimination ruling</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DUNCAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913611</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
STRATHCLYDE Regional Council has lost its appeal against an industrial
tribunal's ruling that it unfairly sacked an Asian social worker.
Mr Abdur Rashid Zafar was dismissed in 1989 following alleged incidents
involving clients and colleagues.
In April this year, a Glasgow industrial tribunal decided that his dismissal
was unfair. It further ruled that the dismissal was discriminatory on racial
grounds.
The region then appealed against the decision, and the Employment Appeal
Tribunal heard the case last month. It has now issued its findings dismissing
the appeal.
Mr Zafar, 59, from Garnethill, Glasgow, said yesterday: ``I am very pleased
that this seven-year ordeal is over. It is shameful that the biggest local
authority in Europe, which claims to be an equal opportunities employer, should
treat ethnic minorities like this.
``They have wrecked my life. I can not describe how it feels to lose your job
through no fault of your own.''
A regional spokeswoman yesterday confirmed it had received the appeal
tribunal's findings.
The original industrial tribunal hearing of Mr Zafar's case began in September,
1993. His claim of unfair dismissal had the backing of the Commission for
Racial Equality.
The region denied racial discrimination and maintained that he had been sacked
for professional misconduct after allegations made against him by clients and
colleagues.
The industrial tribunal also dealt with several other complaints from Mr Zafar,
including alleged racial discrimination over promotion, but rejected these.
When the region lodged its appeal against the tribunal's ruling on his
dismissal, a tribunal hearing to decide on a remedy - the questions of
reinstatement and compensation - had to be postponed. It is not yet known when
the remedy hearing might take place.
But Pakistan-born Mr Zafar, who spent 20 years in social work in Glasgow, said
yesterday he would be seeking his job back and up to #150,000 in compensation
to cover loss of earnings, pension rights and injury to feelings.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951213-000074</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000074</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Redwood's mission New single currency campaign</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE></BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Leader</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974913612</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE ineffable optimism of some politicians is what makes them sometimes
attractive people or, in Mr John Redwood's case, a downright mystery. Yesterday
he announced his mission to the businessmen by initiating yet another campaign
against the European single currency. He plans to launch a debate inside
British industry on the subject and confidently believes that he can sway
businessmen and persuade them to speak out against a single currency.
There is nothing wrong with a debate; democracy thrives on it and on the
subject of European Monetary Union it would make a welcome change from the
usual hysterical jingoism which has emanated from Mr Redwood's corner.
Businessmen have said often enough in recent months that they would welcome
some reasoned argument on the subject, and also that they are irritated and
worried by the Euro-scepticism which is so prevalent in the Government party
and which they believe is damaging to their business prospects and to the
national interest. Given that the bulk of business leaders consulted by the CBI
have also said clearly that they are not against a single currency and are
opposed to any move to rule it out as an option, Mr Redwood may find his
wide-eyed campaign less than welcome. So be it; he appears to be the sort of
man who learns lessons only by bumping into reality and no doubt his talks with
businessmen will be an enlightening experience, if only for him. But, as we
report elsewhere this morning, the dangers of British isolation on this issue
are growing and should not be underestimated. Senior Tories, including Lord
Howe, Lord Kingsdown, and Sir Leon Brittan warned yesterday that any manifesto
commitment against a single currency would split the party and alienate
businessmen. More importantly for the national interest, it would confirm
Britain's position as a slow-track member of the EU. That must not happen.
</TEXT>
