<DOCNO>GH951213-000075</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000075</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Court told how `ruse' sidestepped FA ban</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913613</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FORMER Scottish international football star Frank McLintock admitted in court
yesterday using a ``ruse'' to get round an antiquated Football Association ban
on payments for agents who recruited players during a deal with England coach
Terry Venables.
The one-time Arsenal and Scotland central defender said he received a fee -
described by another witness as #25,000 - for handling the #2.1m Spurs signing
of ex-Nottingham Forest player Teddy Sheringham.
Mr McLintock said a #50,000 invoice submitted to the White Hart Lane club
deliberately omitted to mention that part of the money was for that purpose. He
claimed many clubs used a similar stratagem.
Mr McLintock was giving evidence at Central London County Court where
advertising executive Jeffrey Fugler is suing Mr Venables's London club Scribes
West for #19,379.88 plus interest allegedly outstanding on a #30,000 bill for a
campaign to recruit members.
The club denies it owes the money and is counterclaiming a similar amount to
take account of the cost of the campaign's failure to stimulate new business.
During the first part of the hearing last month Mr Fugler claimed that Mr
Venables's business partner, Mr Eddie Ashby, showed him a number of bogus
invoices, one of which was from Mr McLintock's sports management company, First
Wave.
Mr McLintock, questioned about the First Wave invoice, agreed with Mr Shane
Dougall, for Mr Fugler, that while the document only referred to ``distribution
and merchandising network'' activities for Spurs, it had been decided to
``lump'' the Sheringham transfer work in with it.
That move, he explained, was so he and his partner would get the ``agreed fee''
that had been asked for.
Mr Dougall: ``Part of that invoice involved negotiating the deal with Mr
Sheringham, and you are getting a fee for that.'' Mr McLintock agreed.
Mr Dougall: ``If one looked at that invoice one couldn't possibly see that. Mr
Sheringham is not mentioned in that invoice.''
Mr McLintock again agreed with him.
The barrister: ``This invoice hides a payment to agents?'' Mr McLintock: ``Yes,
it does.''
Mr Dougall: ``That was a common ruse . . . at the time?'' Mr McLintock replied:
``It is used by a number of clubs, if not most of them, to get past what is
seen as an antiquated law of the Football Association.''
Regarding the so-called ``ruse'', he later told David Farrer QC for Scribes
West: ``The vast majority of clubs do this. It is widely regarded as the thing
to do . . . clubs can pay plumbers or accountants but not agents who could have
worked long and hard for them.''
The trial was adjourned until today, when Mr Venables is expected to give
evidence.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
