<DOCNO>GH951213-000076</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000076</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Father of abandoned `baby nobody' jailed for dreadful abuse of a 14-year-old girl Six years for under-age sex</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BRUCE McKAIN Law Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974913614</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A 14-YEAR-OLD schoolgirl gave birth to a stillborn baby in secret and hid it
overnight under her bed in a plastic bag, a court heard yesterday.
The following day, Christmas Eve, she took the body to a park and abandoned it.
The discovery a week later of the child who became known as ``baby nobody''
sparked off a major police appeal which was solved only after the girl became
pregnant again by the same man and had an abortion.
Yesterday, at the High Court in Edinburgh, Peter Staszek, the 43-year-old man
who got the girl pregnant twice was jailed for six years after he admitted
having unlawful sex with her.
Mr Craig Scott, Advocate-depute, told the court that it was not until December
last year that the girl realised she was pregnant after having sex with the
accused.
``She didn't tell anyone about the pregnancy and wore baggy clothes to school
to conceal the fact.''
The girl also tried to stay with her grandmother as often as possible, but,
just before Christmas, her mother wanted her to go back home.
On December 23 the girl was suffering from a sore back, not feeling well and
stayed off school. Late that night she felt as if she needed to go to the
toilet.
``However, when she did so she had a baby. She describes it as having been
delivered feet first. She picked up the child and indicates that when she did
so the child was dead.
``In due course, with some difficulty, she managed to cut the cord and dealt on
her own with the afterbirth. She placed the body of the baby boy in a carrier
bag, put it under the bed and went back to bed.''
The following day she got up early and, after her mother went out, got dressed,
took the body from under the bed and took it to a park, the Kilns in Dalkeith,
Midlothian, where she placed the bag near a path.
The body was discovered a week later by two young boys who were passing by.
Police launched an appeal for the mother to come forward, and the infant was
buried in a moving ceremony at Newbattle cemetery, Dalkeith.
The Rev Jared Hay, who conducted the service, pleaded with the mother to come
forward, saying: ``We really don't know why we should have to be here to lay in
the cold ground a baby who should be lying warm and cosy with his mother.''
Tbe girl did not tell anyone what had happened and did not see a doctor.
``She simply returned to school and continued with her normal life,'' the
advocate-depute told the court.
About six months later, at the beginning of June, the girl suspected that she
was pregnant again. She had a pregnancy test, which proved positive, after
going to the doctor on the pretext that she had been bitten by a dog.
This time, she told her mother she was expecting and the pregnancy was
terminated on June 19.
Mr Scott added: ``At the hospital the girl told her mother that the baby which
had been found abandoned in a bag at the Kilns was her baby.''
She also revealed that Staszek was the father of both infants and this was
confirmed by DNA tests.
Mr Gordon Jackson QC, defence counsel, told the court that there had never been
any question of force being used and the girl had consented to intercourse.
Like everyone else, the accused had known nothing about the first pregnancy
until it was revealed by the girl.
Mr Jackson said that the girl was now in what could be described as a state of
denial in that she was saying that she had never been pregnant on the first
occasion and that she had made up the story.
However, the scientific evidence proved otherwise.
Jailing Staszek for six years, temporary judge Mr Alexander Wilkinson QC
described the offence as a dreadful abuse of a young girl.
</TEXT>
