<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Appeal Court delay sidelines railway sell-off</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROY ROGERS Industrial Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913615</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
RAIL privatisation was shunted into the sidings yesterday as Appeal Court
judges demanded more time before deciding whether it can proceed or whether the
lengthy passenger franchising process must be started afresh.
Instead of giving their ruling yesterday morning as expected Sir Thomas
Bingham, Master of the Rolls, Lord Justice Waite and Lord Justice Otton,
announced they would not be in a position to give their verdict until Friday.
Labour transport spokesman Mr Brian Wilson described the delay as ``very
hopeful news and a further humiliation for Ministers''.
He added: ``I am sure that pressure will continue to mount for them to scrap
the whole thing.''
The first franchises for passenger services on South West Trains and LTS
(London, Tilbury and Southend) Rail were due to be announced yesterday, but
will now remain under wraps, until next Tuesday at least, after the court
ordered a stay on any signing of contracts.
Whichever side loses the current legal battle is likely to appeal to the House
of Lords for a final ruling.
Campaigners had asked the Appeal Court judges to overturn a High Court ruling
on Friday which cleared franchise director Roger Salmon of accusations that he
unlawfully set minimum passenger service levels at too low a figure.
Mr Justice Macpherson ruled then that Mr Salmon had not acted ``perversely,
irrationally or unfairly''.
But in the Court of Appeal the pressure group Save Our Railways, backed by the
rail unions and more than 20 local authorities, made another attempt to have
the sell-off procedures declared fatally flawed and illegal.
Yesterday Sir Thomas told a packed court that ``having read the papers
overnight and thinking about this matter - and being conscious of the great
public importance of the issue which is raised'' - it would wrong to be
``stampeded'' into giving judgment this morning ``when we none of us feels
ready to do so''.
He said he hoped the reasons for the hesitation would be understood and said
the court now planned to give its full judgment on Friday morning.
SOR is challenging the legality of the franchising proposals for the first
three lines to be sold off - Great Western, South West Trains and LTS Rail - as
well as the next four: InterCity East Coast, Network SouthCentral, Midland Main
Line and Gatwick Express.
Mr Jeremy Sullivan QC, for Mr Salmon, told the judges that by Friday two of the
franchises would have been let, and asked them not to make a stay on any
signing of contracts.
But Sir Thomas directed: ``We think in the circumstances there should be a stay
from taking any action to sign or announce signing of franchises until delivery
of judgment on Friday.''
Outside the court SOR secretary Keith Bill said that the ``very senior judges''
of the Court of Appeal were taking the issue seriously enough to grant a stay
of the franchise signing to give themselves more time to consider.
Two Scottish bus companies - Stagecoach and FirstBus - are front runners for
two of the franchises on offer.
Perth-based Stagecoach is widely tipped to get South West Trains. FirstBus,
which is based in Aberdeen, is part of a consortium bidding for Great Western
Trains, which runs services from Paddington to Wales and the west of England.
</TEXT>
