<DOCNO>GH951213-000078</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000078</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Skye Bridge builders may have just claim</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID ROSS Highland Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913616</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Government is still considering whether to pay an estimated #5m
compensation to the builders of the Skye Bridge.
However, it now appears that the company, Miller/Dywidag, may have a valid
claim.
It was confirmed yesterday that permission to start work on the project came
three months later than expected and a month after the final starting date
agreed with the Scottish Office.
Mr Brian Wilson, Labour's transport spokesman, has tabled a series of
Parliamentary questions calling on the Secretary of State to publish the full
terms of the contract.
He is also to ask the Public Accounts Committee to investigate the public
expenditure involved in the project.
Miller/Dywidag was criticised last summer for seeking compensation on the
grounds that the public inquiry had taken too long.
This meant work planned for the summer was delayed into winter when the weather
and sea conditions were far more difficult.
It was announced on November 28, 1991, that a public inquiry would be held and,
shortly afterwards - on December 16, the Scottish Office signed the contract
with Miller/Dywidag.
The inquiry sat on only nine days between January 28 and February 7, 1992.
Work began on the bridge in July, 1992, despite members of the public still
having a legal period in which to appeal against the project.
A company spokes-man said: ``We expected to start work at the end of March, but
the last possible date was the end of May.''
The Herald understands that the company had always been working to the earlier
date - and the Scottish Office knew that.
Yesterday an official spokesman would only confirm May 30 as an agreed start
date. But even that meant the company started a full month after its ``last
possible start date''.
The Herald also understands that the claim is largely based on delays and not -
as has been suggested by the Scottish Office - on the design changes demanded
by the National Trust.
Mrs Kathleen MacRae, of the Skye Bridge Appeal Group, said yesterday: ``It was
clear that the Government wanted to avoid a public inquiry. Scottish Office
Minister Lord James Douglas-Hamilton said at the beginning of November, 1991,
that the Government expected work to start within six months.
``That's obviously what was agreed with the company the following month.''
``Given the public inquiry and all the complexities of the project, nobody
would have been surprised if they had been talking about a start date of March,
1993.''
</TEXT>
