<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Suicides at Cornton Vale</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974913617</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE director of the Scottish Prison Service and the governor of Cornton Vale
condemned recent media publicity about the prison in the wake of three
suicides. They believed this publicity had been unfair and hurtful to staff who
were working in a caring way with the women.
As the writer of one feature relating to the suicides (February 6), I would
like, in the light of these comments, to raise my own experience, because it is
relevant to the question of what media policy is pursued by the SPS and the
prison itself in order to present a fair picture of the work done with women by
staff.
About two years ago I wished to write features for The Herald, and for a
charity magazine I edit, on the valuable work being developed at Cornton Vale
by the voluntary organisation Apex Scotland in collaboration with staff.
Apex were running courses with the prisoners on employment issues and other
skills valuable to women on release. These were progressive developments with
support and involvement from prison staff, and the feature would have brought
positive publicity to the prison.
I applied through all the proper channels giving written details of my project
and asked if any mutually convenient time could be found. After weeks of delay
I was finally refused permission to visit the prison.
Sarah Nelson,
19 Comely Bank Road,
Edinburgh.
</TEXT>
