<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Housing associations face #2m bill Tax proposal fuels fears of + rent rises</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CALUM MACDONALD</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913618</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EXCLUSIVE THOUSANDS of tenants in homes owned by Scottish housing associations
could face rent rises because of a little-noticed proposal in last
month's Budget, a financial expert warned yesterday.
The move, if ratified by the Scottish Office, would end the associations'
effective exemption from corporation tax and leave them facing annual bills
costing a total of more than #2m.
Mr Mike Blyth, the Scottish managing partner of chartered accountants Kidsons
Impey, said the change would force housing associations to raise their rents,
or put off maintenance on homes.
He said the Budget had abolished corporation tax relief for all associations
which did not have charitable status. Charities remain exempt from such tax
duties.
The decision seems intended to encourage private housing companies into the
rented sector in England and Wales, by giving them a level playing field with
associations.
In Scotland, non-charitable associations have traditionally received a full
reimbursement of any corporation tax from the Scottish Office, via funding
agency Scottish Homes. The total repaid in 1993/4 was #1.75m, and #2.5m in
1994/5.
About three-quarters of the 200 associations in Scotland, which have about
70,000 tenants, are non-charitable. Their individual annual bills are thought
to range up to #150,000.
However, Mr Blyth said it was now expected that relief would be reduced to
zero, in line with England and Wales.
He pointed out that any surpluses made by associations tended to be invested in
essential upgrading work, such as window replacement or kitchen improvements.
In addition, many had recently undertaken large transfers of whole housing
estates, involving thousands of homes, which had been planned and financed on
the assumption that corporation tax relief would be remain in place.
Mr Blyth said: ``The effects of the 1995 Budget will be felt by the housing
association sector for many years to come. The associations affected will be
forced either to put up rents or forego improvements to their properties.
``The Chancellor has adopted a back-door method to save cash by taking away
grant aid that was extremely important to the majority of housing associations
in this country.
``For many tenants, this move will, almost certainly, more than offset the
personal tax reductions offered in the Chancellor's speech.''
Mr David Orr, the director of the Scottish Federation of Housing Associations,
said: ``This proposal is a body blow to Scottish housing associations and has
no justification.
``The changes are being introduced as a consequence of proposed legislation in
England and Wales which will not apply to Scotland."
A spokeswoman for the Scottish Office said yesterday: ``We are still
considering what the most appropriate solution for Scotland would be. There is
no decision yet.''
</TEXT>
