<DOCNO>GH951213-000081</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000081</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Minimal wages do not work</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974913619</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I AM hardly surprised at the letter from Hugh Craigie Halkett on the minimum
wage issue (December 8).
It is the usual line taken by managing directors - screw wages down, employ
workers part-time on starvation rates, spew forth specious figures about
unemployment in other countries.
Government unemployment figures are improving, but they are just figures and
without substance.
If you have 16 hours' work, you are fully employed. If a man loses a skilled
job at #400 a week and his wife gets a job at some check-out earning a
take-home pay of little more than #30 a week, one job has been lost, one job
has been gained. Unemployment figures would have it that there is no change.
Positions as security guards have been on offer at Ayr Job Centre at #1.80 per
hour and a 72-hour week. How can anyone buy a house or a car or even a pair of
shoes on a wage like that?
Can Conservatives not see that every unemployed person is a customer lost to
every shop in the High Street, one who cannot afford to buy British-made goods
if he buys at all?
James W McHardy,
18 The Holm,
Cumnock.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951213-000082</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000082</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Woman weeps at sentence</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913620</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A MOTHER of two young children broke down and wept yesterday as a judge told
her she must be jailed for drugs offences.
Lord Hamilton told Susan Bartraham: ``If I were to take a light view I would be
failing in my public duty to take steps to discourage a trade which has caused
so much misery and so much death to a wide number of people.''
Bartraham, 34, a first offender, was convicted at the High Court in Glasgow of
being concerned in the supply of heroin and Temazepam at her home in Liddesdale
Pass, Milton, Glasgow, between March and June last year.
The court was told that Bartraham, who looks after her disabled mother and
grandmother, was paid to keep the drugs at her house over a two-week period.
Lord Hamilton deferred sentence to obtain background reports and said yesterday
at the High Court in Edinburgh that the case had caused him considerable
concern.
He accepted that Bartraham, who has two young daughters, looked after her
family and had never been in trouble before.
The judge added: ``However, you have committed crimes of which this court must
take a very serious view.
Lord Hamilton jailed Bartraham for 18 months and also ruled that #900 found in
the house should be forfeited.
</TEXT>
