<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Institute proposes `fortune accounts' Report unveils alternative to welfare state</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By IAIN WILSON Chief Reporter</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913621</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE right-wing Adam Smith Institute will unveil its successor to state welfare
today in the form of the right to opt-out from state pension and social
security contributions.
People should be free to save into personal, privately-run ``fortune accounts''
designed to provide lifetime insurance and basic pension benefits, according to
authors Eamonn Butler and Madsen Pirie.
Their report argues:
.q.The current pay-as-you-go pension system is not only financially unsound but
``a precarious chain letter''. In effect, today's ``taxpayers are funding
today's pensioners in the hope future taxpapers will in turn fund them.''
.q.The benefits' system is shaped more by the power of vested interest groups
than by actuarial realities. Its impersonal nature not only makes
``contributors resent paying for others but encourages fraud because the
benefits are seen as other people's money''.
The institute is adamant the only way out of the ``pathology'' of the welfare
state is to replace the collective, politicised system with one based on the
so-called fortune accounts.
These would bear the names of individuals, be privately-managed, and provide
savings for retirement and insurance for lifetime needs.
The report declares: ``By contributing a part of their income into their own
account, people will accumulate savings when young, fit, and in work, in order
to fund their needs in retirement or when unempoyed, sick, or disabled.''
It adds that instead of trying and failing to be an insurance company, the
Government would be restricted ``to the purely welfare function of topping up
the accounts of those who cannot afford to contribute themselves''.
The free market institute also proposes extending the funding principle to
social security as well as pensions; regards personal savings ``as a
replacement rather than supplement to the welfare state,'' and wants
individuals' funds managed by competing private providers rather than by the
state.
Citing examples from Chile and Singapore, the authors stress accounts would be
the property of individuals. As such, they could not be eroded by politicians
changing the rules, and people would have less incentive to defraud the system.
Labour's depute Shadow Scottish Secretary John McFall said last night the
institute wanted no state responsibility whatsoever for its citizens. That was
unacceptable, and he added: ``The proposals may be OK for a minority, but for
the majority would increase pecuniary.''
Mr McFall spoke of people being plunged into trouble because of personal
pension arrangements. Although it was acceptable for people to make personal
provisions, there had to be a public-private mix so that everyone was protected.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951213-000084</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000084</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Alcohol warnings diluted New drink limits fuel health row</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ALAN MacDERMID Medical Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913622</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HEALTH Secretary Stephen Dorrell was accused of mixing his messages yesterday
when he issued new guidelines seen as encouraging people to drink more.
Although it follows expert advice that moderate alcohol consumption can have
health benefits, his announcement was attacked as untimely because of the
efforts being directed against drinking and driving during the festive season.
He has effectively raised the maximum safe drinking levels recommended by the
Government by a third in the case of men and a half in the case of women.
However, Mr Dorrell's decision to serve up the new limits as a daily ration
instead of a weekly total went down smoothly with most critics, since they help
to emphasise the danger of binge drinking.
The new guidelines, developed after consultations with doctors' groups, advise
that men can drink up to four units of alcohol a day without suffering harm,
while women could have up to three units a day.
Until now the upper limits were 21 units a week for men and 14 for women - one
unit of alcohol is a half-pint of normal strength beer or one glass of wine,
although these equivalents become less meaningful when applied to high-strength
beers or to the alcoholic fruit drinks whose use by young people has become a
cause for concern.
The new recommended levels come with publication of a report by an
inter-departmental working group which examined drinking limits.
The report throws in an extra dash of controversy by suggesting that some
teetotallers should take up drinking for its beneficial effects, although Mr
Dorrell watered this down by refusing to recommend it personally.
The notion that a little of what you fancy does you good is based on the effect
of alcohol in dilating the blood vessels - thereby protecting against heart
attacks or strokes - and the observation that moderate drinkers have a lower
mortality than total abstainers, even allowing for those who have given up due
to ill-health.
Daily consumption of one to two units of alcohol ``gives a significant health
benefit,'' reducing heart disease for men over 40 and post-menopausal women,
according to the report.
Mr Dorrell said: ``Alcohol consumption will always be a major public health
issue and it is important for the Government to present a balanced view which
recognises the risks of alcohol but also offers soundly-based and credible
advice on which people can base their own choices.''
The report made very clear that excessive drinking carried significant and
growing health risks, he added. It also showed the need to target specific
messages at different groups of the population, such as pregnant women and
young people.
Transport Minister Steven Norris said the Government's advice on drinking and
driving remained the same: don't drink at all.
Professor Paul Wallace, of the Royal College of General Practitioners, insisted
the new limits were not a green light for heavy drinking. The move from weekly
to daily limits reflected the fact that occasional binge drinking was more
dangerous than regular moderate intake.
The report was also welcomed by Mr Douglas Allsop, director of the Scottish
Council on Alcohol, who said: ``It is not aimed at problem drinkers or people
who are abusing alcohol, but the general population who drink for pleasure and
enjoy it.''
The shift to a daily limit was welcomed by Ms Belinda Lindon, nursing adviser
to the British Heart Foundation, who
also accepted the safety of the new limits.
However, the British Medical Association chairman, Dr Sandy Macara, said:
``Whatever the intention of the Government, relaxing the sensible drinking
limits a week after the launch of the Christmas drink-driving campaign is both
irresponsible and badly timed. The confusing message about daily as opposed to
weekly limits is unhelpful and will be misunderstood and misinterpreted by the
public.''
The alcohol adviser to the World Health Organisation, Dr Peter Anderson, also
condemned the new drinking limits. ``The basic message that the World Health
Organisation is saying in relation to alcohol is that less is better,'' he told
BBC Radio 4's World at One.
He added: ``In my opinion, the scientific evidence would show that if you are
drinking at those levels of alcohol consumption, you are very likely to put
your health at risk.''
Dr Adrian Carr, head of Law, Health and Social Administration, at Bell College,
Hamilton, and an expert on alcohol-related issues, said most people who drank
regularly were already drinking on the limit or above.
``I would take issue with encouraging people to drink,'' he said.
Shadow Health Secretary Harriet Harman criticised the Government for issuing
mixed messages. ``His priority ought not to be to tell people to drink more but
to deal with young people getting drunk, the link between drink and crime and
the still major problem of drinking and driving,'' she said.
Professor Philip Graham, chairman of the Royal College of Physicians and
British Paediatric Association working party on alcohol and the young, pointed
out that relaxing the limits had been opposed earlier this year by three of the
medical Royal Colleges.
Their report document, Alcohol and the Heart in Perspective, ``made it
absolutely clear'' that relaxing the sensible limits guidelines for alcohol
would have detrimental effects on individual risks, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951213-000085</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000085</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Amec dismisses its PR firm</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANDREW WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913623</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SOUR note has been introduced into the Kvaerner takeover bid for Amec with
highly regarded public relations firm Financial Dynamics being sacked by the
British company after criticism from the Takeover Panel.
The Norwegian shipbuilding and engineering group had brought in the panel after
press articles appeared over the weekend of December 2-3. These implied that
Amec was about to produce 1996 profit forecasts which were higher than in the
current range of analysts estimates.
The panel said that there had been a conversation between a Financial Dynamics
director and a member of a securities house unconnected with either Amec or
Kvaerner about Amec's profits for 1996 and also contents of the defence
document that were not due to be released for several days.
This breach of the takeover code whereby information must be released to all
shareholders at the same time resulted in two press articles appearing to the
effect that Amec would achieve pre-tax profits in 1996 of about #35m.
In the event, Amec has made only a turnover forecast and said that it was
inappropriate to make one for 1996 profits.
The panel said that Financial Dynamics had failed to take sufficient care in
its discussions with analysts which resulted in serious breaches of the code.
It has been replaced by Dewe Rogerson, best known for privatisation issues.
n.KVAERNER bought the Provident Mutual Life holding of 4.91 million Amec shares
yesterday at the 100p bid price to raise its holding from 20.14% to 22.56%.
The offer closes next Monday but it seems likely that the outcome should be
decided by tomorrow night.
</TEXT>
