<DOCNO>GH951213-000086</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000086</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Scottish Amicable backs bid for Forte catering empire</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANDREW WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913624</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH Amicable Investment Management has thrown its weight behind Granada in
its #3300m hostile bid for the Forte hotels and catering empire.
Last night, chief executive officer Douglas Ferrans said it had been a backer
of Granada's chief executive Gerry Robinson since 1991 and had done very well.
Like him, SAIM believed in cash flow generation and the takeover would create
significant shareholder value. ``It's a cracking deal at this price,'' he said.
Some six million Forte shares and four-and-a-half million Granada are managed
on behalf of clients.
Earlier, Mr Robinson said he had ``very serious doubts'' that Forte had put in
place many of the sales announced since the beginning of the #3300m bid.
But he added that he accepted two things. One was that bankers had been
appointed to sell Travelodge and the other that the 78-strong White Hart hotel
chain had been open to bids.
However, he said Forte should stop the disposals until the end of the bid as it
was against shareholders interests.
Mr Robinson was speaking after yesterday's extraordinary meeting called to
approve the issue of new shares and change the borrowings limit.
That was passed with 40% of shareholders voting in favour and just 0.4% against
- many institutions did not vote on what was a foregone conclusion. Of the 30
or so shareholders and larger number of advisers present, only two voted
against the motion on a show of hands.
Forte revealed in the afternoon that it had sold a hotel in Liege and another
in Majorca for #2.2m as well as offering the Polygon site in Southampton which
has planning permission for offices.
Granada has already complained to the Takeover Panel about the Forte sales
programme but as yet the panel has taken no action.
Mr Robinson, who said he was ``avoiding the temptation'' of sending a Christmas
card to Sir Rocco Forte, charged that the image of Forte as an international
hotel company was belied by the reality.
The Post House chain had been significantly underinvested and some hotels were
in very poor order indeed, while the Little Chef brand was very tired and had
older customers, he said. Under Granada management, he added, he would
introduce fast food in about 100 outlets.
There is no chance of a change of mind on the Savoy which both groups are now
pledged to sell. Forte has a 68% stake which it has used to make management
changes.
Mr Robinson pointed out that in a recent poll, the Savoy had been the only
hotels group to show lower acceptance levels by users. ``I don't think Charlie
(Lord) Forte would have been happy with that.'' He added that sort of trophy
asset did not rest easily in a plc.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951213-000087</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000087</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Bankers rake in #600,000 bonuses</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913625</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MEMBERS of a leading City investment bank yesterday heard they are to receive
bonuses of about #600,000 each.
The 33 London partners of American-owned Goldman Sachs and 20 other key staff
are understood to be in line for the bonus payments on top of their basic
salaries.
Staff at Morgan Stanley, another US investment bank, were also told how much
they would receive in annual bonuses.
The bumper payouts follow an excellent year for investment banks after a record
level of takeover business in the US and Europe which has generated enormous
fees for advisers.
Rising share prices through the year on worldwide stock markets have also
provided a big boost for the major City players such as Goldman.
Goldman said it was not company policy to comment on staff bonuses.
In the UK, takeovers have dominated headlines of the business press throughout
the year. Towering above them all was the #9000m acquisition of drugs group
Wellcome by its bigger rival Glaxo - a record sum for a UK takeover.
In the banking sector, Lloyds was making news with its #1800m takeover of the
Cheltenham &amp; Gloucester Building Society and more recently, its proposed #5900m
acquisition of TSB.
The landscape of the electricity industry has changed out of all recognition
over recent months as a result of takeovers within the sector, an acquisition
by an American power company and successful bids from two privatised water
companies.
The generous bonus payouts are still below the level in 1993 when about 70
London executives at Goldman Sachs earned $1m (about #653,000) each in
performance-related pay.
Administrative and support staff received a bonus of 30% of basic salary in
1993 against 8% in 1994 and 20% for this year.
A spokeswoman for Morgan Stanley said: ``Bonuses paid will be better than in
1994 although not at the same level as in 1993 and reflect improved market
conditions and the upturn in the industry and a tremendous effort by our staff
this year.''
</TEXT>
