<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951213-000088</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000088</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Let battle commence</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>business comment</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974913626</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TOMORROW will be a crucial day for BT as it will hear the decision of the
Monopolies and Mergers Commission (MMC) over who should bear the cost of
enabling a consumer to retain an existing number when switching to another
telephony provider.
BT had argued that it was the proprietor of the number and should not have to
pay. The regulator, Don Cruickshank, thought otherwise. When the two cannot
agree on a matter of this sort the MMC has to decide.
BT will be examining the MMC ruling carefully, as if it is favourable to it, or
at least not totally in support of Mr Cruickshank, it will be emboldened to
force another more important issue to the MMC.
This relates to Mr Cruickshank's proposal for a lighter regulatory regime when
it comes up for renewal in 1977. In exchange for allowing BT greater freedom
over pricing, he wants wider authority to stamp on what he sees as
anti-competitive practices as soon as they arise. He feels the present
licensing framework is too rule-bound.
With technology changing so fast rules are out of date by the time they are
written and are complex to the extent of being incomprehensible to anyone but
an expert.
BT certainly likes the idea of having greater pricing freedom but is fearful of
having a regulator with a roving brief. So the issue is likely to end up with
the MMC.
More immediately there is the problem of interconnection charges, the fees
competitors have to pay BT to deliver calls via its network. Then there are
figures relating to interconnect charges for overseas calls into foreign
networks. So Oftel is busy - hyperactive BT would no doubt say.
For domestic consumers the arguments are esoteric and even Mr Cruickshank
accepts that it will take a long time before competitors make major inroads
into BT's market share in this area.
As in the case of mobile phones, he foresees a period of confusion before
comparison between competitors' tariffs and conditions become clearer. He will
be doing his bit by publishing audited figures on quality of service and, in
conjunction with the Consumers' Association, will give details of call charges
to enable comparisons to be made more easily.
Hot property
BRITISH Land is pushing hard on the heels of Britain's biggest property
company, Land Securities, in terms of size and seems certain to provide a more
rewarding dividend flow over the next few years.
Admittedly, there are few surprises in the half-time results after the
announcement last month of the #223m rights issue to buy the outstanding 50% of
the massive Broadgate office development in the City for #120m from the
receiver of Rosehaugh, but that deal means British Land is now the biggest
owner of `A' quality property in the Square Mile.
Chairman John Ritblat has been gearing it up, and after the Broadgate deal has
been completed some 80% of the #4500m portfolio will be less than seven years
old. The implications for future revenue are, therefore, highly favourable
enabling it to reduce its cover to help boost dividends, as it will require
relatively low retentions.
Interim gross rental income leapt 30.6% to #109m, which after sharply higher
interest charges - these rose #19.5m to #63.4m - left the pre-tax total just
5.1% ahead at #24.9m. The dividend is 5.3% higher at 2.78p.
Gearing is probably around 130%. But as the shortage of prime quality property
pushes up capital values, it will fall quite sharply. The company is
renegotiating its loan book at a time of low interest rates.
Future rental income growth is further assured through the recent purchase of
three Scottish retail parks and seven more Tesco supermarkets.
The full-year results will be scrutinised very carefully for the net asset
value which may hold about steady at 420p, with the expectation that it could
rise to about 480p a year later.
The shares closed 6p easier at 368p where they stand at an attractive 13%
discount to net asset value for 1995-96 and almost 25% for the year to March
1997.
Property is not the most popular sector, but this is a stock which should prove
more dependable than most - and a return to inflation would be an added bonus.
Sensible view
THE Greenbury report and proposals on executive pay and perks not surprisingly
upset a number of the so-called fat cats in business who did so much to sour
the scene, particularly over privatisations.
In fact, Sir Richard and his committee had rather expected to be criticised for
being too soft. In the event, while this did happen, there has also been a
distinct campaign to undermine their findings using a variety of arguments.
Interestingly Lord Young, late of Cable &amp; Wireless before being sacked and
currently seeking considerable compensation, who remains president of the
Institute of Directors, has been particularly scathing.
But now Tim Melville-Ross, the IoD's director-general and a member of the
Greenbury Committee, has launched a fierce counter attack against attempts to
block or tinker with individual recommendations of the report which, he claims,
would undermine its overall effectiveness.
Mr Melville-Ross argues that the committee spent a long time trying to get the
balance right. And while not every member agreed with every detailed
recommendation, they all subscribed to the whole.
The result, he maintains, should be recognised for what it is - an important
step forward and a bulwark against wholly unacceptable legislation.
Addressing the Institute of Chartered Secretaries and Administrators' dinner at
the Guildhall, he called upon companies to take the high ground in responding
to Greenbury by setting performance measurements and reward systems, using
disclosure of their benefits, and making managers into owners.
He also called for a change of culture surrounding boardroom pay. As with other
investments, investment in executive pay should be scrutinised to maximise the
return, he believes.
Mr Melville contends that we need to develop a view that business is not just
about relatively short-term financial performance, but rather long-term
shareholder gain, which requires other measures of performance than the purely
financial to be taken into account.
Better corporate behaviour at the top will create a new climate and new
standards helpful to all kinds and sizes of business, he concludes.
His views are rugged and sensible and, hopefully, will take precedence over the
growing carping and sniping at Greenbury.
</TEXT>
