<DOCNO>GH951213-000089</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000089</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>BoS International moves into corporate lending</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KRISTY DORSEY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913627</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BANK of Scotland is continuing to expand its business base in Australia, this
time in corporate finance.
Its recently established Australian subsidiary BoS International (Australia) is
raising A$750m (#360m) in commercial paper and medium-term notes to set itself
up in the corporate loans business.
The financing package is unconnected with the Bank of Scotland's #437m purchase
of Bank of Western Australia (BankWest) which was completed last month.
BankWest is a retail bank with an extensive branch network, whereas BoS
International handles only large corporate deals.
BoS International has given a mandate to Sydney-based Westpac Banking Corp to
arrange the issue of commercial paper and medium-term notes, thought to be the
first combined deal of this nature in Australia.
Robin Browning, a general manager at Bank of Scotland in Edinburgh, said BoS
would use the proceeds to fund other subsidiaries in Australia such as Scottish
Pacific Business Finance and Capital Corporate Finance.
``In a way, it's sort of a treasury operation in the Bank of Scotland groups,''
Mr Browning said. ``The A$750m is just an additional souce of income to that
which BoS has already raised itself.''
BoS was formed six months ago to take deposits from Australian banks and
companies and arrange large corporate loans.
Bank of Scotland is unconditionally guaranteeing its financial obligations
under the A$750m programme.
Reports that Capital Corporate Finance plans to spend A$200m (#96m) on a Sydney
headquarters for its Asia-Pacific region are premature, Mr Browning said.
There was no firm commitment to spending that amount and such a development
would be ``at least five years down the road'', he said. It would depend on how
quickly Bank of Scotland's Asian operations grew, he added.
</TEXT>
