<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951213-000090</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000090</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Bundesbank may hold rates to avoid political taint</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913628</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Frankfurt, Tuesday - The Bundesbank is unlikely to succumb to intense political
pressure and reduce official interest rates on Thursday, but a cut to put its
key indicator on track for the new year cannot be ruled out.
Economists said the central bank could accompany a review of its main policy
guide, M3 money supply, with an interest rate cut designed to boost lending and
help M3 grow at a faster clip, invigorating worryingly sluggish economic growth.
But many economists believe the Bundesbank is more likely to delay a reduction
by several weeks, in order to avoid the impression that it was bowing to
escalating political pressure at home and abroad.
The Bundesbank last reduced its discount and Lombard rates by 50 basis points
or half-a-percentage point each, in August in response to weak M3 growth. The
discount rate is now at 3.5% and the Lombard 5.5%.
The central bank's credibility rests in large part on financial market
conviction that its interest rate decisions are designed to keep medium-term
inflation pressures, reflected in M3, in check and thereby protect the mark's
value.
German consumer price inflation was unchanged in November from October and up
1.7% year-on-year.
The Bundesbank argues that moderate inflation and low long-term interest rates
are its best contribution to fostering economic growth. Market fears that it
would tolerate inflation to boost short-term growth would do more damage than
good.
But news last week that German economic growth had ground to a halt in the
third quarter fuelled fears for the economy next year and prompted
unprecedented calls from leading economic institutes and from politicians for a
reduction.
Yesterday, Oskar Lafon-taine, leader of the opposition Social Democratic Party,
led a chorus of calls urging the Bundesbank to cut rates to spur investment and
job creation.
However, economists played down hopes of an immediate cut.
``I see the chances now as fewer than 50% that a reduction will come this
week,'' said Thomas Mayer, economist at Goldman Sachs in Frankfurt.
``The pressure has grown enormously in Germany because of the economy . . . and
in the past the Bundesbank has always defended itself against views it was
responding to the economy (with a rate move,)'' Mayer said.
Economists noted that Bundesbank president Hans Tietmeyer has said that
monetary policy can do little to jump-start the economy at this point, given
already low rates. In addition, the Bundesbank may fear an interest rate cut
now might awaken speculation it was helping out its neighbour France, and
smoothing the path to this week's crucial European Union summit. France has
been hit by escalating strikes, as the government tightens its budgetary belt
to ensure that the country meets the criteria for a future single European
currency that are likely to be made concrete at the Madrid EU summit.
Gerhard Grebe, economist at Bank Julius Baer in Frankfurt, said the Bundesbank
would want to ensure that any rate cut was not seen as greasing the route for
other nations to participate in Europe's single currency project. Mr Tietmeyer
has said that each nation must keep its own fiscal house in order.
The Bundesbank and Germany have also been in the vanguard of the movement to
make sure nations adhere to strict criteria before they may be allowed to join
in the single currency.
Nonetheless, many econo-mists do see a rate cut within the next several weeks
or months. - Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951213-000091</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000091</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Burns festival faces cash crisis</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID STEELE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913629</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EXCLUSIVE
THE Burns International Festival is facing a cash crisis and may have to be
radically pruned or even cancelled if more funding cannot be found.
Local authorities, enterprise companies and other funding bodies already
contributing more than #250,000 are to be urged to take a ``leap of faith'' and
come up with around #175,000 more to save the festival, established to mark the
bicentenary of the bard's death.
Festival director John Struthers will be seeking backing from as yet untapped
sources such as Strathclyde region and the Scottish Tourist Board.
It is also understood that the Scottish Office may be asked to assist the
festival, which is facing a serious shortfall because of the reluctance of
commercial sponsors to sign up and the fact that European funding is dependent
on an equal amount of funding being in place.
On the day that the festival announced its initial programme for the ``birthday
season'' - starting in less than three weeks and lasting until May - it emerged
that board members have been warned of serious financial difficulties.
The news is a further damaging blow to the festival company which is running
out of time to secure sponsors for the 12-month programme of events.
Since The Herald disclosed problems within the festival organisation earlier
this year, there has been a series of incidents which have combined to weaken
faith in the festival and embarrass the organisers.
Chairman Eric Rowe left his wife and family to live in England, the day after
helping patron the Princess Royal to launch the festival in Kilmarnock. And top
performers Kiri Te Kanawa, Billy Connolly, and Runrig said they were not
properly consulted prior to being bandied about as potential participants.
Ms Te Kanawa's personal manager Nick Grace said: ``We were approached about
becoming involved. We wanted to know more but there were no further approaches
from the organisers.''
Runrig may yet appear, if the Centrum arena can be completed in time,
increasingly unlikely since owner Mr Bill Barr is still awaiting lottery cash
towards the project.
Meanwhile, there are worries among the local Burns fraternity that the festival
is merely riding piggy back on events which would have gone on anyway.
Sources point to the fact that following the cancellation of the world's
biggest Burns Supper, to be broadcast worldwide by satellite, the festival has
``linked up'' with the 10-year-old Westsound Burns Supper.
Mr Sam Gaw, world president of the Burns Federation, said: ``It is
disappointing to note that some of the events put forward as festival events
are in fact already organised.''
Mr Struthers said: ``We were always in existence to provide a catalyst and to
promote and support events. There is nothing wrong with the fact that some of
the events in the festival programme are not solely the work of the festival
organisers.''
Best laid schemes - Page 13
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951213-000092</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000092</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Compass sets course</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Nicola Reeves</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913630</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
COMPASS, the largest European-owned catering group, has sold its healthcare
division to its management for #178.8m, which is dependent on the level of net
assets prior to completion, writes NICOLA REEVES.
The bulk of the purchase price, just under #171m, will be paid in cash with the
remainder in a secured loan. Finance for the management buy-out was provided by
CINVen.
Compass Healthcare provides a range of healthcare services in the UK. It
operates 15 private hospitals offering acute surgical and medical care, two
nursing homes and a healthcare screening business. In the year to October 1,
1995, it made an operating profit of #15.8m on turnover of #69.7m. The net
asset value of the division was #128.8m.
The disposal was expected given the strong international growth of Compass's
catering business. Last year, Compass's sales were #1505.8m of which #1436.1m
was derived from catering and related activities. The proceeds of the disposal
will be used to reduce borrowings incurred following Compass's acquisition of
the catering group Eurest for #580m in September.
Group chief executive Francis Mackay said the disposal was ``a natural
extension'' of Compass's long-standing strategy of focusing on the development
of its core international catering operations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951213-000093</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000093</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Contracts for roads</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By LYNNE ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913631</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FIVE-year contracts to maintain Scotland's trunk road network have been awarded
to three local authority consortia.
Scottish Roads Minister Lord James Douglas-Hamilton yesterday described the
council bids as ``very good value for money'' and said they had been successful
in an open competition for the work.
The winning bids were submitted by the Tay Local Authority Consortium for the
Tay Premium Unit roads; the Forth Local Authority consortium for the Forth
Premium Unit and the Clyde Local Authority Consortium for the Clyde Premium
Unit.
The contracts will become effective on April 1, following local government
reorganisation.
The roads are currently maintained by regional councils under agency agreements
with the Secretary of State.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951213-000094</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000094</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Britain heads back to the drawing board</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Nicola Reeves</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974913632</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Tory Party is keen that Britain should be seen as the enterprise economy of
Europe. Therefore it will no doubt enthusiastically support Project Business
(UK), launched by the charity Young Enterprise earlier this week.
Indeed Lord Henley, the Education and Employment minister said he was confident
that it would prove to be attractive to teachers and students and would
establish itself in schools and colleges.
The project aims to introduce 14-16 year old students to the world of business
and economics in an exciting and innovative way. It forms a close working
partnership between education and business, involving business volunteers
working with teachers, both in their classrooms and in their companies.
In recent years there have been concerns expressed about the relevance of much
of what is learned in school. The rapid pace of technological change has
heightened such concerns. Project Business (UK) will be particularly welcomed
by those interested in promoting vocational education.
Just as work placements are meant to provide students with an idea of how they
might have to apply their skills in the workplace, so Project Business is meant
to give students practical experience in the form of a business or works visit
and through structured classroom sessions, an insight into the different
aspects of British business. Issues covered in the programme include the role
of the consumer, advertising and the workings of the market economy.
Currently funding of #250 is needed to support each Project Business (UK)
class, typically involving a partner, a teacher and 25 students. The money goes
towards the partners' manuals, student workbooks, training, local support and
registration. Funding may be provided by the business partners' company or
other local agencies.
Companies supporting the programme include Unilever, W H Smith and GEC. The
Department for Education and Employment contributed towards the initial pilot
project and co-sponsored the extended pilot. Next month a similar pilot project
begins in Scotland.
More and more people are recognising the usefulness of closer links between
schools and businesses. Nine out of ten young people are now thought to take
part in work experience before they leave school. Over 90% of secondary schools
have links with local businesses and over 170,000 teachers have had placements
in business since 1989.
Educational programmes such as Projects Business (UK), given at a young age,
are needed now more than ever given the breakdown of the traditional labour
market and the subsequent increase in self-employment and flexible working.
Teachers as much as pupils need to understand the changing needs of business
and industry so that they can be better equipped to meet those needs.
Small firms are the key to future employment growth and provide a more amenable
working environment for many people, particularly women trying to balance the
demands of work and family life.
Skills which can help young people to successfully set up and run their own
business are useful at a time when increasing numbers of graduates are leaving
school and universities only to find that there are not enough jobs to go round.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951213-000095</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000095</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Hanson planning sell offs</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913633</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TRADING prospects for the medium and long term were very good, industrial
conglomerate Hanson announced yesterday.
In the group's annual report, chairman Lord Hanson said that while a softening
in several parts of the UK economy was having an impact on some of its UK
businesses, the US remained vigorous.
He believed the group's future growth and development lay in chemicals,
consumer products, energy, building materials and equipment businesses. It also
intended to concentrate on fewer, larger interests and sell a number of
businesses.
``The year to come will see further corporate activity substantially to reduce
debt and deliver value to shareholders,'' added Lord Hanson.
The annual report shows Lord Hanson's pay packet inched ahead in the year to
September 30 to #1,374,000 from #1,362,000 in the previous 12 months.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951213-000096</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000096</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>9.5% pay cut looms at HarperCollins</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM TINNING</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913634</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ABOUT 350 workers at the HarperCollins' book manufacturing plant at
Bishopbriggs, near Glasgow, looks set to accept a 9.5% wage cut and a
compensation package rather than face losing their jobs.
The workers had been told that the plant would close on Friday unless they
accepted a deal by 5pm today.
However, The Herald understands the deadline has been extended until Friday at
1pm for workers to accept the proposals put forward on Monday by Mr Chris
Hardie, the prospective owner of the manufacturing plant, and Mr Eddie Bell,
HarperCollins's executive chairman.
The company has agreed to offer an 18-month compensation package which would be
worth between #2000 and #3000 per person before tax and which would be payable
on January 5 if the 9.5% wage cut is accepted.
Staff previously unanimously rejected a 25% wage cut proposed by Mr Hardie, the
owner of a small Berwick-based company, Martins the Printers, which employs 30
people.
It is understood that union legal advisers have warned workers that they would
have problems in winning unfair dismissal claims if they were paid off.
HarperCollins has also warned that the Government minimum redundancy package
would be paid in the event of closure.
No-one from HarperCollins or the Graphic, Paper and Media Union, which
represents most of the workers, was available for comment last night.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951213-000097</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000097</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>HIV doctor seeks a return to surgery</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALAN MacDERMID Medical Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913635</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BPROFESSOR George Browning, the ear, nose and throat surgeon who was found to
have the HIV virus almost a year ago, has asked to be allowed to resume
operating on patients.
Professor Browning, who is based at Glasgow Royal Infirmary, said last night
that the type of surgery he performed was recognised as relatively low-risk.
He is a specialist in what is virtually keyhole surgery inside the ear, using
instruments manipulated by remote control.
Three months after the diagnosis last Christmas Professor Browning returned to
work, but did not resume operating on patients. He has held out-patient clinics
and continues to teach at Glasgow University.
He has now asked a Department of Health advisory committee, which looks at
cases of doctors with HIV or other potientially dangerous infections or risk
factors, to look at his case.
``They have said they will consider it, and that is as far as it has gone,'' he
said.
Professor Browning added: ``My patients have been very positive, and a number
of those for whom I have recommended surgery have said they would be willing to
have me operate on them.''
After he had recovered from the illness that led to the infection being
detected, he had been encouraged to return to work.
``I am now keeping very good health, the waiting lists are going up, and I have
a skill to offer which people might want to use.''
</TEXT>
