<DOCNO>GH951213-000098</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000098</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Kirk inquiry ends with suspension</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913636</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A CAMPBELTOWN congregation of the Church of Scotland has been declared to be in
``an unsatisfactory state'' and its minister has been suspended after an
investigation.
The Presbytery of South Argyll made the decision at a special meeting on Monday
because of a breakdown in relations between the Rev Donald Lawrie and members
of his Highland congregation.
Mr Lawrie was inducted to the Campbeltown Highland parish four years ago as his
first ministry. He will be appealing against the judgment to the judicial
commission of the General Assembly.
Mr Lawrie, who declined to comment yesterday, will continue to receive his
salary for an unspecified period whether or not his appeal is successful. The
affairs of the congregation will be administered meantime by a minister
appointed by the presbytery.
Insiders of the South Argyll Presbytery say they had been expecting such an
outcome.
Some blamed the Kirk, which cut the number of churches in Campbeltown and made
it inevitable that Mr Lawrie's workload would involve him in requests for
services from those who were not practising Christians.
Others cite Mr Lawrie's attitude to baptism and marriage. He  is understood to
have inflexible views.
</TEXT>
