<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951213-000099</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000099</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>MP's death adds to Tory troubles</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By STUART TROTTER Political Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974913637</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Government's prospect of staying in office until April 1997 suffered a
further blow yesterday with the death of Sir David Lightbown, MP for South-east
Staffordshire.
The MP, who was 63, suffered a heart attack while attending the
Oxford-Cambridge university rugby match at Twickenham.
His death cuts the Government majority in the Commons to five over all other
parties and Labour looks well-placed to win the by-election. His winning margin
over Labour at the last election was 7192 which, in the current climate of
opinion, looks highly vulnerable.
With another by-election pending in the safe Labour seat of Hemsworth, two
Labour victories would cut Mr Major's majority back to three. Actuarial
calculations indicate that the Prime Minister will be fortunate to face no
other by-elections before April 1997 when the present Parliament ends.
Conservative spokesmen pointed out that the Government habitually enjoys the
support in important votes of Sir Richard Body, the MP for Holland with Boston
in Lincolnshire, who resigned the Tory whip over Europe.
The Prime Minister expressed his shock and sadness at the sudden death of Sir
David who until recently had been a formidable member of the Government's team
of whips.
A massive man whose bulk could be overpowering, he was nicknamed the Terminator
because of his uncompromising approach to Tory rebels. He played a leading role
in keeping many doubting MPs in line during the voting on the Maastricht Treaty
Bill.
Mr Greg Knight, the deputy chief Government whip, said: ``I am very upset. He
was a whip par excellence and also a great character. Although the press
reported many stories of his strong-arm tactics I don't think anyone he cajoled
didn't have increased respect for him.''
Commons Leader Tony Newton said Sir David was ``a great Parliamentary character
who will be missed on both sides of the House''.
Sir David put on about a stone in weight to his already formidable 17 stones
after leaving the whips office last summer.
He was elected an MP in 1983 after a career in local politics and joined the
whips office in 1986. He is survived by his wife Ann.
A by-election in the neighbouring Mid Staffordshire constituency halfway
through the last Parliament resulted in a resounding Labour victory against an
even larger Tory majority. However, the Conservatives recaptured the seat at
the 1992 General Election.
Party sources were putting a brave face on the by-election prospects saying
they expected to continue putting their legislation through the Commons
``without difficulty''.
But the party failed to win any seats up in last May's local elections for
Tamworth borough council which covers the largest part of the constituency.
They also lost 16 seats and forfeited control to Labour in Lichfield district
council part of which is in the constituency. The Conservatives have not won a
by-election since Richmond in Yorkshire in February 1989.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951213-000100</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000100</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Lottery `bribe' pressure mounts</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974913638</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PRESSURE was mounting last night for Heritage Secretary Virginia Bottomley to
take action over beleaguered National Lottery watchdog chief Peter Davis and
for lottery firm GTech to ``sue or shut up'' in response to a bribery
allegation.
Labour said Mr Davis, director general of Oflot, had put his position ``in
question'' by admitting that he took free flights from GTech, a major investor
in lottery operator Camelot.
And Virgin tycoon Richard Branson challenged GTech to ``let the courts decide''
the truth of his claim that he was offered a bribe by the American firm's
chairman.
But Mrs Bottomley said she would wait for a full committee report - which may
not be delivered until March - before making any decision about Mr Davis's
position.
And GTech said it would not be hurried into a decision over legal action.
Shadow Heritage Secretary Jack Cunningham said Mr Davis compromised his
position by taking flights in GTech private jets and is writing to Mrs
Bottomley asking what action she plans to take.
Mr Davis, who said his decision to fly in GTech private jets saved taxpayers'
money, was keeping a low profile yesterday after his admission to a Commons
committee.
Mr Davis is taking legal advice over the allegations made by Mr Branson in
Monday's Panorama programme. The Virgin boss claimed he had informed Mr Davis
of the bribe allegedly offered by Mr Guy Snowden, chief of GTech, which has a
22% stake in lottery operator Camelot.
Oflot insisted that the claim that Mr Branson told Mr Davis ``was untrue''. Mr
Snowden has already vehemently rejected the ``grossly defamatory and totally
untrue'' bribery allegation and said he was ``reviewing legal options''.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
