<DOCNO>GH951213-000101</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000101</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Electricity companies announce new batch of job losses as cost cutting continues ScottishPower sacks 350 at Manweb</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBERT POWELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913639</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISHPOWER plans to sack a further 350 staff at its English subsidiary
Manweb over the next 12 months, in addition to 1000 laid off by Manweb's former
management earlier this year.
The axe will fall hardest on administrative staff at Manweb's headquarters in
Chester which will be moved to smaller premises.
ScottishPower is determined to streamline the management of the company which
it acquired two months ago in a hostile #1130m takeover bid.
The financial implications of the latest job cuts, which will reduce Manweb's
workforce to about 3000, will be spelt out next month.
``We thought it was important to give our employees an early indication of the
transition team's findings,'' said ScottishPower chief executive Ian Robinson.
``We are currently finalising our detailed plans and it remains our intention
to make full presentation of these in mid-January.''
ScottishPower hinted that in the longer term there could be even more job
losses at Manweb. The company referred to ``an initial reduction in the next 12
months of about 350 jobs,'' implying further cuts might follow.
The company has, meanwhile, made a better-than-expected #27m profit from the
sale of Manweb's 4.8% stake in National Grid, the high-voltage power
transmission network serving England and Wales.
It valued Manweb's holding in the grid at #141m when it launched a takeover bid
for the power company serving Merseyside and North Wales in July. But it sold
the stake for #168m when National Grid was floated on the Stock Exchange on
Monday.
ScottishPower achieved a price of 208p per share, a whisker less than the
National Grid's closing price of 209!sp on its first day of trade.
Some City analysts had said ScottishPower, which sold its shares in a joint
offering with North West Water, would be lucky to get 200p.
The #27m profit on the sale will reduce ScottishPower's debt gearing more
rapidly than anticipated.
Gearing soared to more than 100% when the Glasgow-based company bought Manweb
in October. It was due to come down to 75% by the end of the financial year in
March, but the windfall gain could reduce it to about 60% by then.
But the City ignored the cost reductions that will flow from the job cuts and
the shares windfall. ScottishPower shares closed down 2p at 365p in line with
the generally weaker trend in electricity stocks.
ScottishPower welcomed a decision by Professor Stephen Littlechild, the
industry regulator, to lift price caps on electricity sold into the English and
Welsh pool.
Two years ago National Power and PowerGen voluntarily undertook to cap the
price at which they sell power into the pool which, in turn, sells electricity
to the 12 regional electricity companies in England and Wales.
But Professor Littlechild said yesterday pool prices had remained comfortably
below the ceilings set. He, therefore, saw no reason to maintain the
restrictions, particularly since National Power and PowerGen are selling off
6000 megawatts of their generating capacity - a move that will increase
competition.
ScottishPower will derive marginal benefit from this since it supplies less
than 1.5% of all power sold into the pool. Even so, a company spokesman said:
``Anything that removes artificial constraints on the wholesale market is to be
welcomed.''
ScottishPower and Scottish Hydro-Electric should be able to sell more
electricity south of the Border in two years time, once the capacity of the
inter-connector power line to England is upgraded to 2200 megawatts from its
present 1200.
</TEXT>
