<DOCNO>GH951213-000102</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000102</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Team formed to tender for missile</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By IAN BRUCE Defence Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913640</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A GROUP of more than 100 British companies has been formed, under the
leadership of the US Hughes electronics and aircraft corporation, to
co-ordinate a bid for a new air-launched missile which will give the Royal Air
Force stealth capability at bargain prices.
The group, known as Team Airhawk, includes Hughes   Microelectronics Europa
Ltd, of Glenrothes, Fife, which has already gained a #2m contract to supply
test equipment and other parts for the UK version of the Tomahawk cruise
missile.
The deal with the Scottish firm marks the first production work on the missile
outside North America. HMEL has a workforce of 700 and an order book worth #60m
in the current year.
The Airhawk will be designed as an entirely British modification of the
missiles which struck targets in Iraq during the Gulf War and more recently
were used to bombard the Bosnian Serbs.
The consortium has been set up in response to a Defence Ministry invitation to
tender for a conventionally-armed, precision-guided missile capable of being
launched from aircraft at ranges of up to 400 miles from target.
Mr Stephen McElroy, director of the Airhawk programme, said last night: ``This
value-for-money weapon will give the RAF's strike aircraft the same
survivability as stealth aircraft with smart munitions. The Airhawk can be
launched beyond the reach of air defences, allowing aircraft and crews to avoid
the risk of being shot down over their targets.''
Meanwhile, orders for Scottish-based electronics companies dropped for the
first time in five years in the quarter leading up to December, according to
figures released by Scottish Engineering, the employers' federation.
Mr Howard Jordan, SE's chief executive, said last night: ``Even during the
worst downturn of the early 90s, the electronic sector was a solid standby. The
only heartening thing is that although companies are reporting a drop in
orders, there has been no corresponding drop in production.''
.q.Motorola is to shed 500 of the 3000 jobs at its Livingston plant, it was
claimed last night.
The move is understood to affect mainly part-time workers and is seen as a
response to the sudden fragility of the semi-conductor market. Nobody from
Motorola could be contacted for comment.
</TEXT>
