<DOCNO>GH951213-000103</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000103</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Northern earnings slip lower</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Christopher Sims</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913641</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NORTHERN Electric revealed further heavy job losses as it reported a small fall
in profits and confirmed its special 56.5p dividend to be paid in February
1997, writes CHRISTOPHER SIMS.
Up to 800 jobs are expected to go by the end of the decade as the group
continues to cut costs. The move follows the #500m package for shareholders in
the ``scorched earth'' defence against the bid from Trafalgar House, which
started off the auction of the English regional electricity companies.
Northern's profits dipped #4.7m to #58.7m in the six months to September owing
to the one-off costs of the defence package, a property disposal in 1994 and
higher financing costs. The job losses are expected to be through natural
wastage.
The group re-affirmed its intention to pay current year dividends totalling
39.9p and an interim of 12p, up 7%, is declared. Its intention is to grow
dividends by 7% a year until 1999 or the year 2000, subject to maintaining
satisfactory dividend cover.
This implies an underlying trading improvement if the group is to overcome the
higher financing charges which will result from its gearing up to pay for the
shareholders' package, at a time of increasing competition in the industry.
Chairman David Morris said it had made further progress in cutting costs, with
operating costs down almost 10% in real terms. He added: ``Our policy of
maximising shareholder value will remain absolute while we continue to manage
the business in an increasingly competitive market place.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951213-000104</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000104</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Pilots clear the path to peace</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974913642</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE two French airmen shot down and held captive by the Bosnian Serbs for more
than 100 days flew home to a heroes' welcome yesterday, clearing the way for a
peace ceremony to end the conflict.
President Jacques Chirac and Defence Minister Charles Millon greeted Captain
Frederic Chiffot and Lieutenant Jose Souvignet at an air base near Paris.
They were flown from Serbia in the plane of the chief of staff of the French
armed forces.
Their return followed French threats of action against their captors. The peace
treaty, formally ending the war in Bosnia, should now be signed in Paris
tomorrow.
After meeting their families, and before heading for Paris for a medical
check-up, they told reporters they ``felt fine''.
The two men were shot down on August 30, following Nato air raids against the
Bosnian Serbs. The men, who had not been seen in public since their Mirage 2000
was blown out of the sky near the Bosnian Serb stronghold of Pale, were handed
over to France's armed forces chief at the Bosnian-Serbian border.
They were handed over by Bosnian Serb military commander General Ratko Mladic.
He told them he wished them ``a fast recovery . . . and I wish you to be pilots
again but for planes of peace''.
They were flown from the border town of Zvornik to Belgrade and then on to
Paris.
``I was treated quite well as you can see,'' Lieutenant Souvignet said in
Zvornik. ``I had some pain in my leg but they had very good doctors.''
Both suffered leg injuries when they baled out of their fighter jet after it
was hit by the Bosnian Serb missile.
There had been speculation that General Mladic and Bosnian Serb leader Radovan
Karadzic held the airmen either to press for changes in the Bosnia peace
agreement or as an insurance policy against their arrest for war crimes.
France denied there had been any deal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951213-000105</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000105</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Retailers enjoy Christmas boom</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By CRAIG WATSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913643</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CITY centre retailers across Scotland have reported buoyant sales in the run up
to Christmas. Edinburgh is likely to have its best ever festive sales figure
and in Glasgow takings are up by almost a third in some outlets.
Mr Chris Blake, chairman of the Edinburgh Chamber of Commerce retail group,
said: ``After a fairly slow autumn season it's now coming good. It could be our
best Christmas ever, given the way things are going at the moment.''
He said extended shopping hours, Sunday trading and a full weekend before
Christmas Day would contribute further to the surge.
Glasgow Chamber of Commerce and the Glasgow City Centre Association (GCCA) have
carried out an informal survey of retailers. The results, released yesterday,
showed that sales levels were either ``well above'' or ``just above'' the same
period last year.
Dundee city centre manager Gordon Reid said informal discussions with managers
from the big stores showed a ``consistently high level of performance''.
Mr John Michie, treasurer of the Aberdeen City Centre Association and board
member of the city chamber of commerce, said he was optimistic that it would
prove to be a successful year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951213-000106</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000106</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Thriving hotels division on lookout for acquisitions as casino income drops slightly Stakis checks in higher profits</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>NICOLA REEVES</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974913644</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE hotel industry has been set alight by Granada's recent hostile bid for
Forte.
Whoever emerges victorious, the likely fallout from the bid is being closely
monitored by others in the industry, including Stakis which is on the lookout
for more provincial hotel acquisitions.
However, it is not prepared to pay what it deems to be high prices - which is
why it did not buy the Copthorne chain recently sold to the Singapore-based CDL
Hotels group.
Stakis itself is confident of growing its hotels business by another 20% in the
next two years. In 1995 it was active in the development of the business,
adding 615 rooms to its portfolio, including 74 in East Kilbride, taking the
total to just under 5000.
A combination of increased occupancy, up 2.4% to 72.1%, and higher room rates,
up 5.5% to just under #44.00, enabled the hotels division to increase its
profits by 26.5% to #31.2m. Margins, at 29.9%, were just short of the company's
30% target.
Chief executive David Michels said the group had the highest provincial
occupancy and margins in the UK. He attributed this to good locations,
well-refurbished units and good marketing.
In contrast, profitability in the casinos division slipped by 7%, or #800,000,
to #11.7m. New units in Bournemouth and the Isle of Man made higher profits but
the rest of the business declined. A number of factors were cited for this,
among them competition from the National Lottery, the introduction of guest
charges, since withdrawn, and a drop in the average spend of its 1000 biggest
customers. The hot summer is also likely to have reduced attendance.
The board is confident increased promotional activity, the withdrawal of guest
charges, and the creation of attractive purpose-built casinos in more appealing
locations, such as the Riverboat Casino on the Clyde in Glasgow, will benefit
the business in the year ahead.
Mr Michels also called for a level playing field for all gambling vis-a-vis the
National Lottery and for a change to what he described as ``archaic
legislation''.
Given a free market, he said casino attendance in the UK, currently at 2% of
the population, would rise closer to the 30% seen in the US. He added the group
had ``strong faith in the casino business for the future''.
In January, a White Paper on the casino industry is due to be published by the
Government.
Despite the active capital programme, the balance sheet remains strong. Free
cashflow at the year-end was #21.2m.
Generation of such cash is seen as a major driver of future growth in the
business, together with the addition of features such as leisure clubs and more
bedrooms. Capital expenditure of around #23m has been pencilled in for the
hotel division next year with #18m to be spent on extensions.
Overall group profits grew by 28% to #25.8m before tax. Chairman Richard
Cole-Hamilton said it was ``a very good set of figures''. However, Stakis
shares dipped 3p to 79p.
FACT FILE
Final 1995 1994
Turnover #173.4m #145.9m
Pre-tax profit #25.8m #20.2m
EPS 4.93p 4.27p
Dividend 1.75p 1.55p
</TEXT>
