<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951213-000107</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000107</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>US trade picture improves in the third quarter</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913645</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE US trade picture improved last quarter as the current account deficit
narrowed by nearly 9% to $39.5bn.
The Commerce Department said the deficit dropped as US exports of goods and
services rose, while imports fell.
The current account is the broadest-based of all government's trade statistics
since it covers investments as well as trade in goods and services.
In the second quarter, the deficit was $43.3bn, just shy of the record set in
the final three months of last year.
Much of last quarter's improvement came in merchandise trade, a chronic weak
point for the United States.
The department said the merchandise trade deficit - basically the shortfall
between exports and imports of goods - fell to $43.4bn in the third quarter
from $48.8bn in the second.
Analysts said US companies have become more competitive on world markets as
they have pruned staff and spent money on computers and other capital equipment.
However, in a sign of potential trouble ahead, the Commerce Department said the
US deficit on investment income widened to $4200m in the third quarter from
$2600m in the second.
For many years, the United States had run a surplus in that area, as it earned
more money on its investment abroad than foreigners did on theirs in America.
But the huge increase in the US budget deficit in the 1980s turned the United
States into a net debtor nation, so that it now owes more abroad than it takes
in. - Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951213-000108</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000108</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Vaux calls time on 41 public houses</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANDREW WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974913646</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ON the day that Whitbread Inns forecast the disappearance of 5000 pubs out of a
UK total of 58,000 by the year 2005, regional brewer Vaux came out with figures
which added hard evidence, writes ANDREW WILSON.
The north east of England company has been victim of the closure of the Durham
coalfields as well as Calais-based illegal imports.
In recent years, it has unknowingly added to its problems by buying tenancies
where the incumbents cannot afford to upgrade their properties to meet the
competition from brewer backed managed houses at a time when beer volumes are
declining and there is alternative uses for disposable income such as the
inexcrable scratchcard. So Vaux is now switching over to managed houses and
spending more on upgrading, particularly on good sites to attract substantial
volumes.
As a result, 41 pubs were either sold or closed last year with another 41 to
share the same fate this time round to reduce the total to about 750 outlets
while over a two year period, about 70 will be transferred into management.
That had helped restrain the increase in group pre-tax profits last year to
8.7% at #31.8m with tenancies producing #1.5m less at #14.6m. However half that
was recouped in Vaux Inns.
Brewing and wholesaling managed a slight gain with a lower volume of commodity
brewing for Tesco.
The star performance came from Swallow Hotels with profits up by a quarter at
#19.7m. That was helped by higher occupancy at 67.8% and a 12% greater yield
thanks to the brand being seen as offering good four star value. The impetus
came from the London properties helped by burgeoning tourism with turnover
growth double that in the Scottish hotels.
St Andrews nursing homes, which saw two more Scottish openings in Arbroath and
Dundee, were held back by higher front end costs and leasing charges - but that
is simply prudent accounting. Demography is onside as the aged population grows.
Conservative accounting also led to a #12.1m reduction in the valuation of the
pub estate and so Vaux is unlikely to give any nasty shocks on the property
front.
The dividend total has been raised 3.6% to 10.2p with a 6.75p final for a 5%
yield with the shares down 12p at 252p.
FACT FILE
Final         1994-95        1993-94
Turnover  #259m          #254m
Pre-tax profit  #31.8m        #29.3m
EPS            17.9p          16.3p
Dividend    10.2p           9.85p
</TEXT>
