<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951213-000109</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000109</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Village battles    to keep cross</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913647</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
VILLAGERS battling to keep an ancient Celtic cross in the village where it has
stood for 1000 years took their fight to a public inquiry yesterday.
The Dupplin Cross, which overlooks the village of Forteviot in Perthshire, was
erected to celebrate the union of the Scots and the Picts in the ninth century.
The cross is one of the finest early Christian crosses in Scotland and features
intricate Latin script.
Villagers and experts are agreed that the cross, which has become badly eroded,
should be moved indoors but the two camps disagree on an appropriate site for
the stone.
The National Museums of Scotland wants the cross to be the centrepiece of the
new National Museum in Edinburgh but villagers, who have formed the Friends of
the Dupplin Cross action group, say the stone should stay as close as possible
to its original location.
Yesterday, Lord Forteviot, the chairman of the Dupplin Trust, which owns the
cross, told the inquiry that to move the ancient stone to the National Museum
was the only way the safeguard its future.
He said: ``It was obvious to me that the condition of the cross has been
deteriorating for some time and that this deterioration appeared to be
accelerating.''
He added: ``I understand the feelings of those opposed to moving the cross to
Edinburgh and my initial instinct as a local person also is to share these
feelings.
``But the transfer of ownership of the cross to the National Museums of
Scotland provides a permanent arrangement for preserving the cross and ensuring
that it will be kept safe and available for public display in perpetuity.''
National Museums of Scotland curator Dr Mike Spearman told the inquiry that the
cost of moving was expected to be #56,000 and that National Museums of Scotland
was prepared to spend a further #16,000 on a replica cross to be placed on the
site of the original.
But the Friends of the Dupplin Cross maintain that the ancient sculpture should
remain as close as possible to the original site. They want the cross to be
housed in Forteviot church where, they say, it could become a tourist
attraction and a focal point for worship.
The action group has enlisted the support of Historic Scotland and has formed
an alternative plan to house the cross in St Serf's church in Dunning.
The group and Historic Scotland are expected to give evidence to the inquiry
today.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951213-000110</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000110</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Water capping branded a `fraud'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By FRANCES HORSBURGH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913648</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH Secretary Michael Forsyth's plan to cap water charges next year was
yesterday branded an elaborate fraud by the Labour Party.
Shadow Scottish Secretary George Robertson said it was becoming clear that the
price that would be paid for lower water charges would be cuts in council
services and increases in council tax.
As the Herald exclusively revealed last month, Mr Forsyth plans to cap
increases by the three new public authorities at an average of 6% next year.
Although the water authorities will take control of the council-run services
next April, the new unitary council authorities will still be responsible for
sending out water bills and for ensuring the charges are collected.
They will be paid for the service by the water authorities.
In a letter to Mr Forsyth, Mr Robertson claims the capping can only be achieved
if some of the administrative costs for billing and collection are passed to
the new unitary councils.
He asks Mr Forsyth: ``Will you confirm that instead of compensating Scotland's
council's in full for the administrative costs of this service, you propose to
limit the amount of money they receive - thereby passing some of the costs on
to local tax payers?''
Mr Robertson is also seeking confirmation that the price cap could not be
achieved but for the fact that councils will be obliged to meet any shortfall
created by non payment of water charges.
Last night the Scottish Office confirmed that a maximum charge by councils to
the water authorities of 4% of the amount collected had been proposed in a
consultation paper.
A spokesman said delayed payment and non-payment had also been taken into
account in a formula produced after working discussions with Cosla.
</TEXT>
