<HEADLINE>Yugoslav states kick war into touch</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913649</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LAST month they were embroiled in war, last night former Yugoslav states were
drawing up battle plans for victory on the football field.
The 1998 World Cup final sections put Bosnia, Croatia, and Slovenia, three of
the five separate states from the now fractured Yugoslav republic, in the same
group.
But Bosnian trainer Faruk Hadzibegic said: ``We're just happy to play in the
World Cup. The fact that we play Croatia and Slovenia changes nothing. In fact,
it's a pleasure.
``We will play with the whole Bosnian people behind us thinking only of victory
and not of politics.''
Marko Ilesic, vice-president of Slovenian federation said: ``I don't think
there will be much interference from politics in the group and we're guaranteed
big crowds.''
Scotland face Sweden, who beat them in a friendly earlier this season, as well
as Austria, and another three of the former Soviet Union sides, Belarus and the
Baltic states of Estonia and Latvia in a six-team group.
In soccer rivalry terms, there could have been little more dramatic than Italy
and England meeting in a tough group which also includes Poland, Georgia and
Moldova.
Only group winners are certain to qualify for the World Cup finals in France in
1998.
Italy, three times winners and finalists last year, and England, champions in
1966, met in the third place playoff at the Italian World Cup in 1990 when
Italy won 1-0.
Italian coach Arrigo Sacchi said: ``Our group is very hard. England and Poland
are very good teams. England have strong players but I hope Italy will be
stronger and finish first.''
In a World Cup draw which threw up a number of interesting clashes between
European neighbours, Belgium appeared in the same group as the Netherlands and
the Czech Republic were drawn against Slovakia.
</TEXT>
