<HEADLINE>Nablus makes most of early handover</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974913652</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Nablus, Tuesday
LOUDSPEAKERS played the once-outlawed Palestinian national anthem, ``Biladi''
(My Country), throughout the city. Palestinian flags waved everywhere.
Thousands danced in the streets in their pyjamas, in the rain.
Residents of Nablus, in the West Bank, said the day Israeli troops left after
28 years of occupation was the happiest day of their lives.
``We heard the redeployment started so we rushed out of our houses to go and
watch the celebrations. We never felt happier than today,'' said Sahar
Istetiyeh, a 40-year-old teacher, standing in the chilly rain in her nightgown.
The fact the Israelis left suddenly last night, 48 hours before they were
scheduled to redeploy under a peace deal with the PLO, threw the city into a
state of delighted confusion.
The Palestinian police force that was supposed to take over security from the
Israelis wasn't there yet. City leaders improvised, deploying municipal police
to maintain order in the interval.
The Israelis had been gone for hours and the streets were already crowded with
revellers when people started to decorate the city with colourful lights and
banners prepared for the handover.
``I was surprised when I heard on the loudspeakers and the streets they had
already redeployed,'' said Abdel Rahim al-Maani, 46. ``I immediately put on my
scarf and went out in the cold and it was drizzling and despite the rain and
the cold I went out to join the people in this historic moment.
``It was like a dream, a dream come true,'' he said.
Evacuated offices of the military government drew crowds who wished to see them
empty of the signs of occupation. Former prisoners hugged and kissed in the
empty rooms of the military court and prisons.
Abu Dalal al-Afghani toured the evacuated prison building and said: ``I spent
12 years in this prison, but being here today means that every wound that bled
in this place has healed now, since our land which we fought for is back with
us.''-Reuter.
</TEXT>
