<HEADLINE>The one thing everyone agrees on about new alcohol consumption guidelines is they were announced on wrong date Calling time on inept decision</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANNE JOHNSTONE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph graph table</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974913653</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Relaxing the sensible drinking limits a week after the launch of the Christmas
drink driving campaign is both irresponsible and badly timed            BMA
chairman Dr Sandy Macara
SOMEONE should give the Government a lesson in timing. The week before the
booziest fortnight of the year and the week after launching a #1m anti drink
driving campaign, HMG has seen fit to put out a message which at first sight
looks like a green light for heavy drinking. It even contains an exhortation to
abstainers to think about taking up drinking on health grounds.
``Wrong message, bad timing'' read the stark headline on the British Medical
Association's statement in response to the news that the Department of Health
is to raise the recommended maximimum alcohol intake limits. ``Relaxing the
sensible drinking limits a week after the launch of the Christmas drink driving
campaign is both irresponsible and badly timed,'' said BMA chairman Dr Sandy
Macara.
Mr Mark Bennett, spokesman for the lobby group Alcohol Concern, said: ``Nobody
thinks they're drinking too much. A lot of people will think they are being
given the green light to drink more this Christmas.'' His argument is that
encouraging moderate drinking risks sending the wrong message to heavy
drinkers, especially during the ``season of good cheer''.
Even those who welcome the new guidelines believe the timing of the
announcement is inept to say the least. Mr Douglas Allsop, executive director
of the Scottish Council on Alcohol, said the statement reflected a growing
recognition that the old limits were simply not credible but added: ``Perhaps
they would have been better to delay this until January.''
So what does Health Minister Stephen Dorrell think he is up to? Those keen on
conspiracy theories will be quick to accuse the Department of Health of caving
in under pressure from the enormously powerful drinks industry, aided and
abetted by the Treasury. The key statistic here is the #6000m a year the
Government collects from taxes on alcohol. An extra loud ring from the till of
every off-licence and pub this Christmas would suit the agenda of a tax-cutting
Government very nicely thank you.
In fact, yesterday's announcement is the culmination of a long and careful
weighing up of not only the various risks associated with alcohol abuse but
also the health benefits linked with of moderate alcohol consumption. The key
word here is ``moderate''.
Many studies have shown that drinking a small amount can reduce the risk of
heart attacks in older men and post-menopausal women. For example, in one
American study, 340 heart attack victims were questioned and compared with a
control group. Those who consumed one to three units of alcohol per day had
half the heart attack risk of those who never drank.
Other studies have shown a similar daily intake might also offer limited
protection from strokes, gallstones, and some types of diabetes. However,
consuming more than three drinks per day did not appear to lower the risk
further.
``After a certain point, there's an increasing problem that you're buying
protection against cardio-vascular disease at the cost of something else -
neurological damage, cancer of the oesophagus, social damage, accidents at
work, for example,'' said Mr John Davies, professor of psychology at
Strathclyde University.
Since 1987, the Government has chosen to place that point at 21 units a week
for men and 14 units for women. A unit equals approximately half a pint of
beer, a single measure of spirits, or a glass of wine.
Mr Davies believed any so-called ``safe'' limit was false ``because everyone
assumes that if you stay below it you are totally safe''.
Mr Douglas Allsop, of the Scottish Council on Alcohol, said there had always
been ``an amber area'' between the so-called ``safe'' drinking limit - 21 units
for men and 14 for women - and the Government's other limit, the so-called
``dangerous'' drinking limit of 50 units a week for men and 35 for women. The
council uses the traffic lights analogy with the 21 to 50 area for men and 14
to 35 zone for women, classed as amber or ``a sliding scale into danger''. The
new guidelines of 28 units for men and 21 for women simply make the amber area
a bit smaller.
In fact, yesterday's statement gives more recognition to the idea of a sliding
scale of harm than its predecessors. The maximum health advantage will come
from consuming one to two alcohol units a day. Three to four for a man, or two
to three for a woman, are not accompanied by big health risks.
The more units piled on on top of that, the more danger there is to your
health. Yesterday, groups like Alcohol Concern welcomed the care with which the
Depertment of Health and its advisors had weighed up the pros and cons on the
basis of scientific evidence but expressed doubts that new guidelines could be
reduced to a simple and effective health education message.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
