<DOCNO>GH951213-000116</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000116</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Director urges investment in education</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS HOLME</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913654</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
RELAXATION of the Government's recommended safe drinking limits was given a
mixed reception last night.
Mr Penny Richardson, director of the Edinburgh and Lothian Council on Alcohol,
said: ``We are slightly puzzled at the message being put out. There is this
relaxation on one hand but on the other the various royal medical colleges are
still advocating the lower limits.
``The move to a daily limit is helpful but we would like to see a matching
investment in health promotion and education, and funding for the councils on
alcohol.
``The central message should always be that whatever and whenever you take,
don't mix alcohol with other drugs, machinery, or when you are driving or
working.''
Actor and broadcaster Iain Agnew sees the issue from both sides. He appears as
a fearsome clan chief in one of the new television commercials aiming to win a
younger market for whisky, but also hears the darker side of drink when he has
to fend off the occasional late-night callers who have had one too many on his
Scot FM phone-in programme.
``I have always been of the opinion that a glass of red wine certainly does no
harm. It is so good for you'' he said. ``The same applies to whisky. But there
is nothing more boring than a drunk on air, thinking they are entertaining the
audience but they are not. I just try to make sure they don't get on air.''
Mr Ronald Gow, assistant director the CBI Scotland, said attitudes to alcohol
among companies had shifted considerably in recent years.
``I don't think anybody in industry is trying to change the social habits of a
country but there has been a move away from alcohol as part of a move towards
promoting good health. We encourage employers to take a holistic approach to
their employees' health. A healthy body and healthy mind means that people are
happy at their work and more productive,'' he said.
Mr Douglas Allsop, the director of the Scottish Council on Alcohol, welcomed
the new limits. ``Moving to daily limits is a substantial step forward. We are
still apt to regard Friday and Saturday nights as drinking nights in Scotland
when people go out and quaff their entire weekly ration,'' he said.
``Quite frankly, the old 21 and 14-unit limits were so low that not many people
paid much attention to them. Most people can see from life and observation that
a man who drinks two pints of beer a day is not doing any harm to himself at
all.
``Another major step forward is that the Government has now taken on board the
growing body of evidence that moderate drinking does carry some positive
benefits.''
Asked if he thought the new limits would be heeded, Mr Alsopp said: ``All you
can do is give people facts. It is a free country.''
Mr Robin Tucek, co-author of a new book on malt whisky, is less convinced. He
said: ``Any guidance from government departments should be treated with a large
pinch of salt. Most people drink sensibly and will not be changing their
lifestyle simply because someone says it is safe to take this amount or that
amount. The only government guidance that is worthwhile is not to drink and
drive.''
</TEXT>
