<HEADLINE>BBC reschedules Reporting Scotland</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913655</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BBC Scotland's flagship news programme Reporting Scotland is changing its
starting time from next Monday to compete directly with rival news programmes
shown by Scottish and Grampian Television.
BBC Scotland chiefs conceded that their programme has been disadvantaged in the
past by going on air up to three minutes after Scottish Television's Scotland
Today and Grampian's North Tonight. Reporting Scotland is normally shown after
the national weather forecast broadcast at the end of the Six O' Clock News.
The programme attracts less than one-third of the potential viewing audience
while its main rival, Scottish Television, is understood to have just over 50%.
BBC Scotland's rescheduling will involve dispensing with the services of
weather people such as Ian McCaskill and Michael Fish in the early part of the
evening.
Instead Heather Reid will cover Scottish, national, and international weather,
in a slot lasting at least two-and-a-half minutes at the end of Reporting
Scotland.
</TEXT>
