<HEADLINE>Research shows drink can beat lethal diseases THE BENEFITS</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ALISON DANIELS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913657</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE publication of the report, which highlights the significant health benefits
of moderate drinking in preventing some common but potentially lethal diseases,
was welcomed by some medical experts who confirmed that the Government claims
were backed by scientific research.
Yesterday, Mr John Duffy, senior lecturer in the University of Edinburgh's
department of psychiatry and a member of the renowned Edinburgh-based Alcohol
Research Group, said he had carried out a lengthy study into the protective
effects of alcohol, particulary on middle-aged men, and was pleased the
findings had been recognised by the Department of Health.
Mr Duffy said the effects of alcohol on health were far less controversial than
other assertions contained in the report and there was considerable evidence to
suggest moderate consumption of alcohol could prevent coronary heart disease,
ischaemic strokes, cholesterol gallstones, and certain prostate conditions in
men.
In the case of coronary heart disease, scientific studies carried out in
Britain and America had shown that alcohol appeared to prevent dangerous blood
clots by dilating blood vessels.
Mr Duffy also said that years of research into the health effects of alcohol
had cast doubt on the assertion that the recommended limit for men should be 21
units per week.
In a paper published in the International Journal of Epidemiology earlier this
year, Mr Duffy concluded: ``The misinterpretation of 21 units per week for men
as a safe limit, implying that any drinking above that level is hazardous, does
not seem justified.''
He added that all the indications were that the so-called accepted levels of
sensible alcohol consumption were not those which scientists would describe as
the maximum levels a person could safely consume.
In his paper, Mr Duffy also pointed to findings which suggested total
abstention from drink carried certain risks but said further research was
needed.
Mr Duffy also warned that, while there was reason to question the ``less is
best'' approach advocated by the World Health Organisation and the Scandinavian
countries and evidence that 21 units was not the most the average man could
safely drink, the setting of new ``safe'' recommended levels was to some extent
a spurious exercise since there was no definitive evidence over what levels
could prevent disease.
</TEXT>
