<HEADLINE>Drunk accident victims crowd city hospital</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Alison Daniels</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913658</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE DRAWBACKS
STUPID, insensitive, and based on questionable scientific evidence. This was
the reaction yesterday of one consultant working in the accident and emergency
department of an average city hospital to the Government's new guidelines on
recommended maximum alcohol intake levels.
Pick any night of the week and the emergency rooms of the Victoria Infirmary in
the south of Glasgow sees a stream of up to 200 accident admissions.
Few eyebrows would be raised by those working in any other Scottish hospital to
learn that around half of the Victoria's casualties have come to grief through
drink. By the late evening, consultant Ian Anderson said you would be
hard-pressed to find a patient who was sober.
Mr Anderson painted a depressing picture of a department forced to deal with
the effects of Scotland's ``number one drug''. In a slightly resigned tone, he
told of the vomiting, abusive, violent patients who use vast amounts of
hospital time, staff patience, and much-needed beds.
Among each batch of daily admissions are those who have been involved in a
fight, those who have fallen over, and those who have simply poisoned
themselves with drink.
For accident and emergency staff, moping up can be an unrewarding, dangerous
job compounded by the problem of attempting to make an accurate diagnosis of
conditions often obscured by drunkenness.
``The real problem with drink is that it is a great mimicker of other
conditions,'' said Mr Anderson. ``The danger is smelling drink and dismissing
someone as merely a drunk when something else is wrong. Consequently, we have
to keep people in overnight while an assessment is made. A lot of beds in this
city are being used to watch people.''
Mr Anderson described the timing of the announcement, in the run-up to
Christmas and on the heels of the Government's straight to the point drink
drive campaign, as ``insensitive and remarkably stupid''.
He said: ``Frankly, people have a problem with this Government's credibility.
It seems like the Department of Health is deliberately looking for a banana
skin.''
Mr Anderson also questioned the raising of recommended limits by nearly 50%
when, he said, the original levels were fairly arbitrary. ``Does this mean they
got it wrong 10 years ago? I don't think there is a safe level since what is
okay for one individual is not for another.
``It's like saying there are safe levels of exercise or food. It's just a
figure plucked out of the air. I remain to be convinced by the safety claims.''
</TEXT>
