<HEADLINE>Maradona cleared of drug smuggling</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<FLAG>foreign digest</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974913659</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ROME: Argentine football star Diego Maradona and his former personal manager
were yesterday acquitted of drug trafficking.
The case dated back to 1989, when Maradona played in Italy with first-division
Napoli. He left Italy three years ago after receiving a 15-month international
suspension for cocaine use and did not attend the trial in Rome.
Briton sent home
AUSTIN: A Briton accused of receiving millions of pounds embezzled from
telephone giant AT&amp;T will not be prosecuted in the US because he is dying of
Aids. Michael Lindsey Faulkner, 29, who had a lavish lifestyle in Texas, was
allowed to return to Britain at the weekend.
Ferry fire
MANILA: Three passengers died when a fire broke out in the galley of a
Philippine island ferry with at least 127 people on board. The navy evacuated
more than 100.
Suspect held
NEW YORK: The FBI has brought another terrorism suspect to the US in connection
with a plot to blow up American aircraft over the Far East. Wali Khan is an
associate of the suspected mastermind of the 1993 World Trade Centre bombing,
Ramzi Yousef, who is also accused of plotting to bomb US planes.
Jackson home
NEW YORK: Pop star Michael Jackson left hospital yesterday to the cheers of
fans after a week's treatment for a life-threatening viral infection that
caused him to faint on stage.
Brain to burn
PORTAGE: A US judge has ordered the cremation of Jeffrey Dahmer's brain,
rejecting a plea from the serial killer's mother that it be examined for clues
to what led him to murder 17 young men and boys. Dahmer was beaten to death in
prison a year ago. The rest of his remains have already been cremated.
Advice for Diana
NEW YORK: America's best-known sex therapist, Dr Ruth Westheimer, has offered
the Princess of Wales her help after meeting her briefly at a charity dinner.
Of the princess's Panorama interview about her marriage, Dr Ruth said: ``I
would have liked to talk to the two of them . . . My office has two entrances.
People can come to me without being seen.''
Sinatra tamed
LOS ANGELES: Singer Frank Sinatra celebrated his 80th birthday yesterday
without the wild parties that marked his earlier years. ``Dad doesn't like
birthdays,'' said daughter Nancy. ``We are planning a quiet family dinner.
Well, it won't be quiet but it will be a family dinner.''
</TEXT>
