<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Hanger 13 rave venue wants to reopen</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913662</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A BID to reopen the notorious Hanger 13 rave venue will be made in the new year.
The boss of the seaside nightclub wants it to become a ``role model'' for safe
dancing.
Three youths died at the venue in Ayr last year after taking ecstasy at weekend
rave parties.
Mr Fraser McIntyre, manager of the club which was shut down by licensing bosses
last March, said: ``We will be applying to the council for the return of our
licence early next year. We want to get back into business as the premises are
providing no income at the moment.
``A lot of other activities such as discos, tea dances, and children's parties
were stopped when they took away our entertainments licence.
``We want to start again and don't see why we should not have weekend dances.
``But we have no intention of retaining the name Hanger 13, simply out of
respect for the boys who died and their families.''
Kyle and Carrick licensing board will consider an application to renew the
licence at its meeting in March.
Mr Fraser said: ``A lot of people support our view that closing clubs is not
the answer to the drugs problem.
``We worked very closely with the Drugs Forum at the Scottish Office to mould
new legislation for safer rave venues.
``We could become a role model in the running of such dances in the future.''
``Whether or not Hanger 13 exists, there will still be a drugs problem in the
country.''
In May last year John Nisbet, 18, of New Cumnock, and Andrew Dick, 19, of
Glasgow, died from taking ecstasy at the club. Three months later Andrew
Stoddart, 20, from Rigside, Lanarkshire, died in similar circumstances.
</TEXT>
