<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Goal of the Indian view of nature</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH BUIE Environment Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913663</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE American Indians' belief that ``the environment is something that we have
borrowed from our children, not something we have inherited from our parents''
was held up as a definition of sustainable development by Scottish Environment
Minister Lord Lindsay yesterday.
However, speaking at the Scottish Environmental Forum's seminar in Glasgow, he
warned environmentalists that the practical application of this principle was
more complex. He said that since 178 countries signed Agenda 21, the programme
for local and national action on sustainable development, at the Earth Summit
in Rio de Janeiro in 1992, the UK had made impressive progress.
The Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development last year had placed
the UK top or second in 10 of its 37 core indicators, he said.
Lord Lindsay praised efforts at grassroots level and by local authorities to
implement the objectives of Agenda 21.
``Without the voluntary contribution and initiatives by people closer to ground
level, the diktats and prescriptions from central Government have a fairly
limited shelf-life,'' he said.
He also announced that the principle aim of the new Scottish Environmental
Protection Agency, which will be launched in April, will be ``to deliver
well-managed integrated environmental protection, not only as an end in itself
but as a contribution to the Government's goal of sustainable development''.
The guidance is being put out for consultation.
The director of Friends of the Earth Scotland, Mr Kevin Dunion, who chaired the
seminar, called for a new mechanism to link local and national action.
``In particular, the home energy efficiency scheme (whose funding was cut in
the Budget), has now become a victim of its own success,'' he said.
</TEXT>
