<HEADLINE>Accused soldiers blame each other for murder of tour guide</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913665</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Larnaca, Tuesday
A CYPRUS court today heard conflicting statements in which three British
soldiers blamed each other for the killing of a Danish woman tour guide.
Geoff Pernell, 23, Allan Ford, and Justin Fowler, both 27, have denied
abduction, conspiracy to rape, and the manslaughter of Louise Jensen, found
dead in a shallow grave near Ayia Napa on September 15, 1994.
The three, in statements read out by a police officer in the island's Assizes
court, gave conflicting accounts of how the 23-year-old tour guide was raped
and bludgeoned to death.
Ford admitted bludgeoning Jensen several times over the head and throat with an
army spade, but not killing her.
Pernell said Fowler had sex with Jensen and Ford battered her to death.
Fowler said Ford and then Pernell had sex with Jensen and then beat her to
death.
Cyprus police chief inspector Charalambos Argyrou read one statement by Ford,
three by Pernell, and one by Fowler to a hushed courtroom.
The defendants, based with the 1st Battalion, Royal Greenjackets at the British
base of Dhekelia in Cyprus, sat together in the dock, silent and expressionless.
Jensen's Cypriot boyfriend had testified that the three soldiers abducted her
after knocking the two of them off a motorcycle with their yellow ``mini moke''
recreational vehicle on the outskirts of the resort.
``I don't remember picking up the spade but I hit her on the head with the flat
side just hard enough to knock her unconscious. It didn't work.......I hit her
again the same as before and she slumped sideways,'' Ford, from Birmingham,
said in his statement.
``I know she wasn't dead because I could still hear her breathing. She looked
like she was asleep. Somebody grabbed the spade off me and pushed me away.
Stunned, I just stared at her face. Then the spade hit her, I think, neck and
again and again.''
Ford said he looked away from her but did not look at who was hitting her.
``I was frightened and sickened,'' said Pernell, who is from Oldbury, West
Midlands. ``When we stopped the car Justin asked the girl for sex. She didn't
refuse.......I saw them having sex.
``Allan was standing behind them. When Justin got up he hit her over the head a
number of times. She was not screaming.......it was as though she had trouble
breathing. There was also a bubbling noise present. Allan was hitting her on
the face, nose, and throat.''
Pernell said he was pacing up and down. ``I didn't think either one was capable
of this,'' he said.
Fowler, from Falmouth, blamed the other two for urging him to knock Jensen and
her boyfriend off their bike, because they ``wanted a woman''.
By the time they reached a dirt track, where Jensen was eventually found
buried, Jensen had soiled her jeans, he said. The other two men ripped off her
clothes and Ford told him to have intercourse with Jensen, he claimed.
``I pulled down my shorts and tried to do as I was told but the smell and
situation made it impossible,'' said Fowler.
He claimed he saw Ford try to have sex with Jensen and then Pernell swopped
places with him.
``Then I saw Geoff hit the woman with a spade. I couldn't believe it was
happening,'' Fowler said. The trial continues.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
