<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Call for children to be used in off-licence `stings'</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913666</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Test purchases are an effective and proven deterrent. I cannot understand why
Home Office Ministers are dragging their feet.             Nigel Griffiths
CHILDREN should be allowed to pose as customers to trap off-licences selling
alcohol to under-age buyers, Labour said yesterday.
The call came as a leading children's doctor said three out of four emergencies
she had encountered at one stage involved drunk adolescents.
Shadow consumer affairs spokesman Nigel Griffiths called for a change in the
law which would allow trading standards officers and the police to work with
children to make ``test'' purchases of alcohol.
The law currently allows children, under supervision, to buy cigarettes, adult
videos, and fireworks, and test purchases have resulted in successful
prosecutions.
Mr Griffiths said such purchases were allowed because, while it was illegal to
sell fireworks, adult videos, and cigarettes to children, it was not illegal
for children to buy them.
However, it was illegal for children to buy alcohol so test purchases could not
be made since the children would also be guilty. Mr Griffiths said he wanted
the 1988 Licensing Act to be amended.
``The public are alarmed at the increase in teenage drunkenness and by the ease
with which under-age children can buy alcohol,'' he said. ``Test purchases are
an effective and proven deterrent. I cannot understand why Home Office
Ministers are dragging their feet.''
Dr Joan Robson, leading consultant in paediatric accident and emergency
medicine at Liverpool's Alder Hey Hospital, said: ``Every Friday and Saturday
evening we see adolescents who are unconscious due to alcohol. At one stage,
three out of four emergencies we were dealing with were drunken children. I
welcome this initiative to reduce the problem.''
Mr Peter Maudsley, director of Liverpool Council's consumer protection
committee, also gave his support to Labour's proposal to give trading standards
officers more powers to prosecute off-licences which break the law.
``The carefully organised and supervised practice of working with children is
endorsed by the High Court and in Home Office guidelines of good practice.
Sadly, the Home Office refuses to amend the law similarly to permit test
purchases for alcohol.''
He said supervised purchases of fireworks and adult videos had seen their
illegal sale to under-age children drop from 50% to 5%.
Professor Philip Graham, who chaired the Royal College of Physicians and
British Paediatric Association working party on alcohol and the young, said:
``The supervised purchase of cigarettes to catch illegal sellers to children,
with their parents' consent, has been effective. There is no reason why this
should not be extended to alcohol purchases.''
Professor Graham said: ``The figures we produced in our report were that one in
four 14-year-olds had found it possible to buy alcohol in a pub, and two in
five of 16-year-olds had.
``This suggests there are hundreds of thousands of 15, 16, and 17-year-olds not
finding it difficult to buy alcohol in pubs, so it is clear the law is being
flouted very considerably.''
An official survey had found 28% of 13-year-old boys and 15% of 13-year-old
girls had been drunk at least once in the previous year, and over half of
15-year-old boys and just under half 15-year-old girls.
</TEXT>
