<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Five life terms for attacker Appeal to victims of serial rapist</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>PHOTOGRAPH</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974913667</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
POLICE have appealed for victims of a serial rapist to come forward after the
attacker yesterday began five life sentences.
Victor Willoughby, 30, is suspected of more than 100 sex attacks.
Detective Superintendent Duncan MacRae described him as ``the most dangerous
and prolific serial sex offender I have ever come across''.
The officer continued: ``We are dealing with the tip of the iceberg. We have
already investigated 17 rapes and I wouldn't be surprised if the total went
into three figures.
``We believe out there among the public are more of his victims and we clearly
would like to hear from them.''
His appeal was echoed by two of Willoughby's eight victims who were in court to
see their attacker convicted and sentenced.
Police have set up a special help line for other victims to report their
ordeal. It will be manned by female officers familiar with the case. The number
is 0181 733 3842.
The judge said the attacks, spanning a year, ``were all of the most appalling
sexual ferocity''.
At the Old Bailey, Judge Neil Denison said: ``The protection of the community
and particularly of women requires that I pass an indeterminate sentence. You
have a previous conviction very similar to these attacks.''
Willoughby started his reign of terror in north-west London shortly after he
was released from jail for a previous assault.
He terrorised women walking home alone late at night and stalked night buses
and scoured streets in his search for victims, the court had heard.
He was convicted of four rapes, another serious sexual offence, three indecent
assaults, false imprisonment, robbery, attempted robbery and dangerous driving.
The defendant from Tottenham, north London, had denied all charges.
In 1987, he was sentenced to eight years for dishonesty and attempting to rape
a woman walking home from a night bus.
On his release in 1992, he wounded a man in a street attack and was sent back
to prison for 12 months. Released in August 1993, he began stalking and
attacking his current victims within weeks.
The women, aged between 16 and 47, were subjected to degrading sexual assaults.
All the women were on their way home after a night out.
In one attack he pretended he was a minicab driver and then raped the woman in
the car.
In some attacks he hid behind bushes or in the shadows and pounced on his
victims from behind, dragging them into alleyways and, on one occasion, into a
churchyard.
He threatened violence and ``each woman was so frightened they offered
relatively no resistance,'' said Mr Nigel Sweeney, prosecuting. Only one woman
managed to fight him off.
Two of his victims remembered a distinct smell during their ordeal. One noticed
a pink oil moisturising gel in his hair. Another registered `` a sickly sweet
smell about her attacker''.
When arrested, Willoughby had the same sort of gel in his hair.
Mr Sweeney said there had also been a DNA match.
The two victims in court urged others attacked to come forward.
``It is a difficult thing to do, but we have received sensitive treatment from
the police and the court. I was so angry and I was determined to go through the
case,'' said 22-year-old student, Miss X.
</TEXT>
