<DOCNO>GH951213-000130</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000130</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Eight face genocide charges in Rwanda</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913668</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Arusha, Tanzania, Monday
THE UN tribunal investigating Rwanda's genocide issued its first indictments
today, accusing eight people of taking part in the mass slaughter of thousands
in a football stadium and church.
Tribunal chairman Judge Richard Goldstone refused to name the accused in case
four still at liberty escaped arrest. Four were in custody in Zambia, he said.
Goldstone, a South African judge, said the eight were charged with carrying out
genocide and three counts of crimes against humanity in the western Rwandan
town of Kibuye last year.
Rwanda's genocide, one of the most intense bouts of killing in history, lasted
from April to June last year, as mobs of the Hutu majority led by soldiers and
militia systematically put to death up to one million minority Tutsis and
politically moderate Hutus.
Governments concerned are obliged by the United Nations to hand over suspects
to the UN-appointed tribunal, but Goldstone admitted the difficulties in
bringing suspects to justice.
``The indictments mark the beginning of a long and difficult road.......many
challenges lie ahead,'' he said.
He expected trials to start within six to eight weeks and the tribunal to begin
excavating mass graves next month.
In the Rwandan capital Kigali, some officials reacted with dismay.
``For a genocide of one million people, only eight indicted? This isn't enough.
The tribunal could have done more,'' said Information Minister Jean-Pierre
Bizimana.
Goldstone's decision not to name the accused came under fire from
prosecutor-general Simeon Rwagasore.
``Our people would like to know immediately which criminals are on the list.
Everyone has been waiting for this. We have a right to know,'' he said.
Rwagasore warned that further delays would prompt genocide survivors to take
justice into their own hands.
Rwanda's own justice system has been paralysed. Jails are crammed with 60,000
people not tried under genocide charges. The prison population is growing by
1000 a week.
``If criminals remain free, this will only strengthen our culture of impunity.
Our people have already begun taking justice in their hands. Acts of revenge
will only increase. Repatriation of refugees will be paralysed,'' he said.
In another development today, Rwanda and the Security Council agreed in
principle on keeping 1200 UN troops and 200 military observers in the central
African country.
However a resolution on the UN Assistance Mission for Rwanda (Unamir), whose
mandate expired on Friday but was extended until today, was still being
negotiated as envoys argued about whether troops should protect aid
workers.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
