<DOCNO>GH951213-000131</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000131</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Ski slopes and beaches fall prey to warmer climate</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>From JUDE WEBBER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913669</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Rome, Tuesday
WITHIN 50 years, skiers could find no snow on their favourite Alpine slopes and
and sunbathers scant sand on Mediterranean shores, the World Wide Fund for
Nature (WWF) warned today.
The environmental group outlined the stark scenario as scientists from the
UN-sponsored Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change met in Rome to approve
new research that suggests the earth's average temperature could rise by 2C
next century.
The WWF said half of the world's glaciers and 85% of deltas could disappear
within 100 years as the greenhouse effect caused lower snowfalls, more rain,
and hotter summers.
Scientists believe the phenomenon is largely caused by burning fossil fuels
which release greenhouse gases like carbon dioxide and methane, which trap heat
in the atmosphere.
``The Alps are experiencing one of the fastest changes,'' said Paolo Lombardi,
International Programme Officer at the WWF in Italy.
In parts of the Swiss Alps, the snowline has risen 110yd since 1980. Martin
Beniston, who helped co-ordinate an IPCC study into the effect of global
warming on mountains, said that would worsen.
``The expected rise in the snowline in winter is 100 metres for every degree
increase in temperature,'' he said.
That would put famous Alpine ski resorts such as Courcheval and Val d'Isere at
risk, Lombardi said.
He said 20in of snow for 100 days a year constituted good skiing conditions,
and those were usually found at 1333yd altitude.
``There could be a shift in 30-50 years to more than 1666yd,'' he said.
``That's bad. Three hundred metres (333yd) may seem like a little, but it's
not.''
Beniston said the Rockies in the United States could also suffer and the WWF
forecast the US ski industry could lose up to $1.7bn a year (#1001m) because of
climate change. It said Australia's ski business could dry up altogether.
Lombardi said global warming also consituted a big threat to the Mediterranean,
whose coastlines are at risk of rapid erosion in the next century.
``The Mediterranean is considered one of the areas in the world most threatened
by climate change,'' he said. ``One-third of beaches are already retreating.''
He said sea levels rose by 1.2in to 1.6in last century but could rise an
average 20in by the second half of the 21st century.
Rising water levels are a particular threat to areas where subsidence is
already a big problem. ``The Venice lagoon will disappear unless dikes are
built,'' he said.
The IPCC, an independent body set up in 1988 by the United Nations and the
World Meteorological Organisation, is meeting to approve new guidelines on
climate change.
Some 300 delegates from 120 countries approved three key studies stating there
was a ``discernible human impact'' on world weather.
They were still haggling over another text designed to help governments turn
scientific information into action when signatories of the UN's 1991 Framework
Convention on climate meet in March.
The convention, signed at the Earth Summit in Rio, called on countries to
stabilise emissions of carbon dioxide at 1990 levels by 2000.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
