<DOCNO>GH951213-000132</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000132</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Charge against Sun reporter not proven</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913670</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A REPORTER and photographer working for the Sun accused of a breach of the
peace walked free from court yesterday after the case was found not proven.
At Dundee Sheriff Court, Mrs Doris Brannan, 50, claimed she was ``hysterical''
when reporter David Dinsmore and freelance photographer Alan Ewing came to her
door.
However, the two men said they had been assaulted by her son.
The court heard they wanted to interview the widow of murder victim Danny
Hallet, a Dundee publican.
They believed Mrs Dale Hallet was at a flat in Murrayfield Terrace, Dundee, but
found it occupied by Mrs Doris Brannan, who refused to give them Mrs Hallet's
address.
Mrs Brannan said: ``I shouted at them to go away. I got hysterical and my son
evicted them.''
Her son, Peter Lea, 26, said he grabbed the reporter by the arm and ``threw him
out the house''.
However, Mr Ewing, 38, of Dungoil Road, Lenzie, said a man ``came at him'' from
inside the house. He added: ``I put my hand up and he caught me on the side of
the head.''
Mr Dinsmore, 27, of Lancaster Crescent, Kelvindale, Glasgow, said Mr Lea spat
on his coat as he and Mr Ewing went down the stairs.
</TEXT>
