<DOCNO>GH951213-000133</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000133</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Peres urges Syrians to join peace process</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>From PATRICK BROGAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913671</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Washington, Tuesday
THE new Israeli Prime Minister, Shimon Peres, has launched a new effort to make
peace with Syria, using a visit to Washington as his platform.
He addressed a joint session of Congress today, and took the occasion to call
on President Assad to make the last, final effort to reach an agreement.
Mr Peres came to the United States to attend a memorial service for Yitzhak
Rabin in New York on Sunday and to pay his first formal visit to Washington as
premier. The joint session, which tied up members of Congress for most of the
morning when they might have been debating Bosnia or working on the budget
crisis, was a gesture of respect to the late prime minister as much as a
welcome to his successor.
The Secretary of State, Warren Christopher, will return to the Middle East
later this week, after the Dayton agreement is signed in Paris on Thursday, to
try to make some progress on the peace negotiations. They have been stalled
since last summer on the issue of military patrols on the Golan Heights, and on
the question of the amount of Syrian territory that Israel will return.
The Syrians want the whole of the Golan, just as Anwar Sadat insisted on the
whole of Sinai when he made peace with Israel in 1979. The Israelis have
demanded that there should be independent monitors to watch for the movement of
troops in the liberated territory.
There has been a small international force in Sinai, including some Americans,
since the Egyptian-Israeli peace agreement, ensuring that Egypt does not move
troops into the demilitarised areas. Israel wants the same facilities on the
Golan, and has offered to allow Syrians to monitor Israeli troop movements
along the shores of the Sea of Galilee.
So far, Mr Assad has refused to move. However, he called President Clinton
yesterday while Mr Peres was in the White House, to agree to Mr Christopher's
mission and the president said later that he hoped that this was a sign of
progress.
In his address to Congress, Mr Peres said: ``I would like to use this podium to
turn to President Assad of Syria and say to him: `Without forgetting the past,
let us not look back. Let fingertips touch a new hope. Let each party yield to
the other, each giving consideration to the respective needs of the other'.''
He also noted: ``Nothing convinced Israelis of the sincerity of the Arabs more
than the sympathy and condolences they expressed when they heard of the
assassination of Yitzhak Rabin.'' He suggested that Israel's loss, in turn,
should convince the Arabs of the sincerity of its desire for peace.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951213-000134</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000134</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Bankies, Airdrie hope it's third time lucky</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>29</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913672</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CLYDEBANK and Airdrie will try for a third time later this month after their
clash last night was knocked out by fog 45 minutes before the kick-off. The
clubs hastily contacted Scottish League secretary Peter Donald to get
permission for the game to go ahead on Saturday, December 23.
Bankies secretary Ian Steedman said: ``The league rules suggest it should be
played next midweek. But it is better to play on a Saturday. We contacted the
league secretary and he has given the go-ahead.''
q.DUNFERMLINE striker Andy Smith, who broke a leg in a pre-season game against
Bolton only weeks after his move from Airdrie, has come through three reserve
games without reaction.
q.DAVE Bassett yesterday quit as manager of first division Sheffield United.
His departure, understood to be ``by mutual consent,'' ends an eight-year stay
with United, who only last week came under the control of new chairman Mike
McDonald.
q.WALSALL moved into the FA Cup third round after scoring five extra-time goals
in an incredible 8-4 home win over Torquay, the side propping up the third
division.
The teams finished level at 3-3 in normal time. Walsall, lucky to survive when
an Ian Hathaway shot hit both posts in the final minute, went clear with goals
from Chris Marsh, Kyle Lightbourne, and Martin O'Connor in the first seven
minutes of extra time.
FOOTBALL ROUND-UP
</TEXT>
