<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951213-000135</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000135</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>A home where life's a beach</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>scotlands homes</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974913673</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
VIEWS of Arran, a private road to the beach, and an award-winning
bed-and-breakfast business - Spottiswoode is a vibrant reminder of the
traditional Clyde coast lifestyle.
The late Victorian villa stands in Seamill, right next to the Hydro, and was
built in 1895 on a private road which leads straight to the sandy beach (with
no roads for children to cross).
The ground-floor accommodation consists of an entrance hall, sitting room,
dining room, kitchen and family room, utility room, and shower room on the
ground floor. On the first floor there are four bedrooms, en-suite bathroom,
and two family bathrooms. Then there are a further two bedrooms, study and
bathroom on the second floor.
The house has been well maintained and considerable effort has been made to
retain its character and charm. Although the purchaser could use it as a
substantial family home, Spottiswoode also offers considerable potential for
running a small bed-and-breakfast business. It is currently one of the few
establishments in Ayrshire to hold the Scottish Tourist Board's Delux Award.
To the front is a Victorian-style 100ft-long walled garden which creates
privacy and seclusion. The rear garden has an old-fashioned drying green with
vegetable, flower and herb beds. Gates divide the front and rear gardens and
there is a single garage.
The Largs-based estate agency Welch &amp; Roe is marketing Spottiswoode at a fixed
price of #157,000.
</TEXT>
