<HEADLINE>Charlton's men are out to defy the odds one more time</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ian Paul</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>29</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974913674</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IF the bookmakers and pundits have got it right, Anfield, which has housed many
a historical football evening, will be the setting tonight for an Irish wake, a
celebration of a memorable era that has come to an end.
The problem with such theorising is that it concerns a man, Jack Charlton, and
a team, the Republic of Ireland, who have spent the last nine years defying
odds, experts, and logic. When dealing with that kind of defiance, it is best
not to bank on winning the wherewithal for the family Christmas by betting
against them.
Rationale says that Holland, a team of all the Ajax talents, should beat them
comfortably enough in the play-off to decide the last place in next summer's
European Championship finals in England.
Indeed, people are already suggesting that the Dutch are good bets to win the
tournament itself, but there has ever been an inherent flaw in the Holland
players' make-up which forces any analyst to ca' canny.
In fact, it is this self-destructive trait which has brought about their role
in this play-off in the first place.
The squad was not enamoured when Guus Hiddink took over as manager from Dick
Advocaat at the start of the year, so much so that the Ajax contingent
boycotted a friendly because they were too busy at club level.
Ultimately, they lost to Belarus, of all countries, and only retrieved the
play-off position by beating Norway.
All appears to be well with the players now, but you never can be sure. They
certainly know each other well enough. It is expected that the team will
consist of eight Ajax players and three former Ajax men, an incredible tribute
to the world and European club champions from Amsterdam.
A sign of the changing times in that cosmopolitan city is that six of the
players are black but, more important, all 11 are products of the Ajax school
of excellence which is unquestionably the leader in its field.
Charlton, typically, throws cold water on the Ajax theory, pointing out that no
country has ever successfully transferred a club team to international level.
The Dutch club might well be the exception to that rule, if the standards they
have set are maintained.
Charlton has said he will not decide his own future immediately after the game,
preferring to take a little time to discuss matters with the Irish FA.
However, if his team does lose, it will surely be finale time after glorious
defiance in World Cups and European Championships which took his adopted
country to a place among the elite of football nations.
Although that was done by dispensing with the frills and taking the direct
route to goal, a tactic which flummoxed the dedicated strategists, there was a
great deal more to his team than the long-ball punt.
He has hidden his men away in the Borders this week as he wrestled with his
selection, following the injury in training suffered by Steve Staunton. He will
field four full backs, two of them as midfield defenders, to combat the threat
of Dutch wingers Marc Overmars and Glenn Helder. That means a recall for
Chelsea's new signing, Terry Phelan.
The presence of Marseille's former Celtic man Tony Cascarino - who is nothing
else if not a survivor - will ensure the normal ``garryowen'' ball into the
middle to annoy the more cultured Dutch defence, but the return of John
Sheridan, a player of redoubtable passing skills, is an indication that other
options are available.
Overall, the brilliance of players like Denis Bergkamp, Clarence Seedorf, and
Patrick Kluivert, to name but three, should see Holland through but, in the
jargon of the modern game, they will have to be up for it, or Big Jack's
roadshow might still have another tour to do.
IAN PAUL
EUROPEAN CHAMPIONSHIP PLAY-OFF
</TEXT>
