<HEADLINE>Fading stars of Sweden</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN BROADLEY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913676</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
OUR OPPONENTS:
SCOTLAND can count themselves lucky with last night's draw in Paris for World
Cup '98. Sweden, the No.1 seeds in Group 4, and Austria, the main threats to
Scotland's qualifying hopes, are teams past their prime.
The Swedes, who have been encountered in three previous World Cup campaigns,
have yet to record a single victory over the Scots. Their prospects of doing so
in the qualifying process will lie with a diminishing group of star players
past their sell-by date.
Only Thomas Brolin, sold by Parma to Leeds United last month after serious
injury problems, can hold genuine claims to world-class status.
Others, such as eccentric keeper Thomas Ravelli, Kennet Andersson, Klas
Ingesson and Stefan Schwartz, who made no significant impact in his time with
Arsenal, can no longer be regarded among the leading exponents of their
profession.
Austria are currently in a period of steep decline. Their domestic leagues are
blighted by falling attendances, bankruptcy,  and a lack of emerging talent.
Over the years the Bundesliga has proved to be a natural progression for their
best players, yet this season only two are to be found plying their trade there.
One is captain Andreas Herzog, a formidable attacking midfielder with Bayern
Munich, but he, too, has been hampered by injuries. The other is FC Cologne
striker Toni Polster, now 31, and no longer such a prolific scorer.
Latvia, Belarus, and Estonia have employed Russian coaches to assist their
development, but without the infrastructure and finance, their progress has
been restricted, even though there is undoubted talent. Aberdeen found that out
last season, when they were beaten in the UEFA Cup by Skonto Riga, of Latvia.
However, none of the representatives from these three nations made any
appreciable headway this season in the European club competitions.
</TEXT>
