<TEXT>
CONNOISSEURS of the hallway should have a look at The Beeches, a substantial
house in Cambuslang's conservation area.
The former manse has been converted into two dwellings and the whole of the
ground floor is now for sale. The house was built around 1870, converted in
1961, and retains many of its original features - of which the strongest is
probably the hall, a baronial-style space which also serves as a dining area.
Thus retaining an echo of ancient feasts in ancient halls, it has mahogany wood
panelling to three-quarter height and two full-height stained and leaded glass
windows, with their shutters in working order.
Two wooden doors have leaded glass insets and there is parquet flooring at the
reception area, original ceiling coving and ornate centre ceiling cornicing. A
pair of Victorian brass wall-mounted candleholders completes the period feel of
the hall.
The accommodation extends to about 2000sq.ft and comprises: the hall/dining
room; breakfasting kitchen; utility room; three bedrooms (main bedroom with
en-suite); family bathroom and separate toilet. The house has a large private
garden which offers the possibility of future development potential.
Slater Hogg &amp; Howison invites offers over #116,000.
</TEXT>
