<HEADLINE>MORTGAGE LENDERS LOOK AHEAD - AND THE NEWS IS GOOD New horizons for the home-buyer</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEWART McINTOSH The Herald Property Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>scotlands homes</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974913679</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
the UK could be boosted if this group were to be provided with new inducements
to buy homes.
The bad news is that there will be a decline in the number of people in the
first-time buyer age group over the next ten years. But the escalator need not
stall, says the CML research. The report reveals that home ownership levels
among the 30-44 age band are lower than those in the 45-64 age group. A dip in
home-ownership could be created as these lower rates feed through to the
succeeding age band during the next ten years - unless action is taken too
stimulate ownership among the current 30-.to 44-year-olds.
``This report shows that there is still significant scope for more people in
the UK to get the chance to own their own homes - particularly if conditions
which support owner-occupation are favourable,'' says Adrian Coles, CML
director-general. ``Affordability is currently excellent, but longer-term
changes in the types of households identified by this report should also be
taken into account when considering the future of home-ownership.''
Meanwhile, the lenders have also been looking at how the property crash has
affected the attitudes of buyers. Falls in house prices and the resulting
negative equity south of the Border have changed beliefs and behaviour in
relation to home-ownership.
Major influences on borrowing are: the advent of a low inflation economy;
greater insecurity in the labour market; and the ``overhang'' of high levels of
personal financial commitments from the late 1980s. Mortgage affordability also
plays a part.
The lack of the ``feelgood factor'' is at the heart of the changing beliefs
about borrowing. There has been some limited recovery in overall consumer
confidence since 1992.
The report also points out that a willingness to borrow and a willingness to
buy a home are separate, although related, processes. The first requires a
resurgence of consumers' confidence in their financial prospects. The second
also requires some certainty that house purchase will not be a disinvestment --
that house prices will not decline further and may indeed rise.
Only when consumer confidence about both financial prospects and house prices
coincide is mortgage borrowing likely to increase. Even when this happens, the
report concludes, house purchases and mortgage lending are likely to lag behind
any sustained recovery in consumer confidence.
``Overall attitudes to home-ownership have remained stable, and show a gradual
increase in the numbers of people expressing a preference for owning rather
than renting a home,'' says Peter Williams, CML head of research and external
affairs.
THE big mortgage lenders have been anxiously studying where their future market
will come from. Having seen the mortgage market flat on its back for the last
five years, the banks and building societies have launched a major examination
into future home-ownership trends.
And the news is good. Home-ownership is set to rise over the next ten years,
according to research for the Council of Mortgage Lenders (CML) which says that
the UK's 67% owner-occupation rate is likely to reach 70% to 75% by 2006.
Scotland's lower rate of home-ownership than the UK average means that there is
scope for even more rapid growth. At the moment less than 60% of Scottish
households are in owner-occupation.
Home-ownership in the UK: the Potential for Growth was written by researchers
from the University of Bristol and South Bank University for the CML. It
reviews the past growth of home-ownership since 1973 - including the huge
impact of council house sales - and looks at how changes in the make-up of the
population are likely to affect future trends in owner-occupation.
Much of the growth will come from changes in lifestyle. Although the population
is not increasing, Government estimates suggest that there will be a 12% growth
in the overall number of households over the next ten years - generating a
higher demand for owner- occupation.
It is estimated that, by the early years of the next century, there will be a
decline of 3.5% in the number of married households; an increase of 2% in the
number of lone parent households; and a 17% increase in single-person
households.
Single-person households have tradition-ally had low rates of home-ownership.
