<HEADLINE>Sell-out crowd a testimony to captain's appeal Cheers among souvenirs of McStay's big night out</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN PAUL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>29</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974913680</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EVEN the fog lifted enough to let the 37,300 see the man of the night, Paul
McStay, celebrating almost 15 years as a signed Parkhead player doing what he
does best, playing in the green-and-white hoops.
From the moment he came on the pitch with his two little daughters in his arms
until he was cheered to the night sky at the end, the fans made this his own
special occasion.
The presence of Manchester United guaranteed such a crowd and a bumper pay-out
for McStay, who would collect something close to #400,000 from the testimonial
fund after the takings had been counted.
United manager Alex Ferguson would not grudge him a penny as one of his
staunchest admirers. Ferguson had hoped to field more of his star turns but
injury prevented him from doing so. The team he fielded made a decent game of
it, however, but they came up against Pierre van Hooydonk in lethal form.
The Dutch striker shot home the first goal early in the first half and after
United equalised through Paul Scholes before half-time, he produced a stunning
second score midway through the second period.
Substitute Chris Hay added a third before the end and the cheering went on . .
. and on.
McStay went to the centre circle, picked up the trophy presented by his
parents, then the main man took the mike and thanked the troops. The cheers
went on . . . but we have been through that.
Afterwards, the tributes flowed.
From Ferguson: ``It was a fabulous night. The number of people who showed up
proved what he means to them. He's been a marvellous player for Celtic, and
he's also a smashing lad. To have achieved what he has and retained humility
makes him special.''
From Tommy Burns: ``The supporters demonstrated how much they love him as a
player and how much they appreciate the fact that he stayed here.''
From Brian McClair: ``He is a rare talent and a great ambassador for the game.
He would compare with any midfield player I have seen or played with.''
From McStay, who threw his shirt into what used to be the jungle: ``It was a
bit different from the last time I did that. This time it was in pure
happiness. I didn't get a lot of sleep last night and it turned out to be a
very emotional game for me. I want to thank the fans not just for tonight but
for my whole career.''
As the crowd gathered earlier in the evening when the fog was at its worst, the
lights of Celtic's proud new stand loomed through the mist like a grounded
cruise liner, but the lines of the makeshift stand behind the goal, used for
the first time, could at least be spotted, and the pre-match fun, with
Coronation Street stars among the celebrity side, was discernible enough to
keep the crowd entertained.
The Old Crock Celtic side, possibly relieved that their former talents were not
over-scrutinised in the dim outlook, did have enough going for them to beat the
soap stars.
The mist, presumably under orders from the committee, eased just before
kick-off as the teams came out, each player with a young mascot.
They lined up in the middle of the park and awaited the arrival of the man
himself, who came on carrying his daughters, Melissa and Siobhan, to a
deafening reception.
Manchester, in one of their multitude of change strips, this version in grey,
were missing many of their stars of course, but this did not stop their fans
giving vein to the ``Ooh, aah, Cantona'' chant but maybe they were surprised to
hear the home troops joining in with gusto.
It made us wonder what reception the controversial Gallic stylist would have
received had he been fit to play.
The Celtic fans had another name to chant after 13 minutes when van Hooydonk
stepped in with one of the goals that are becoming a welcome habit at Parkhead.
It was the consequence of a sweet move, too, with Simon Donnelly holding the
ball intelligently before laying it across to Andy Walker, who promptly pushed
it to the far post where the Dutchman had no problems in sending it past Keith
Pilkington.
United equalised eight minutes later when a Lee Sharpe corner was touched on by
Steve Bruce and Scholes shot through a ruck of players into the net.
Celtic left Donnelly and O'Donnell inside at half-time, replacing them with Hay
and Brian McLaughlin as the grey mists came swirling over the field again.
Then United put on their first sub, Appleton for O'Kane, followed by Morten
Wieghorst coming on for Celtic in place of Collins.
The game had begun to lose momentum but van Hooydonk was merely biding his
time. In 66 minutes, the Dutchman struck with a tremendous goal, taking a pass
from Tosh McKinlay and thumping it low into the net from 25 yards.
Almost immediately, Celtic took off McKinlay and brought on Stuart Gray and, as
the fog closed in, United brought on Tomlinson for Cole.
Hay completed the scoring four minutes from time.
All that was left now was the final celebrations. The fog gave it all an unreal
feeling but McStay will remember it clearly enough.
CELTIC - Kerr, Vata, McKinlay, McNamara, Mackay, O'Donnell, Donnelly, McStay,
van Hooydonk, Walker, Collins. Substitutes - Wieghorst, Marshall, McLaughlin,
Gray, Hay.
MANCHESTER UNITED - Pilkington, Parker, O'Kane, Bruce, Neville, May, Davies,
Sharpe, McClair, Cole, Scholes. Substitutes - McGibbon, Casper, Tomlinson,
Appleton, Clegg.
Referee - H Dallas (Motherwell).
Celtic......................3
Manchester Utd.....1
</TEXT>
