<HEADLINE>The place for busy people on the move</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEWART FRASER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<FLAG>scotlands homes</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974913681</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
KEEP your eye on Paisley used to be the old-time political motto. So how does
it translate today in terms of the housing market, for example? ``Very well
indeed,'' says Janette Turner, director of Paisley Property Letting Centre.
``It's too soon to see whether the Budget had any real effect on the market,
but Paisley is a very popular place for lets.
``In fact, we can say the whole of Renfrewshire is popular. It can get quieter
over Christmas and New Year, but we just can't get enough properties at most
times to meet demand.''
Being close to ``big brother'' Glasgow does not inhibit local enthusiasm.
Increased levels of activity have been noticeable from three specific areas -
the international airport, the local infirmary, and the university.
``This is an expanding area, and a busy one,'' says Janette. ``There are lots
of people in transit, as it were. Staff come for a relatively short-term
period. They don't want to be tied down, buying a property. They need a good
home base, and they want it at a good price.
``Young people don't choose to stay at home with their parents, either.
Everybody wants independence, but not to be tied down too soon to a mortgage.
We are solely into letting. We don't take on multi-occupation properties, but
there is a steady demand to meet for everything else, from small flats to
villas.
``We have just moved to new premises ourselves, on the main street. That has
given us a much higher profile. Business has improved - it just seems to have
taken off. And we can offer better prices than you get in Glasgow. That always
helps business.''
There is a similar story of steady business from Cluttons, at its Houston
office. People are moving into the area wanting to rent rather than buy. The
airport, infirmary, and university sectors provide a large degree of interest.
For a comparison of prices, Janette Turner indicates the possibilities in a
detached three-bedroom villa at Johnstone, coming on the market early in the
New Year. Fully furnished, with gas central heating, double glazing, a pleasant
garden and parking space, it will come in at around #500 a month.
A more modest place, say a fully-furnished studio flat in Paisley, comes in at
about #210, meeting many budgets.
Going for a one-bedroom fully furnished flat in the town, with shower room,
electric heating, and double glazing could increase the price to #280 a month.
Even moving out to Lochwinnoch need not be too expensive. A two-bedroom flat,
fully furnished, with electric heating - and convenient for Castle Semple Loch
, of course - is on the books for #350 a month.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951213-000144</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000144</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>'Muir survive visitors' late penalty claim</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>29</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913682</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Stenhousemuir 2, Arbroath 2
ARBROATH manager John Brogan was less than happy with referee Bobby Tait when
the whistler refused claims for a penalty in the dying seconds after striker
Steve McCormick - a former Stenhousemuir player - had been pulled down in the
box.
``Steve's jersey was pulled,'' said Brogan. ``I really thought it was a
penalty.''
But he was well pleased with his side's display. ``They (Stenhousemuir) are
League Challenge Cup holders and a division above us, but I thought we competed
well and, as I say, might have sneaked it if the penalty had been given.''
Ochilview counterpart Terry Christie was unhappy with his side's performance.
``We did not keep our shape at the back and lost silly goals as a
consequence,'' he said.
George McGeachie fired home to put the Warriors ahead with just a minute
gone, but McCormick shot home the leveller after 10     minutes.
Two bizarre own goals accounted for the final result. A Lee Gardner cross hit
'Muir midfielder Jimmy Fisher to fly into the net in 33 minutes. But two
minutes from the break, the pair accidentally combined again to enable the
Warriors to level, Gardner this time knocking a Fisher back-heeler past his own
keeper from close range.
</TEXT>
