<HEADLINE>Think of the blinking neighbours</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEWART McINTOSH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>scotlands homes </FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Illustration</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974913683</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
n.SOD the season of goodwill (suggests STEWART McINTOSH). Christmas brings a
shining opportunity to check out the neuroses of your neighbours. Have you ever
considered that those ostentatious fairy lights next-door might be a cry for
help or a flashy appeal for friendship?
Psychologists in the USA - well, where else would they come from? - say that
people who put that extra bit of sparkle on to their Christmas trees are either
very friendly and sociable...... or are lonely and trying to make new friends.
Perhaps in a bid to make new friends in the psychological world, Wimpey Homes
has carried out its own research into those blinking lights. It reveals that
the amount of decoration which adorns a neighbourhood for Halloween or
Christmas can affect perceptions about the area.
The sight of Christmas decorations on the outside of homes - even just a simple
wreath - persuades passers-by that the neighbourhood is open and sociable. Some
householders admitted to Wimpey's researchers that they decorate their homes in
an attempt to try to get to know people in the area.
(This can lead to disappointment. Catching sight of your neighbours as they
shin back over the garden fence with your fairy lights in a swag bag might not
be the social contact that was anticipated.)
Other studies have shown that houses with doors accessible from the street are
felt to contain people who are friendly and approachable. Other features which
give visitors the impression that they will get a friendly greeting on your
doorstep include: front walls painted in vivid (but not flashy) colours;
curtains which can be clearly seen from the road; and a garden which does not
obscure the house. So, if the house next door is lit up brighter than George
Square and its garden is teeming with plastic Rudolphs and inflatable snowmen,
don't just scream for the style police. After all, it could be a cry for help.
You could reply by sharing some goodwill and inviting him or her in for a mince
pie.
Or you could buy yourself a couple of pit bull terriers for Christmas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
