<TEXT>
ENGLAND
TERRY Venables will face a huge job to take England to the 1998 World Cup
finals.
Losing finalists Italy, the side that ended Ron Greenwood's bid to reach
Argentina in 1978, and old enemy Poland are bad enough, but the draw also threw
in the dangerous former Russian satellites of Georgia and Moldova.
``The prospect of two games with Italy is exciting and it wouldn't be the World
Cup without Poland, would it?'' said Venables. ``It's a tough group, but I
think the public now understand there aren't any soft games.
``Moldova and Georgia overwhelmed Wales and they will be very strong.''
But the main threats are Italy and Poland, qualifying opponents for the fifth
time in 22 years. The Italians have not lost to England for 18 years, while the
Poles ended Sir Alf Ramsey's hopes back in 1973.
</TEXT>
