<TEXT>
Ross Finlay finds
something extra in a six-gear Audi
RUNNING out of time on a test drive, I decided to put the Audi A6 into a
three-point turn and head back the way I had come. I fumbled for reverse and
discovered, to my dismay, that I had a box full of forwards. On events like
this, with the manufacturer's representatives back at base, unfortunate
incidents do happen.
A colleague who once returned a car with a shunted front end described
graphically how he had had to swerve to avoid a loose sheep on the road, and
cannoned into a wall. It was either the wall or the sheep. Everybody
sympathised, until another colleague who lived locally pointed out that, at
that time of the farming year, there would not have been a sheep within five
miles.
Transmission derangements are usually put down as the ham-fisted driver's
fault. Wanting to avoid that embarrassment, I peered at the gear lever, and
suddenly noticed what I had forgotten during the drive. The numbers on the knob
went from one to six, and reverse was out on a limb of its own.
This A6 was the turbo diesel 140 version with a six-speed box. I had thought up
till then that it was not as relaxed and long-legged as claimed, but that was
because, as well as forgetting where reverse lay, I had never got the Audi out
of fifth.
There are arguments about whether six-speed boxes are anything more than a
gimmick. When fitted to performance cars which have enough power and torque to
romp around with a three-speed transmission, let alone a four or five, they may
represent an over-egging of the technical pudding.
But when it comes to economical cruising, there is a definite appeal in a car
which will pull a really high sixth gear, always assuming that the engine is
flexible enough not to hiccup at the first sniff of a hill. The Audi A6 TDI 140
provides the most impressive combined performance/economy figures of any diesel
powered car on the market.
As the model designation suggests, the 2.5-litre five-cylinder turbo diesel
engine peaks at a very high 140bhp. An oil cooler, modifications to the fuel
injectors, and tinkering around with the electronics give it 25bhp extra over
the ordinary 2.5 TDI. It will pull over 33mph for every 1000rpm of engine
speed, and provides the phenomenal torque figures of a 214lb ft peak at under
2000rpm.
So there is power and flexibility, as well as ultra high gearing to show the
low-revving diesel engine at its best. In a roomy saloon or estate you can
expect something like 64mpg at 56mph, 46 at 75 and 37mpg around town.
But there is class-leading performance too. The TDI 140 will sprint to 60mph in
about 9.5 seconds, hit nearly 130mph on a test track, and murder its own
petrol-engined relatives in rolling acceleration.
When you add a well designed interior, and good passenger space, this car ought
to be in a class of its own. Some day soon it probably will be, but for the
moment the A6 is one of the older stagers in the Audi line-up. That brilliant
engine and optimistic transmission are installed in a car which is essentially
of the 1980s, based on the superseded Audi 100.
As in many cars with antecedents of that kind, wind and tyre noise are quite
pronounced. While ride quality is fine for the class, the A6 is a design
generation back in handling. It is more cumbersome when being pressed on
smartly than the newer and admittedly smaller A4.
Prices range from #23,500 to #27,177 according to body style and trim levels,
and a four-wheel drive quattro version has been introduced from #27,516. Twin
airbags are standard since the start of this month.
The present model's expected replacement may add higher-speed handling
qualities in advance of what is available now, but this A6 already has the
beating of its rivals in its outstanding combination of performance and economy.
</TEXT>
