<TEXT>
MODERN houses offer much more comfort and warmth than those of the past, but
they don't usually have as much character as their older counterparts. So when
a building company with a strong ``modern'' track record redevelops an old
building by an important architect, the result is . . . well, our picture says
much of it.
An unusual opportunity has been created to live in a traditional house - with
all the benefits of up-to-date comforts, conveniences and building techniques.
CALA Homes' Auchenbothie site at Kilmacolm offers such a choice of lifestyle -
something old or something new? The scheme consists of modern executive housing
dotted around Auchenbothie House - a nineteenth-century mansion by the
important Scottish architect William Leiper, a specialist in churches and large
houses. His Glasgow kirks include Dowanhill Church, Hyndland Parish Church,
Victoria Park Church, and Camphill Church in Queen's Park.
He also designed commercial and civic buildings such as Partick Burgh Halls,
Dumbarton Town Hall and Burgh Academy, and the French Renaissance style Sun
Life Assurance Building on Glasgow's West George Street. Not to mention the
facade of Templeton's Carpet Factory on Glasgow Green - a daring interpretation
of the Doges' Palace in Venice.
While he was developing his reputation as a church and commercial architect,
Leiper was also much in demand as a designer of private houses. These included
Cornhill house near Biggar and Dalmore in Helensburgh. He had the ability to
design in widely different styles - French and Italian Renaissance buildings
were built in parallel with others which were influenced by Alexander ``Greek''
Thomson.
Auchenbothie was was built in 1898 in the seventeenth-century Scots style with
turrets, harling, crow steps, bay windows, dormer windows, and courtyard.
Now a total of ten apartments have been created in the house, all of them with
one or two bedrooms. They include a large two-bedroom apartment which takes up
the whole of the second floor. It has views in all directions, a hexagonal
dining room built into the largest of the towers, and a roof terrace which is
approached via a spiral staircase from the living room.
Other apartments have rooms built into the original turrets, some of them
grouped around the courtyard.
Meanwhile, some 15 modern detached CALA houses are being built in the extensive
groundsof the main building. Prices range from #92,000 for the apartments and
from #192,000 for the four-  and five-bedroom detached modern houses.
</TEXT>
