<TEXT>
JUST as the winter really begins to bite, a house with a cosy ingleneuk
fireplace seems like the ideal home. But The Lodge offers more than a winter
retreat. Standing on the shores of Loch Goil, this unusual example of delicate,
almost filigreed Victorian architecture is a property for all seasons.
When the spring brings back the first of the watery sunlight to the west of
Scotland, the sun lounge offers a chance to feel the rays without feeling the
cold. And when real summer weather returns, the elegant balconies and covered
verandahs offer you a refreshing breath of fresh air without having to leave
the premises. With more than 200 yards of loch frontage, the house offers an
outdoor lifestyle at any time of year.
The ranch-style lodge is believed to date back to around 1860 and is a delicate
piece of work that seems to defy the term ``stone-built''. It has eight main
apartments and a self-contained granny wing. Under
the slate roof and behind the stone detailing, the drawing room has splendid
wood panelling, a vaulted ceiling, that ingleneuk with its snug seats for
coorying up to the fire, and a large bay window with views across Loch Goil.
French doors lead to a covered verandah.
The lounge also has a large bay window with views of the sea and its fireplace
contains a wood-burning stove. The dining room has a large stone fireplace,
parquet flooring - and more open views. It also has access to the sun room, a
space 16ft by 8ft which is glazed on three sides and has a quarry tile floor
and double doors opening on to the garden.
The kitchen has a south-facing picture window and comes with a gas-fired hob
and an oil-fired Aga. Upstairs are three bedrooms. The main bedroom has a
beamed ceiling, views southwards across the loch and an en-suite bathroom. The
four-apartment granny or guest suite has a living room, kitchen, three bedrooms
and a box room.
Outbuildings include two garages, laundry, workshop, woodstore and coal cellar.
The Lodge is located about 2.5 miles outside Lochgoilhead village in Argyll, on
the road to Carrick Castle. It sits at the foot of the hills, sheltered among
trees in a garden of around 1.7 acres which includes lawns, kitchen garden,
Victorian fountain, and a variety of mature trees and shrubs running down to
the loch shore. The garden also contains a summer house - for those idyllic
days when the ingleneuk season is only a faint memory.
Clyde Property is seeking offers over #195,000 for The Lodge.
</TEXT>
