<HEADLINE>Skilful Portugal give the English a scare</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEVE TONGUE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>29</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913690</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
England 1, Portugal 1
ENGLAND received a taste of things to come in next summer's European
Championship when a technically clever Portuguese side, comfortable qualifiers
for the finals, outmanoeuvred them for much of the night at Wembley, earning a
deserved draw.
Sadly, there was further evidence that it would be unwise to build either a
team strategy or too many hopes around Paul Gascoigne. The Rangers man's header
over the bar four minutes from time followed a rare sortie into the opposing
penalty area.
There was a deserved first start for Nottingham Forest's Steve Stone, after two
successful cameos as a substitute, and he celebrated with a goal after 44
largely uneventful minutes. Les Ferdinand chested down Stuart Pearce's cross
and Stone's aim was low and true from 20 yards out.
That was a setback for Portugal, a gifted young side beaten only once in their
previous 15 matches, whose movement off the ball and interchanging were so good
that it was impossible to pin down who was playing in which position.
Alan Shearer must have welcomed the extra power of Les Ferdinand alongside him
at least as much as Teddy Sheringham's more subtle approach that had worked
well against Switzerland last month. It was disappointing that Ferdinand had to
make way for his Newcastle team-mate Peter Beardsley because of a groin strain
midway in the second half.
By then, Portugal were level. Little Dominguez, playing wide on the right, fed
a shrewd pass through the middle and with Tony Adams distracted by Sa Pinto's
run and Steve Howey badly positioned, the lanky Paulo Alves hit a fierce shot
past David Seaman.
A triple substitution 10 minutes from the end almost worked for Venables as
well. Aston Villa's Gareth Southgate had played less than a minute of
international football when he headed a right-wing corner against the bar.
Venables' view, which cannot have been shared by many of the 29,000 present,
was: ``At half-time we were the better side. Then they had a good spell, but
when we put fresh legs on, we got back into it.''
He added, less controversially: ``They were a very, very good team and another
three workouts like that before next June would be ideal for us.''
ENGLAND - Seaman, Neville, Pearce, Wise, Adams, Howey, Barmby, Gascoigne,
Shearer, Ferdinand, Stone. Substitutes - Flowers, Le Saux, Southgate,
Beardsley, McManaman.
PORTUGAL - Neno, Carlos Secretairo, Dimas, Costa, Couto, Sousa, Figo, J Pinto,
S Pinto, Helder, Folha. Substitutes - Rui Carreira, Pedro, Dani, Domingos,
Paulo Alves.
Referee - R Pederson (Norway).
q.BIRMINGHAM captain Liam Daish will miss the rest of his side's Anglo-Italian
Cup action as organisers reacted to last month's brawl in Ancona.
Daish would have led his side against Cesena in today's group game at St
Andrews, but the club have agreed to a request to leave him out. However, a
carefully worded statement stressed that the decision does not mean any
individual has been found guilty of inflicting injury during a flare-up after
the match on November 15, when Ancona coach Massi Cacciatori was taken to
hospital with a fractured jaw and damage to his left eye.
</TEXT>
