SCOTLAND team manager Craig Brown sat for close to one-and-a-half hours here at
the Louvre in Paris yesterday to find out his World Cup fate. When the decision
arrived and Brown saw the group Scotland had been drawn in he admitted: ``This
section is winnable.''
The delay was caused by Sepp Blatter, general secretary of FIFA, aided by a
host of sporting superstars, trawling through the 170-nation qualifying process
which will involve 639 games worldwide. Europe, predictably, was the last area
to be drawn.
Initially, the Scots had hoped to avoid a six-team section because of the
fixture problems which may militate against them. But when Brown eventually
watched as the major players for the next World Cup, Germany, Italy, and Spain
vanish into other sections he realised that perhaps his luck was running well.
Eventually, Scotland found themselves with Sweden as the top team in their
group, and Austria from the stream of sides just below them. They also found a
trio of sides from the newly emerging nations in Eastern Europe. Estonia,
Latvia, and Belarus are there to add some mystery to the qualification.
Scotland's group was drawn by AC Milan's George Weah and former France
international star Just Fontaine at the glittering ceremony which began with
Michel Platini catching a ball headed by an image of Leonardo da Vinci's Mona
Lisa. However, president Jacques Chirac, who was scheduled to address the
audience, did not show up.
Compared to England, who must play Italy, Brown has reason to feel satisfied.
Predictably, he made warning noises. He stressed that Belarus could be a
threat, but they are not the kind of threat which might have been posed by, for
instance, Croatia. When pressed, the Scotland manager said: ``The group is
winnable. We can, given some luck, end at the top and qualify without having to
face a play-off match.
``We know the Austrians. We played them recently and we won in Vienna. We know
Sweden, too, having met them in Stockholm just six weeks ago. We lost, but
there was nothing which would seriously worry us. Sweden, of course, are there
as seeds because they finished third when the last World Cup was played in the
United States.
``They will be hurting now because they have not qualified for the European
Championships, but we will recognise that, just as we recognise the threat from
Belarus. Too many people write off the `new' nations, but they have, many of
them, a strong football tradition and a very organised infrastructure.
``The group is not easy, but we have a 50-50 chance of qualification.''
Jim Farry, the SFA chief executive, revealed that he and Brown will travel to
Vienna on January 17 to discuss the complicated dates situation. He said: ``We
have to fit in 10 matches, at least, by November 1997. That is not as easy as
it may sound. Four of the countries we are playing, Sweden, Estonia, Latvia,
and Belarus all have lengthy winter shut-downs. It looks as if we will have to
play matches in our own close season to make sure that the fixtures are
fulfilled.''
Farry again stressed, as he did in these pages on Monday, that the possibility
of weekend games, and double-headers would come into play.
He pointed out: ``It would seem the best way for us to do things. We could take
the squad to Latvia, and to Estonia, and play two matches back-to-back without
disrupting the domestic programme too much.''
In the meantime, Brown has to prepare his team for the Championships in England
in the summer. That is why they will avoid World Cup games before then,
although the qualifying programme begins in March.
Farry said: ``We must concentrate on one thing at a time. We have to look to
the finals in England. We are preparing, at the moment, to play one, or
possibly two, warm-up games in the United States on May. These will be in
either Boston or New York.''
Despite increasing speculation to the contrary, there is little doubt that
Brown will continue as international team manager. His contract, in that role,
ends in July. He knows  that a major part of his role at the SFA is to act as
technical director, to help with the youth programme, to help bring on young
talent, and to encourage the spread of a coordinated coaching system, one where
the nation will follow a lead from the SFA.
However, Brown is likely to guide the national side's fortunes into the World
Cup qualifying campaign just as he will do in the European Championships in the
summer. He is a man appointed by the SFA and they are unlikely to change their
views of his position especially following the qualification for England.
The one man wearing a frown in the SFA delegation was commercial director Bill
Wilson. A match with Italy, or Germany, or even Spain, would have given a huge
financial boost. Other draws:
