<HEADLINE>Baden-Powell's virtues</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974913694</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
YOUR columnist Ian Bell (December 9) seemed to enjoy the programme which cut
down Robert Baden-Powell to size, The Secret Lives. Its modern opinions applied
to the past may sound convincing enough.
Inadequate psychology, however, if ineptly applied, can create all sorts of
mischief. Worse, the object of its destructive intent is no longer in a
position to defend himself, to repudiate its facile accusations.
The Bell has a hollow ring, and sounds symptomatic of the sickness our society
suffers from.
Like everyone else, Baden-Powell was a product of the times in which he lived.
He belonged to a militaristic and colonising England, and was under orders to
uphold its values. If he enjoyed such ghastly blood-sports as pig-sticking,
then he and his England were no more pig-sick than countries which to this day
permit bull-fighting.
His admiration of young boys did not turn him into a pervert. Any sound
educationist is permitted to admire children in order the better to educate
them. It is those who dislike children who make the worst educators.
His reputed unease with women seemed to evaporate as soon as he met the right
one.
Interestingly enough, Baden-Powell had no intention at first of founding an
organisation. The movement grew from seeds sown in the hearts of healthy boys
and girls. The adulation they accorded him he received with modesty and grace,
and with no little surprise.
It was a great deal healthier than the destructive sneers which mere cynicism
accords him at the hands of those who have achieved exactly what for young
persons?
Gordon Dimmer,
Trossachs Studio,
Aberfoyle.
I CAN only assume that Ian Bell (December 9) did not like being a Cub many
years ago! His malevolent diatribe against Baden-Powell makes John Macleod seem
like a benign wit.
B-P's vision has enthralled young people for 90 years. This makes him liable to
jealous attacks from sad, embittered people who have achieved nothing for the
benefit of others.
Ian Bell is obviously one of these and told us a lot about himself in his
article. My advice to him is to visit a Scout group and then write another
article.
David Mackay,
21 Novar Drive,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
