<HEADLINE>Ambiguities on devolution</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974913696</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CONFUSION reigns after Hamish Paton's article (December 7). He asserts there is
a distinct possibility of a tax cut and not a tartan tax when a devolved
parliament in Scotland assumes its powers in about 18 months' time.
He went on: ``An independent Scotland oil-rich and debt-free could rapidly
regain its place among the wealthiest nations on the planet''. Planet indeed!
Even the rather self-effacing George Roberston, Labour's Shadow Secretary of
State, may be somewhat taken aback by the sheer exuberance of Mr Paton's
visions for the future.
In any event it is time that a more authoritative statement on the financial
implications of devolution be made by the Labour Party to resolve the many
ambiguities of the current situation.
The electorate need to know how the 130 members of the Scottish parliament
(plus the unspecified number of auxiliary jobs) are to be financed.
Allan MacRitchie,
144 Craigpark, Glasgow.
</TEXT>
