<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Lingering death for nuclear `wicked witch'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Margaret Vaughan</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974913698</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Margaret Vaughan reports how the money men have succeeded where the Green lobby
failed - in striking a death blow against nuclear power
DING, dong the witch is dead. The wicked witch of the West, the nuclear power
industry, killed not in the end by the gleeful Green lobby who are dancing on
her grave but by the City Suits who say she is too costly to keep in the manner
to which we have become accustomed.
The death blow was delivered after a shrewd look at the books convinced them
there was no way a privatised nuclear industry lumbered with huge costs for
decommissioning, disposal of spent fuel, and a #5.5 billion bill for building
two new power plants, could make attractive returns to shareholders.
British Energy's decision to drop plans to build the two remaining nuclear
reactors on its books marks the end of Britain's 50-year experiment with
nuclear power.
That nuclear power was feared for its dangers had, in the end, little bearing
on the decision to kill it off. More fatal was that it looked uneconomic. The
announcement seems almost paradoxical: if nuclear power is uneconomic, how can
it possibly be privatised? Easy, is the answer, if the Government, in hey
presto mode, simply writes off the massive debt accumulated by the industry.
City analysts believe the sale of British Energy will raise somewhere between
#2 billion and #3 billion for its eight power stations, including two in
Scotland. Yet Sizewell B alone cost more than #2 billion to build.
But the decision to halt the planned construction of PWR power plants at
Hinkley and Sizewell will help smooth the path to privatising the holding
company, British Energy which was formed recently out of the most commercials
bits of Nuclear Electric and Scottish Nuclear. The Government is counting on
the proceeds from the privatisation in its plans to reduce public sector
borrowing in the run up to the election.
British Energy argues that there is no reason to build any new power stations.
The price of electricity in the UK has steadily declined because of the falling
price of gas and the existence of spare capacity. It claims that low natural
gas prices have changed the economics of power generation in an uncertain
energy market.
Although the UK will go on producing some nuclear energy until around the year
2035, for Richard Killick, who was Scottish Nuclear's director of safety and
quality until a few months ago, the announcement means that the industry is now
condemned to a slow, lingering death.
Scotland's two nuclear stations, at Torness and Hunterston, produce half of
Scotland's electricity needs: ``The implication is that when they come to the
end of their lives they will not be replaced by nuclear stations. The ultimate
decision point is still five years away but that they don't believe that the
nuclear industry will be viable in future is all the more threatening.''
Mr Killick grew increasingly uneasy about the safety implications of
privatisation before he left in September. He is even more worried now: ``It
seems to me an interesting implication that the people who a couple of years
ago were pressing for the privatisation of the industry as the only way to save
it are now going to kill it off.''
He fears that safety may become a lesser priority as the British Energy
directors' attention is diverted elsewhere. ``My feeling is that the industry
will be pruned as much as they think they can get away with.
``If you are seriously running down the industry, that affects morale. If
people are worried about their jobs and don't feel the top management's main
concern is the nuclear element, I fear you are on a dangerously slippery
slope.''
But if environmental groups, who welcome the last gasp of their old nuclear
energy enemy, are correct and the power industry must look to other sources,
what will they be?
Coal is out of fashion, the mining industry virtually destroyed. You would have
to be a couple of lentils short of a cutlet to believe that wind, wave and the
power of chicken shit is likely to arise to replace the bad old nuclear bag in
the immediate future.
Most money is on gas. A typical nuclear plant costs as much as 10 times to
build as a modern gas-fired plant. But with the rundown of cheap home supplies
of oil and gas, is it sensible to be contemplating a gas-only energy future?
International gas prices are low at the moment. But then so were oil prices in
the early seventies, until the oil crisis plunged the UK into an energy crisis
and a knock-on economic crisis. Quite, says Mr Killick, who continues to
believe there is a future for the UK's nuclear power plants with their
excellent safety records. Quite, says Graham Stein of Friends of the Earth, who
believes there is nothing to stop us replacing nuclear power with alternative
energy sources combined with better conservation measures. For instance?
``Wave power technology could easily be developed and the signs are
encouraging,'' says Mr Stein. But didn't the last prototype launched somewhere
in the North Sea sink just a few months ago? And isn't it the case that
windmills, or wind turbines, once universally seen as cuddly technology, are
now the source of great dissent within the Green movement?
There are about 400 turbines on 21 sites around Britain, twirling and
whooshing, feeding energy into the National Grid, and providing the grand total
of one-fifth of 1% of the country's electricity. And while a wind farm provides
one permanent job, the nuclear industry argues that the Sizewell station alone
would have created 6000 jobs on site and 8000 around the country during the
seven-year construction, while employing 450 staff once built.
The normal trade-off between employment and the environment is one thing. But
what about the concerns about the ill-effects on the environment of the sulphur
dioxide, nitrogen oxide and carbon dioxide of coal-fired stations? The gas
stations which, of course, also use fossil fuels surely add to the destruction
of the atmosphere, and the risk of global warming?
In the end then, is the death of the nuclear dream of cheap energy no more than
a short-term solution to a long-term problem?
Or, now that she's gone, will we begin to see the old witch's good points?
</TEXT>
