<HEADLINE>Untested reform of medical care</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974913699</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Greater Glasgow Health Board has announced a scheme for the provision of
out-of-hours medical care in treatment centres, which is intended largely to
replace home visits by doctors.
Not surprisingly this has been welcomed by representatives of the general
practitioners who have seen the number of house calls escalate in the past few
years, while the number of assaults on doctors performing these calls has also
increased.
This type of development is completely untested on a population the size of
Greater Glasgow, and the decision to retract services from the patient's home
to these treatment centres has not been mandated through any ballot box, so it
is legitimate for the people of Glasgow to ask why this is not initially going
to be introduced as a pilot scheme in one or two areas, and to ask when they
are going to be consulted about the changes.
This new service will be critically dependent upon an increase in the ambulance
service, which at times is unable to meet all the out-of-hours demands for
emergency transfer to hospital, and the public will need to be assured that
present services will not deteriorate further with this development.
The money for this scheme has been top-sliced, meaning that another part of the
NHS in Scotland will be cut to pay for this. It is interesting to note that
these centres will not be new-build, but will be located in existing premises,
and the two teaching hospitals which have expressed an interest are the
Victoria Infirmary and Stobhill.
The financial difficulties facing the Victoria Infirmary have received
widespread publicity. Less widely known is the dispute at the Glasgow Royal
Infirmary concerning the proposed transfer of all of the Victoria Infirmary
accident and emergency staff to the Royal Infirmary. Does the Greater Glasgow
Health Board intend to close accident and emergency services at the Victoria
and move these to the Royal Infirmary?
As always, the people of Greater Glasgow are deliberately being kept in the
dark, and until the GGHB is honest about its proposals we cannot assume, as
Danny Crawford hopes, that acute hospital closures in some form are off the
agenda.
Miles Fisher
(Consultant Physician,
Royal Alexandra Hospital,
Paisley),
53 South Mains Road,
Milngavie.
</TEXT>
