<HEADLINE>A poodle or wily old fox?</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Alf Young</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974913700</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Alf Young considers whether Scottish Enterprise in accepting a 7.5% budget cut
has capitulated or simply made the best of a bad situation - but where will the
cuts fall?
THE man accused of playing the ``political puppet'' role in Michael Forsyth's
Christmas 1995 pantomime production of How Captain Hook Raided Aladdin's Tartan
Piggy Bank was in London yesterday, earning his other living.
Scottish Enterprise chairman Professor Donald MacKay, much vilified by
Opposition MPs and sections of the media for apparently volunteering cuts of
#33m in the enterprise network's headline budget next year, was embroiled,
leading a team from his own economic consultancy Pieda, in the public inquiry
into BAA's plans for a fifth terminal at Heathrow.
MacKay's absence down south and his reluctance - beyond Monday's first formal
SE statement - to be interviewed on the 7.5% cut to #439m in the network's
allocation next year did nothing to still angry accusations that he had
connived in the Bothwell Street butchery for narrow political reasons. But is
that the whole story?
Was the MacKay-led Scottish Enterprise board an easy touch when the Scottish
Secretary came looking for real spending cuts? And, now that the enterprise
network knows the overall level of pain it has to absorb, where are the cuts
going to fall and what impact will they have on SE's ability to deliver the
``jobs and prosperity for the people of Scotland'' by which it expects to be
judged?
In the early stages of the PES round - as this annual haggle over budgets is
known to Whitehall insiders - it became clear that the Scottish Office wanted
real blood from Scottish Enterprise this year. No more standstill budgets,
eroded only by inflation. Real cuts, this time. The options finally canvassed,
say insiders, were cuts of 5%, 10% or 15% in the planned allocation.
Michael Forsyth claimed on Monday that his initial instinct was to go for a 10%
cut. Sources close to MacKay say he was prepared to go public on the damage
which would be done to the agency's ability to deliver meaningful economic
development if the cuts ran much higher than 7%. The final compromise, we now
know, was a cut of #33m or 7.5%, and an equivalent cut in Highlands &amp; Islands
Enterprise.
As part of the compromise Mackay insisted - and the Scottish Office agreed -
that, from April, there will be more flexibility for Scottish Enterprise to
move resources across the five funding blocks which make up its total budget.
These cover enterprise programmes; environment; youth training; adult training;
and management and administration.
A technical, albeit important, concession. But not one to placate those who see
the #33m cut as a mortal wound to the entire Scottish Enterprise experiment.
MacKay is, apparently, unbowed. He regarded some cuts as inevitable. His role,
he believed, was to reach a settlement which acknowledged that fact, but
inflicted minimum damage on the network's ability to do its job. ``He's played
this, not as Forsyth's poodle, but as a wily old fox,'' claims one admirer.
But precisely how does the wily old fox expect to get by on #33m less rations
next year, without doing any operational damage to the 13 cubs in the SE lair?
Scottish Enterprise already allocates more than 82% of its total budget to the
13 Lecs. So, unless the core operation in Bothwell Street withdraws from even
more national initiatives - and significant ones like Locate in Scotland and
Scottish Trade International are ring-fenced - some of the pain will have to be
spread around the network.
These detailed decisions start now. We won't know the outcome until January.
But it is possible to chart some of the options. Listening to Mr Forsyth's
simplistic formula - ``cut back on administration, raise efficiency, and
concentrate on the essentials'' - the obvious target would appear to be the
#50m or so the network still spends on management and administration each year.
But there you quickly encounter a conundrum. The emphasis in much of what
Scottish Enterprise now does is business development - working with people who
want to start new businesses, working with existing businesses to help them
grow bigger, faster. But that kind of work requires high-calibre people,
whether staff or self-employed contractors, who can give businesses the kind of
support non-executive directors are expected to deliver in larger companies.
People of that calibre don't come cheap. So, given past assaults on bureaucracy
within the system, there is even an argument that more, not less, needs to be
spent in block five, which covers the network's running costs, if the Lecs are
to maximise their impact on the business development process. That said,
consultants may find the Scottish Enterprise train has run out of gravy by next
April.
The two other obvious block targets for savings are the adult training budget
and environmental spend. When Education and Employment Secretary Gillian
Shephard acknowledged her departmental allocation immediately after the budget,
she linked the 12% fall in long-term unemployment last year to the 4% reduction
in her allocation for employment and training programmes south of the Border
next year. We can expect an equivalent cut in SE's adult training budget and
greater pressure on employers to take more responsibility for skills training.
But cutting 4%, say, from a budget which totals around #80m this year across
the network, releases little more than #3m, just 10% of the #33m cut Professor
MacKay has accepted. More targets are needed for pruning.
What about environment? That block accounted for #78m in 1994/95 and the Lecs
are still under instructions, in the Scottish Secretary's latest operational
guidelines, to bring derelict brownfield land back into productive use. Many
senior Lec executives are bracing themselves for a hard cut-back on soft,
cosmetic environmental spend.
And then there's the infrastructure side of the big flagship projects - from a
national science centre to a Loch Lomond gateway to the Stirling project. The
lesson of the latest cuts for all of them is likely to be: If you don't raise
the wherewithal from the Millennium Commission or European structural funds,
forget it.
This is, of course, a dynamic process. Chairman MacKay believes he can leverage
further the private sector spending which magnifies the impact the SE budget
alone has. And there are assets across the network, including bricks and mortar
put on the ground since the great SDA factory sale of the late eighties, whose
value might be realised to help plug the budget gap. By January, the fox's
cards will be on the table.
It became clear that the Scottish Office wanted real blood from Scottish
Enterprise this year. No more standstill budgets, eroded only by inflation.
Real cuts, this time
</TEXT>
