<HEADLINE>Best laid schemes of mice and festival directors</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>David Steele</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974913701</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
David Steele examines the efforts to put the Burns International
Festival back
on song
IT seemed like a good idea at the time. Take the fact that Scotland's bard died
200 years before, and use his name and influence to promote varied events aimed
at entertaining the locals and bringing in lots of visitors.
In the words of the mission statement of Burns International Festival 96: ``To
use the bicentenary of the death of Robert Burns as a catalyst to generate
additional economic activity in the south-west of Scotland by organising
events, helping market the area and promoting Burns.''
Fine so far, but then things started to go wrong and the rumblings began up and
down the country as one setback after another plagued the organisation of the
festival.
It is in this organisation, perhaps, where the key can be found as to why the
Burns International Festival has been described variously as a ``fiasco'', a
``shambles'', and a ``wasted opportunity''.
An 18-strong board of directors drawn from all the funding bodies, such as
local authorities and local enterprise companies, was left with the task of
drawing together a wide and varied festival. Many may see this as unwieldy and
a dangerous mixture of enthusiasm and ignorance.
They were to be guided in this by John Struthers, the former theatre and
festival director in various parts of England, who was brought in as director.
The vision he had then is still there despite the knocks, according to
Struthers.
He said: ``I had, and still have, a vision of a festival which brings together
community-based events and international attractions. This is a remarkable
opportunity to commemorate one of the greatest writers and poets and is an
opportunity which must not be missed.''
Mr Struthers will have to go cap in hand to a variety of places in the coming
weeks and there is no guarantee of the extra cash which will release the purse
strings of the EU to let much-needed support cross the Channel.
Unlike some of his board members he is slow to blame the media and is often
refreshingly honest in his comments. ``Yes, many mistakes have been made by me
and by others in the organisation but now we must put these behind us and move
forward to make sure the festival is a success.
``The media have occasionally been critical but too often we were not able to
tell them a full enough story of what was going on.''
The early events are a curious mixture of visual arts, fireworks, ploughing,
reading, reciting, and singing. Perhaps Burns would have approved, but the jury
is still out on that one.
What is for sure is that for the bicentenary to fail in its goal to promote
tourism and bring Burns to an even wider audience would be a crime.
Now Mr Struthers has been told by some of the board that they want more big
names and he must look again at the later programme. It is a tricky one.
He added: ``There is a school of thought that we should be out looking for big
names but the funding is not there. Now I am asking the existing funders,
coupled with a few new ones, to take a leap of faith and make more money
available which will be matched from Europe.
``I know everyone is strapped for cash but it is very important for us to get
the funding right. I will be looking at a wide range of possibilities and I am
still hopeful that commercial sponsorship will be in place in the coming weeks
in time for the later events.''
He is naturally reticent about naming names - a habit which has got him into
trouble in the past - but Mr Struthers has made it clear that major companies
are nibbling but they have yet to bite.
The biting will probably come when he has something more substantial for them
to chew on. In the meantime, the songs and verse will ring out all over the
world much as it does every January.
Whether 1996 is really all that different remains to be seen. As the bard wrote:
The best laid schemes o' mice an' men gang aft a-gley.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951213-000164</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000164</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Awards need a fun category</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BRIAN MEEK</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>28</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>SPORT</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974913702</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
JONATHAN Edwards - lovely fellow, god-fearing, kind to animals - was named as
the BBC Sports Personality of the Year the other night, voted for by you the
viewers. It is not his fault that his specialist event, the triple jump, is
just about as exciting as synchronised draughts.
Frankly, I have great difficulty in believing that thousands of people wrote in
to say that Jonathan gave them the biggest sporting thrill of 1995. Or that
Frank Bruno came second in anything other than a two-horse race. But I am
probably just being cynical again.
Seriously though, is the BBC show, and its Scottish counterpart, not just a wee
bit stereotyped in its approach? Is it not time to organise a new kind of
sporting award and give the public a real role to play?
Just for the record, my 1, 2, 3 in the BBC list would have been Bernard
Gallacher, because he inspired a Ryder Cup victory that produced the most
thrilling climax of the year; Mike Atherton, for restoring some of England's
cricket pride almost single-handedly; and Stephen Hendry as he is, and has been
for some time, unarguably the best in the world at what he does.
I would create new categories, too. Manager of the year, open to all sports,
featuring Kevin Keegan, Craig Brown, Ian Doyle, Allan McGraw - and Terry
Venables for seeing off a record number of inquiries into his business affairs.
Spoilt brat of the year would be an interesting competition. I would let the
fans pick this one, perhaps by telephone poll.
One would expect Linford Christie to sprint to victory in this category but
let's not dismiss lightly the claims of Eric Cantona, Nick Faldo, Damon Hill,
or Brian Moore, who would be likely to achieve a landslide in the Scottish vote.
The ``you must be kidding, ref'' award could be voted on by referees and
umpires of every sport and go to the player or official who has irritated them
most in the past 12 months. Willie Miller would be the presenter.
Gazza might be the winner for several years, though our own Peter Wright should
pick up the Hawick vote. Video evidence of Jim Farry in action has been
disallowed.
Worst shot of the year would be an interesting diversion. This year's might
include Costantino Rocca's collapsing chip into the Valley of Sin at the Open,
Hearts keeper Henry Smith's missed penalty, and the one fired by the Brazilian
clay-pigeon expert which blew off his little finger.
Unluckiest sports personality of the year is likely to be a close-run thing.
Curtis Strange is a strong candidate, having been unfortunate enough to be
specially selected for the US Ryder Cup team, as is Peter McNeeley, who went 89
seconds with Mike Tyson, and any footballer who bumps into the procurator
fiscal of Glasgow.
For the most boring game of the year I would nominate the recent Boland-England
cricket match, which was cut from four days to one because it was so
uninspiring. No, any cricket match does not qualify.
Worst quote of the year could bring nominations from sports writers from up and
down the land. My own contribution would be from Mr Will Carling, who, when
asked for his highlights of England's Grand Slam win over Scotland, replied:
``Nothing particular,'' and then wrote an article detailing them for a Sunday
newpaper.
Worst sports columnist of the year? No, we are not having any of that nonsense.
I would mention the TV commentator who managed to miss a goal, except that I
sent the wrong score from a rugby match recently, and I do hate cast-ups.
q FOLLOWING last week's column, Jim Telfer, director of everything at the SRU,
rang to tell me he never said that Scottish rugby did not need heroes, though
he fully accepts that he was quoted on those terms in several newspapers.
Always happy to put the record straight.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
