<DOCNO>GH951213-000165</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951213-000165</DOCID>
<DATE>951213</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Hurdler's sentence reduced</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>28</PAGE>
<FLAG>SPORT DIGEST</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974913703</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ATHLETICS
BEWARE the wrath of a husband scorned. Lyudmila Narozhilenko, the world indoor
sprint hurdles record-holder, has been reinstated after serving 34 months of a
four-year suspension for a steroid doping offence, writes Doug Gillon.
The International Amateur Athletic Federation cited ``exceptional
circumstances'' yesterday in announcing the Russian's return.
Narozhilenko protested her innocence, denying all knowledge of the drugs which
were conclusively present in her urine sample, and threatening legal action.
Her husband eventually confessed he had spiked her food following the breakdown
of their marriage.
This admission has been known to the IAAF for at least two years, butthe
hurdler has still served the bulk of her sentence, missing two world outdoor
and one European championship.
Also reinstated under the same rule at the Monaco council meeting was German
endurance runner Iris Biba, whose coach admitted he had given her steroids.
BELFAST has been awarded the 1999 World cross-country championships. The 1997
Grand Prix final will be in Fukuoka, Japan, while Slovakia, marking 100 years
of athletics activity, will host the World Half Marathon Championships (in
Kosice), and the World Race Walking Cup (in Podebrady).
ALL athletes are invited to an open meeting tomorrow (7.30) in Meadowbank
Stadium Lounge. Edinburgh's new development officer, Norrie Williamson, wants
competitors of both sexes and all abilities, from track and field,
cross-country, and road and hill-running, to air their views.
American football
THE Scottish Claymores have cut their ticket prices in half for next season's
World League matches at Murrayfield. The price of adult tickets is halved from
#20 to #10, with children under 14 paying #2 instead of #5.
The Claymores' season kicks off on April 14, when they take on London Monarchs
at White Hart Lane, with the first home match on April 21 against Barcelona
Dragons.
Fans will pay #18 for reserved seats and #10 for general admission. Season
tickets will start at #40 for adults and #8 for children for unreserved seats.
The Claymores will warm up with matches against London and Barcelona at
Scotstoun showgrounds in February, and not at Stepps as was previously reported.
National Football League: Miami 13, Kansas City 6.
Curling
Summit Centre. Brunton Miller Trophy - John Steel 12, Jean Shanks 4.
McKenzie Crook - H Aitken 6, B Martin 5; J Gowan 6, J Semple 6; J Lyon 8, J
Scott Findlay 5; R Dunachie 10, Crosthwaite 5.
Wrestling
ROBERT Clark of Yoker won the award for the Outstanding Performer of the Year
last night at the annual presentation of prizes to the winners of the Scottish
Wrestling Bond Highland Games League.
League winners - Class A: 1, R Clark (Yoker) 50 points; 2, H Taylor (Yoker) 17;
3, D Campbell (Dunfermline) 16. Class B: 1, R McNamara (East Kilbride) 46; 2, D
McGinn (Woodside) 21; 3, H Ferns (Greenock) 11.
Swimming
ALISON Sheppard has returned from six weeks' training in Calgary with a medal
from the Canadian championships, and confident that she can achieve her
ambition of a third Olympic appearance at Atlanta next summer.
The 23-year-old from Milngavie and Bearsden claimed a silver medal with 25.8se
in the 50 metres free-style when she finished runner-up to US record-holder Amy
van Dyken, the fastest in the world this year. She also finished fourth in the
100m free-style in 56.6.
This weekend she has entered six events at the Scottish Winter championships in
Ayr, but will be back on a plane at the end of this month when she joins her
club for a training trip in Arizona.
Rugby league
THE Scottish Border Reivers' plans to play in the new European Super League hae
been shelved - but only temporarily. Their application will be discussed by the
RFL again next year, when the club will be in a much stronger position to
negotiate their way into the big time.
