<HEADLINE>Take the draw in future, is Leslie's message Beveridge anguish as his late gamble fails</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DEREK DOUGLAS CHIEF RUGBY WRITER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>28</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974913704</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
With a little help from their friends: Scott Murray is aided by fellow Scot
Barry Stewart as he outjumps Rob Fiddler, who also receives some support from a
colleague during last night's Under-21 international at Gateshead.
UNDER-21 INTERNATIONAL
England 21, Scotland 18
THE first international against the Auld Enemy at this level ended in a
three-point defeat and for Scotland scrum-half Graeme Beveridge it ended in
tears.
Scotland had clawed back from an 18-7 deficit at half-time. The Scots were all
square after an hour and it was not until five minutes from the end that a drop
goal put the English in front.
Three minutes into injury-time the Scots were awarded a penalty just outside
the English 22. A penalty goal would have secured an honourable draw but young
Beveridge chose to go for broke. He tapped the ball and ran, the move fizzled
out, and the referee blew for no-side. Beveridge was devastated.
The young Boroughmuir scrum-half, one of the finds of the season, had not found
the going as easy as he has on the club scene. None the less, he had laid on a
couple of Scottish tries and he did not deserve this.
Coach David Leslie said later: ``What we are trying to teach these lads is that
you have to win at international level, and if you can't win and the draw is
there for the taking, then take it. It was a tough call but Graeme knows it.
``What we're looking for, and what we're demanding are the right instincts at
the right time. Unfortunately, that last one wasn't quite right.''
The former Scotland flanker added: ``We are trying to teach these boys good
habits. First to win games, and secondly not to lose them.''
Scotland began poorly and had conceded 10 points within the first
quarter-of-an-hour.
Assistant coach John Rutherford had hoped that the Scots would have put the
English under pressure in the opening minutes but after six minutes England
opened the scoring with a soft try, scrum half Scott Benton nipping in
unopposed down the blind-side from a ruck inside the Scottish 22. Simon Binns
converted.
A Mike Duncan penalty attempt had struck the upright but stayed out before
Binns capitalised on extreme English pressure to spear home a penalty goal.
The big English forwards were proving a handful in the close-quarter stuff and
it would be into the third quarter before Scotland were to get their measure.
Nevertheless, after 22 minutes, and following some vigorous rucking by
Scotland, Graham Dall snaffled a ball at the lineout tail from an English throw
and from the ruck Gordon Bulloch charged through for a try which Duncan
converted.
A Binns penalty put England further ahead and a Chris Catling try gave the
English their 18-7 half-time lead.
Although Scotland had been under severe pressure for much of the first half
there were a number of plus points. In particular, the lineout worked well with
Guy Perrett and, specifically, Scott Murray taking some choice ball on the
touchlines.
Dall, cultured player that he is, linked well and was invariably first in the
break-down queue. Leslie, though, confided later that good player though the
young medical student is, he would like him to be much more of a predator.
The 1984 Grand Slam flanker merely gave one of those old-fashioned looks when
he was asked if this meant he would wish young Dall to flirt a wee bit more
with the offside line.
Scotland began the second half with a vengeance, giving credence to Leslie's
observation that a five-hour bus journey - and a host of players with
university exams coming up - is, perhaps, not the best preparation for
international rugby.
Mike Duncan kick-started the comeback with a penalty goal and followed this up
with a drop-goal after 54 minutes.
The equaliser came in 59 minutes, a surprise tap penalty by Beveridge inside
the English 22 setting Dall off, and David McLeish - who was later to suffer a
broken collar-bone - storming over for the try. It was all even, and the game
was definitely there for the taking. The Scots now rued the missed chances in
the first half when they had come away from the England 22 without scoring.
Scotland tackled well in the final 10 minutes as England mounted a last-ditch
effort. The fear for the Scots was that the line would not hold, and Binn's
drop-goal five minutes from the end proved to be the decisive score.
