<TEXT>
CRICKET
aJOHN Emburey was trying not to be too critical of his England A team last
night after the third Test was nearly thrown away in Peshawar.
A determined, unbroken ninth-wicket stand between Jason Pooley and Dean
Headley, who put on 49 in 52 minutes, eventually salvaged a draw and confirmed
England A's 1-0 series victory.
But there was an air of embarrassment in the English camp after a startling and
nervy afternoon collapse from 80 for two to 142 for eight which had left them
staring in to the eyes of defeat.
At tea England A were just 48 runs in front, but Middlesex left-hander Pooley
took charge with a show of confidence that will be of much interest to the
England selectors.
Emburey said: ``I don't want to sound over-critical because we've got the draw,
which is the most important thing. We've also won the series, which is what we
set out to do.
``But we didn't apply ourselves to the situation today and we will have to have
a chat about that once we sit down during the next couple of days to discuss
the limited-overs series which now ends this tour.''
Meanwhile, Mark Ilott's chances of playing in the third Test in South Africa
could depend on how quickly he recovers from a mild bout of food poisoning.
The Essex left-arm paceman missed yesterday's practice session after
complaining of an upset stomach following Monday night's visit to a Japanese
restaurant.
England expect Ilott to be back on parade today - and fighting for a place
against South Africa 24 hours later.
With Darren Gough ruled out by a hamstring injury, Ilott, Lancashire paceman
Peter Martin, and Worcestershire spinner Richard Illingworth appear to be
chasing one spot.
q.INDIA'S women are poised to win the third and final Test against England -
and square the series - in Hyderabad today.
England, who drew the first Test and won the second by two runs, go into the
last day requiring a further 264 runs for an improbable victory with nine
second innings wickets standing.
After Karen Smithies' side had slumped to 98 all out a disastrous second day,
India yesterday declared their second innings on 216 for seven, Chandra Kanta
Ahir top-scoring with 67 to help set England a victory target of 302.
Bradford's Helen Plimmer was then out for a duck before Jan Brittin (27 not
out) and Barbara Daniels (10 not out) guided the tourists to 38 for one by the
close.
q.SCOTTISH cricket legend George Goddard has been appointed to the
international selection committee.
Goddard, who earned 78 caps in a glittering national career spanning 23 years,
is the first recruit of new selection chief Bobby Hill, who said: ``I'm
delighted George has agreed to take on this role. He will command the respect
of all the players and should prove a tremendous asset for Scottish cricket.''
Spin-king Goddard took 154 international wickets and almost 1400 for Heriot's
before retiring last year, aged 57.
</TEXT>
