<TEXT>
CURLING
SCOTLAND'S men and women assured themselves of quarter-final places with wins
over Germany in yesterday's play at the European Championships in Grindelwald,
Switzerland.
Yesterday morning, Hammy McMillan's men bounced back from their Monday night
loss to Norway, beating Andy Kapp's German team by 5-3, and they were followed
on to the rink by Kirsty Hay's women, who dominated their game over Germany's
former world champion Andrea Schopp, to win by 10-6 and retain their unbeaten
record.
In the men's game, Scotland won the toss but McMillan was too heavy with his
last stone draw to give first blood to Germany. The Scots brought the scores
back level at the second with a well-swept draw. In the fifth end, Kapp wrecked
on a guard with his last stone and Scotland stole a single to take the lead.
Germany drew level at the sixth, but Scotland moved clear at the seventh, when
the German sweepers touched one of the lying stones as they followed their own
last stone into the house. McMillan took this chance to draw for two.
Germany had a good chance to level again at the eighth but were too heavy and
could only score one. The Scots restored their two-shot advantage with a single
at the ninth and went on to win when Germany ran out of stones in the tenth end.
In the women's game, the teams swopped singles at the first two ends and, at
the third, Hay took advantage of her first real opportunity and drew her last
stone well to score two for a 3-1 lead.
Schopp responded straight away, scoring two in the next end to level the scores
again, but a confident hit on the nose by Hay in the sixth gave Scotland a
three from that end and a 6-3 lead.
Germany could only manage a single at the sixth and the Scots restored their
three-shot lead with a single at the seventh. A Hay take-out in the eighth end
did not completely clear the house and this gave Germany a chance for a two,
but the Scots made no mistake in the ninth end, scoring three again to move
further away and the Germans conceded the game halfway through the tenth end.
Both Scottish teams now have their final round-robin games today.
