<HEADLINE>North and Midlands anger as their game goes ahead</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ALAN LORIMER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>28</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913708</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A DATE was announced yesterday for South's postponed inter-district
championship match with the Exiles. They will meet at Richmond on Wednesday,
January 10, the kick-off time of 5pm representing a further nightmare for the
oft-vilified marketing men.
This decision follows the bizarre on/off saga of the Exiles' match against
North and Midlands next Sunday in Aberdeen. Last weekend, the N and M officials
and coaches, and several influential voices in the SRU, were all assuming that
their game would be postponed because of the loss of so many players to the
Stirling County v Heriot's FP Tennent's championship decider on Saturday. ``The
decision forcing us to go ahead with the game came as a shock to us,'' said Ian
Rankine, the N and M coach. ``On Sunday night a number of people in the SRU had
said there would be no point in playing the game,'' stated Rankine, who feels
disappointed that South should have been allowed to postpone their match with
the Exiles for the same reason.
Last night Midlands' secretary John Methven expressed more than disappointment.
He declared: ``SRU secretary Bill Hogg told us that the decision had been taken
by the general committee. He said he had phoned them and they have voted in
favour of the game going ahead.
``There is real fury in the North and Midlands and, I can tell you, that
resignations are being threatened.''
North coach Rankine said there is a possibility that the Stirling half-backs,
Ken Harper and Mark McKenzie, could be considered. ``But it would be too much
to ask any of the front five to play twice in 24 hours,'' said Rankine.
If,however, the Stirling halves were ruled out, there would be problems. One
avenue worth exploring for N and M would be offering the scrum-half berth to
Gary Armstrong, who, having spent some time at Dunfermline High School, has
district connections.
North, who had high hopes of lifting the championship, may have the bonus of a
return to duty by Martin Waite, with an outside chance that Scotland captain
Rob Wainwright will be fit by the weekend. The squad will have a practice
session tonight, but it may bear little resemblance to the team that takes the
field on Sunday.
</TEXT>
