<HEADLINE>Oxford incensed by penalty try</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>28</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913710</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Oxford University 19,
Cambridge University 21
OXORD coach Lyn Evans slammed referee Tony Spreadbury after his award of a late
penalty try helped Cambridge clinch victory in an entertaining Varsity Match at
Twickenham yesterday.
But the official stood by his ruling that Oxford, desperately defending a 16-9
lead, were deliberately offside and preventing a try with three minutes to play.
Evans blasted: ``I did not think there was a probability of Cambridge scoring,
which is the definition required by the laws, and in any case, the ball was
dropped in the move.
``It was not the best decision he made during the match and it was not the sort
of decision to make in this situation.''
Spreadbury hit back: ``There was a tryscoring opportunity. I felt there were
players available for a try and it was deliberate offside.'' Inspired by the
penalty try, Cambridge snatched victory when hooker Jonathan Evans grabbed an
injury-time try and so rendered a record-breaking performance by Oxford
stand-off David Humphreys in vain.
Humphreys had collected 19 points to set a new Oxford record and equal Alistair
Hignell's Varsity Match mark.
The Oxford stand-off stroked over a drop-kick, three penalties and the
conversion of his own try to provide full value for the record 71,000 Varsity
Match crowd, who paid a record #1m to witness the first game under Twickenham's
floodlights.
</TEXT>
