<HEADLINE>`Super' win for Nicol</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ELSPETH BURNSIDE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913712</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SQUASH
PETER Nicol's career reached another peak yesterday, when he beat England's
Chris Walker in the final of the Mahindra International Challenge in Bombay and
became the first Scot to win a Super Series title.
The 22-year-old from Inverurie, who has had a disappointing start to the
season, comfortably beat Walker 15-8, 15-11, 15-10 to land his biggest cheque
of #12,000.
Following a tonsils operation in June, and a disastrous run of results, Nicol
dropped to No.8 in the world rankings, his lowest placing for 18 months. But
now he can look forward to making headway back towards his best placing of No.4
when the next list is announced on January 1.
``I'm absolutely delighted,'' said Nicol. ``Hopefully, this will be the first
of many. I had a really tough first-round match and just scraped home 3-2
against Egypt's Ahmed Barada. But I didn't drop another game, and really feel
I'm now reaching my best ever form.
``Because Jansher Kahn (world champion) was missing, I knew the chance was
there to win this title. But you've still got to go out and do it.''
Disappointingly, Nicol is not defending at the Scottish championships in
Edinburgh this weekend. After the arduous run of four Super Series events in
five weeks, he had already decided to take a long rest on his return from
Bombay.
His absence means that Martin Heath, who also proved his form in India with a
narrow 3-2 defeat from world No.2 Rodney Eyles, is favourite to win the
Scottish title for a first time.
In the women's championship, last year's winner, Claire Waddell, and world
No.21 Senga Macfie are joint favourites.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
