<HEADLINE>Clubs set their sights on Europe</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Alan Lorimer</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>28</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974913713</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
The Scottish Rugby Union's proposal that districts should represent Scotland in
Europe seems likely to come under fire.  At a meeting of the Premier League
Clubs' Association in Glasgow last night, it is understood that a majority of
representatives backed the idea of clubs carrying the flag for Scotland.
"The clubs will try to formulate a proposal which would allow a premier league
of eight to play their season through and at the same time accomodate three of
their member clubs participating in a European league," said the association's
David Kilshaw.
The meeting appears to have come out in favour of retaining some kind of
representative rugby being played in December and January as a stepping stome
to the international season.
"We do not think that European rugby played in October and November fits
comfortably as a precursor to international and even more so when the Five
Nations' championship moves back a fortnight," said Kilshaw, who feels that a
higher level of rugby in tghe two midwinter months might go some way to
answering the pleas of the Exiles for future involvement.
The next move for the association, in what is becoming a fascinating battle of
ideas, will be to design a working model  of next season and then to try to
lobby clubs outwith their association.
They are due to meet next in January, but by then it is expected that a
proposal to be put before the SRU will have been formulated.  Further momentum
is likely to be generated tonight at a meeting of the top 10 clubs.
</TEXT>
