<HEADLINE>Ballet   Peter Pan, Theatre Royal, Glasgow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Mary Brennan</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974913817</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I DON'T suppose when Scottish Ballet commissioned Peter Pan in 1989 that they
imagined something so unsecured - first full-length ballet for choreographer
Graham Lustig, first ballet score for composer Edward McGuire, first ballet for
designer Margaret Woznica - would end up being pressed into such regular
company service. At the time of its commissioning, the rising mood within the
company management was ``to try will be an awfully big adventure''. Now, as I
watch the dancers being hoist aloft, courtesy of Foy's clever wires, I have to
admit to a total plummeting of spirits. Because this was never a really
together ballet, ever.
Its magic was elusive and its sense of adventure chased itself in circles round
Neverland for the whole of Act Two. Tweeking took place. And yes, it has been
tweeked again. Even more of the over-literate stuff being stripped out. But
none of this can alter the bedrock fact that whatever's left is still always
going to lack the all-important tingle factor. What the company needs, for all
our sakes, is a shiny new Christmas ballet.
Not just to please the audiences, but because the dancers need, deserve,
something they can get their feet into. Watching them last night, I wished I
was the Lottery Fairy . . . It's nice that Maria Teresa Del Real has stayed on
a bit longer - that impudent hussy, Tinkerbell, is right up her street.
Vladislav Bubnov's Peter, kicks up his heels like an eternal truant while
Elspeth Shaw's Wendy does her best to chivvy him into early domesticity, and
Catherine Evers gives Mrs Darling's solos the emotional quality the
choreography omits.
I would love to say that they got the thing airborne, but what I can say is,
it's not their fault that it lies on stage twitching with less finesse than the
crocodile. I feel for them.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
