<HEADLINE>Play your cards right</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>John Davidson</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974913819</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Winners in fashion must know what suits to play for. John Davidson comes up
trumps with a selection of top designs for the leader of the pack
LET'S play poker. Fashion poker. It's a game of skill, not chance, where
accomplished players make the best of whatever attributes cruel fate (and
sponge cake) has dealt them.
A strictly tailored suit is the disciplined fashion option. In the business
world, it is the sartorial synonym for serious; style shorthand for ``No
messing''. A suit carries the implicit suggestion of formality - demanding
attention, commanding respect.
Fashion's trump card is the suit which creates an aura of sophistication the
very instant a woman slips it on.
She is immediately transported from the struggle of her workaday existence to
the threshold of glamour. Which is exactly where young British design duo,
Pearce Fionda, are taking their followers.
Who plays fashion's knave? There are so many potential candidates - designers
whose creations are cruel and unflattering to the women who fall beneath their
spell.
Or there is Thierry Mugler, whose razor-sharp cut produces the sexiest
silhouette conceivable in gaberdine tailoring.
His suits are serious business, cut to define an hourglass figure, yet their
structure is clever enough to coax the illusion of perfect proportions from a
figure which may not be curvy in quite the right places.
There is a joker in every pack. And in the fashion pack, it was a role
gloriously fulfilled by the late Franco Moschino.
His quirky humour coupled to extraordinary elegance lives on in the
idiosyncratically titled Cheap &amp; Chic collection. Cardsharps should love this
winter's skirt formed from two trompe l'oeil playing cards.
Jackets emblazoned with the legend ``Let's twist again'' are a must-have for
pontoon players. And the little black suit trimmed with dainty bows and ruffled
tulle is fit for any Queen of Hearts.
</TEXT>
